{"title_page": "Agriculture in Brazil", "text_new": "{{Short description|Major economic sector in Brazil}}\n{{Update|date = November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox\n| abovestyle  = background:lightblue\n| headerstyle = background:lightblue\n| above       = Agriculture in [[Brazil]]\n| image1      = [[File:Brasil celeiro.png|300px]]\n| caption1    = Brazil, \"breadbasket of the world\"<ref>Expression coined during the [[Vargas Era]]</ref>\n| image2      = {{flagicon|Brazil|size=100px}}\n| label1      = Area cultivated\n| data1       = 65,338,804 ha.<ref name=\"ibge08\">Thais Leit\u00e3o (ABr) (17 October 2009). [http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/212125.htm \"Produ\u00e7\u00e3o agr\u00edcola brasileira registrar recorded em 2008 com alta de 9,1%.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725071250/http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/212125.htm |date=25 July 2014 }} \u2013 in Portuguese. Paged visited on 30 March 2014.</ref>\n| label2      = Cropland (% of land area)\n| data2       = 31%\n| label3      = Rural population\n| data3       = 5,965,000 families\n| label4      = Main products\n| data4       = sugarcane, coffee, soybeans, corn.\n| header5     = Production\n| label6      = Grains (2008)\n| data6       = 145.4 million tons<ref name=ibge08/>\n| header7     = Major products\n| label8      = Cane and derivatives (2007/08)\n| data8       = 493.4 million tons\n| label9      = Soy (2008)\n| data9       = 59.2 million tons<ref name=ibge08/>\n| label10     = Corn (2008)\n| data10      = 58.9 million tons<ref name=ibge08/>\n| header11    = Participation in the [[Economy of Brazil|economy]] \u2013 2008\n| label12     = Crop value\n| data12      = R$148.4 billion ($65.56 bil. USD)<ref name=ibge08/>\n| label13     = Contribution to GDP\n| data13      = 4.53%<ref name=cepea>CEPEA/USP/CNA Data [http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/pib/ download] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401225352/http://cepea.esalq.usp.br/pib/ |date=1 April 2014 }}, \u2013 in Portuguese. Searched 18 October 2009.</ref>\n| label14     = Agribusiness GDP (Rural industry and trade, livestock and agriculture)\n| data14      = 26.46%<ref name=cepea/>\n}}\nThe '''agriculture of Brazil''' is historically one of the principal bases of [[Economy of Brazil|Brazil's economy]].  While its initial focus was on [[sugarcane]], Brazil eventually became the world's largest exporter of coffee, [[soybeans]], beef, and crop-based [[ethanol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/148928/page/2|title=Brazil Surges Ahead with Commodities Wealth - Newsweek International Edition - Newsweek.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|author=|date=|website=newsweek.com|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807041819/http://www.newsweek.com/id/148928/page/2|archivedate=7 August 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBrazil exported 41,000 tons of processed cashew nuts valued at US$193,900 in 2018.<ref>thebrazilbusiness.com/article/fruit-market-in-brazil</ref>\n\nThe success of agriculture during the [[Vargas Era|Estado Novo]] (New State), with [[Get\u00falio Vargas]], led to the expression, \"Brazil, breadbasket of the world\".<ref name=cc>{{cite magazine | authorlink = Felipe Seibel | title = O novo salto do agroneg\u00f3cio | magazine = [[Exame (magazine)|Exame]] | date = 14 June 2007 | language = Portuguese | url = http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0895/m0131023.html | accessdate = 5 March 2009 |url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080526161346/http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0895/m0131023.html | archivedate = 26 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2009, Brazil had about {{convert|106000000|ha}} of undeveloped fertile land \u2013 a territory larger than the combined area of France and Spain.<ref name=\"veja04\">{{cite magazine | authorlink = Alexandre Secco | title = O tamanho do Brasil que p\u00f5e a mesa | magazine = [[Veja (magazine)|Veja]] | issue = 1843 | page = 78 | publisher = Abril | date = 3 March 2004 | language = Portuguese | url = http://veja.abril.com.br/030304/p_078.html | accessdate = 18 October 2009 |url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090331042823/http://veja.abril.com.br/030304/p_078.html | archivedate = 31 March 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2008 [[IBGE]] study, despite the [[Great Recession|world financial crisis]], Brazil had record agricultural production, with growth of 9.1%, principally motivated by favorable weather.  The production of grains in the year reached an unprecedented 145,400,000 tons.<ref name=\"ibge08\" /> That record output employed an additional 4.8% in planted area, totalling 65,338,000 hectares and producing $148 billion Reals.  The principal products were corn (13.1% growth) and soy (2.4% growth).<ref name=ibge08/>\n\nThe southern one-half to two-thirds of Brazil has a semi-temperate climate, higher rainfall, more fertile soil, more advanced technology and input use, adequate infrastructure and more experienced farmers.  This region produces most of Brazil's grains, [[oilseeds]] (and exports).\n\nThe drought-ridden northeast region and Amazon basin lack well-distributed rainfall, good soil, adequate infrastructure and development capital. Although mostly occupied by subsistence farmers, both regions are increasingly important as exporters of forest products, cocoa and tropical fruits. Central Brazil contains substantial areas of [[grassland]].  Brazilian grasslands are far less fertile than those of North America, and are generally suited only for grazing.\n\nAgriculture in Brazil presents challenges, including the ongoing practice of [[slave labour]],<ref>[http://www.oit.org.br/trabalho_forcado/ ''Combating Forced Labour'', ILO Programme (United Nations)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706161239/http://www.oit.org.br/trabalho_forcado/ |date=6 July 2011 }} \u2013 in Portuguese</ref><ref>Le Breton, B. (2003). ''Trapped: modern-day slavery in the Brazilian Amazon''. Kumarian Press. {{ISBN|1-56549-155-6}}</ref> [[Land reform|agrarian reform]], fire, production financing, and a rural exodus fueled by economic stress on family farming.\n\nHalf of Brazil is covered by forests.  The world's largest [[rain forest]] is in the Amazon Basin.  Migrations into the Amazon and large-scale forest burning have challenged the government's management capabilities.  The [[Lula da Silva|Lula]] administration reduced incentives for such activity and implemented a broader environmental plan.<code><nowiki>{{Citation needed|reason=</nowiki>''Needs reliable source on how the supposed implementation happened.''<nowiki>|date=September 2019}}</nowiki></code>It also adopted an Environmental Crimes Law that established serious penalties for infractions.\n\nSince 1985, 1772 activists for agrarian reform were murdered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bastamag.net/Le-Bresil-risque-de-subir-l-une-des-plus-grandes-regressions-ecologiques-et|title=Le Br\u00e9sil risque de subir l'une des plus grandes r\u00e9gressions \u00e9cologiques et sociales de son histoire|first=Laurent|last=Delcourt|date=|website=Basta !|url-status = live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170731215540/https://www.bastamag.net/Le-Bresil-risque-de-subir-l-une-des-plus-grandes-regressions-ecologiques-et|archivedate=31 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBrazil is now working towards more development in 2019.\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Brazil}}{{quotation|However, the air of the country is very healthful, fresh, and as temperate as that of Entre Douro e Minho, we have found the two climates alike at this season. There is great plenty, an infinitude of waters. The country is so well-favoured that if it were rightly cultivated it would yield everything, because of its waters.<ref>{{cite book| authorlink =Henrique Campos Sim\u00f5es| title =The Letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha| publisher =Temple University| page =10| url =http://isc.temple.edu/evanson/LASC050/Readings/PeroVaz.pdf|url-status = dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120528200117/http://isc.temple.edu/evanson/LASC050/Readings/PeroVaz.pdf| archivedate =28 May 2012| df =dmy-all| access-date =2 April 2014}}</ref>|2=[[Pero Vaz de Caminha]]|3=[[Carta de P\u00earo Vaz de Caminha]]|4=[[s:Carta a El Rei D. Manuel (ortografia atualizada)|Full text on Wikisource \u2013 in Portuguese]] }}\n\n=== Early farming ===\n\n[[File:Brazilian Fruits.jpg|thumb|Brazilian fruits in a painting by [[Albert Eckhout]].]]\nBrazilians (\"Indians\") began farming some 12,000 years ago. They farmed [[cassava]], peanuts, tobacco, [[sweet potato]]es and maize, in addition to extracting the essence from other local plants such as the [[Caryocar brasiliense|pequi]] and the [[Attalea speciosa|babassu]]. Production was for food, [[straw]] or [[madeira]].  They cultivated local fruits such as [[jabuticaba]], [[cashew]]s, [[Spondias mombin]] and [[Goiaba]]s.\n\nThe Indians both influenced and were influenced by the Europeans who arrived in the fifteenth century. The Portuguese \"nourished themselves with wood-flour, slaughtered the big game to eat, packed their nets and imitated the rough, free life\" in the words of Pedro Calmon.<ref>CALMON, Pedro: ''Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil'', S\u00e3o Paulo, 1939, vol. 1</ref>\n\nUntil other crops began to be exported, [[brazilwood]] was the main reason Portugal wanted control in Brazil.<ref>{{cite book | last = ARRUDA | first = Jos\u00e9 Jobson  | title = Hist\u00f3ria Integrada: da Idade M\u00e9dia ao nascimento do mundo moderno  | edition = 2\u00aa | year = 1996 | publisher = [[editora \u00c1tica|\u00c1tica]] | place = S\u00e3o Paulo | isbn = 85-08-05399-1 | pages = 126, 129  | chapter = Cap. 21 \u2013 ''Os primeiros tempos: a explora\u00e7\u00e3o do pau-brasil'' | quote = Foi com o objetivo de explorar o com\u00e9rcio dessa madeira que os portugueses fundaram uma s\u00e9rie de benfeitorias(...) Os europeus dependiam dos \u00edndios para a extra\u00e7\u00e3o das madeiras(...) A partir de 1530 a crise do com\u00e9rcio de especiarias... for\u00e7aram Portugal a ocupar definitivamente(...)}}</ref>\n\n==== Fires ====\n[[File:Queimada ABr 02.jpg|thumb|Fires are one of the problems still present in Brazilian agriculture.]]\nOne practice of indigenous Brazilians was to clear land for cultivation by burning it. This provided arable land and ashes for use as fertilizer and soil cover.\n\nScholars such as [[Monteiro Lobato]] considered this practice to be harmful. However, burning only became a problem when the Europeans adopted the practice aggressively around 1500, divided land into farms, began monocropping, etc. The combination of burning with these new farming methods decimated native flora.<ref name=aa>{{cite journal |title=O uso do fogo: o manejo ind\u00edgena e a piromania da monocultura |volume=14 |issue=40 |pages=231\u2013250 |language=pt |author=Leonel, Mauro |journal=Estudos Avan\u00e7ados |date=Sep\u2013Dec 2000 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1590/S0103-40142000000300019 |doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nIndian land management included garden areas in locations selected to allow interaction with their surroundings. Indians conserved the environment in exchange for hunting the animals and protecting themselves against pests.  This approach was lost, as [[Darcy Ribeiro]] stated, \"Thus they passed millennia, until they came up against the armed agents of our civilization, with their capacity to attack and mortally wound the miraculous balance achieved by those complex lifeforms''.\"''<ref name=aa/>\n\n=== Colonial Brazil: sugarcane ===\n\n[[File:Guilherme Piso engenho 1648.jpg|thumb|Sugar attracted the colonizer who brought slaves from Africa, and it led to invasion of the territory.<br />The picture depicts a Dutch sugar mill in the work [[Historia Naturalis Brasiliae]], 1648.]]\n\nThe discovery of sugarcane in the Northeast region transformed Brazil. [[Sugar plantations in the Caribbean|Plantation]] monoculture enriched the Europeans, but brought little benefit to Brazilians.<ref name=bb>BAER, Werner: ''A Economia Brasileira'', Nobel, S\u00e3o Paulo, 2nd ed, 2003, {{ISBN|85-213-1197-4}}, {{ISBN|978-85-213-1197-3}}</ref>\n\nSugarcane wealth was concentrated under the colonizers, generating a [[feudalism|quasi-feudal]] social system organized around large landholdings. Brazilian sugar was thirty percent less expensive than sugar from elsewhere, creating major export opportunities.\n\nA decline in the second half of the 17th century led many producer regions to diversify production, expanding cotton or, in [[Ba\u00eda de Todos os Santos|Reconcavo Baiano]], tobacco or cocoa. The archaic social structure and obsolete technology outlasted cane production in those regions.<ref name=bb/>\n\n==== Slave labor ====\n{{Main|Slavery in Brazil}}[[File:Jos\u00e9 Mariano da Conceicao Velloso - O fazendeiro do Brazil - cultivador.jpg|thumb|In the illustration of \"O Fazendeiro do Brasil\" (The Farmer in Brazil), 1806, [[Jos\u00e9 Mariano da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o Veloso]] describes the steps and tools used in the cultivation of indigo in Brazil.]]\n\nInitially, plantation owners attempted to use local labor in their fields. While laws prohibited their enslavement, in many areas the law was not respected. Locals responded by rebelling, flight or simply dying. European diseases took a heavy toll on indigenous peoples.\n\nThe settlers then switched to enslaving and importing Africans to do the work.<ref name=\"hh\">SILVA, Joaquim, PENNA, J. B. Damasco: ''Hist\u00f3ria Geral'', Cia. Editora Nacional, S\u00e3o Paulo, 1972</ref> The Portuguese and others imported 4 million Africans to carry out cultivation, using what came to be called the [[plantation economy|plantation system]].\n\nIn the first century, after European arrival the slave population had already surpassed that of the locals, decimated by disease. Antonil stated: \"the slaves are the hands and feet of the mill, because without them in Brazil, it is not possible to make, maintain or expand the farm or have a running mill.\"<ref name=\"hh\" />\n\nThe slaves cleared the agricultural frontiers, such as in the west for coffee [[plantation]]s. By the end of the Second Reign, Brazil accounted for more than half the world's coffee production.<ref name=\"hh\" />\n\nOn 13 May 1888 Brazil adopted the [[Lei \u00c1urea]] ('Golden Law'), which abolished slavery in Brazil. In the preceding years, 75% of the Africans and mulattoes had been freed by [[manumission]].<ref name=\"Bergad\">Bergad, Laird W. 2007. The Comparative Histories of Slavery in Brazil, Cuba, and the United States. New York: Cambridge University Press.\n</ref> According to Jo\u00e3o Ribeiro, \"more than anything humane and Christian, [[Lei \u00c1urea]] ('Golden Law') menaced the work and gravely injured the interests of the farmers; there still had been in Brazil more than seven hundred thousand slaves (...) Many of the farmers turned to the Republican party or became indifferent to the attack of the institutions...\"\n\nThe law did not provide an accompanying land distribution to the ex-captives. It led to a [[rural exodus]], both from the workers and from the now-bankrupt landlords. Slavery and its end formed the root of future problems such as slums, violence and poverty in urban centres.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/contexto_1.html |title=''Um velho desafio brasileiro \u2013 A import\u00e2ncia da reforma agr\u00e1ria para o futuro do pa\u00eds'' |language= |work=Revista Veja |date= |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613130440/http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/contexto_1.html |archivedate=13 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Brazilian Empire: coffee ===\n\nIn the late colonial era coffee was introduced to the country. After [[Independence of Brazil|independence]] production consolidated in the [[Southeast Region, Brazil|Southeast region]], mainly in the state of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. At the beginning of the 19th century, exports totaled 19.6 tons, growing to 3,063,660 tons in the 1880\u20131890 period, growing to about sixty three percent of Brazil's total exports.<ref name=\"bb\" />\n\n[[File:Coffee plantation in Brazil.jpg|thumb|Brazilian coffee plantation in the early twentieth century.]]\n\nCoffee was responsible for the appearance of a new dominant [[oligarchy]] in Brazil, the so-called Coffee Barons. It hastened immigration following the end of slavery. The era reached its peak with [[Caf\u00e9 com leite politics]], ending with the [[Manuel Ferraz de Campos Sales|Campos Sales]] administration. The [[Great Depression]] closed this cycle at the end of the 1930s with industrialization, capitalized by profits from coffee production.<ref>ARRUDA, Jos\u00e9 Jobson de A.: ''Hist\u00f3ria Moderna e Contempor\u00e2nea''. \u00c1tica, S\u00e3o Paulo, 13th ed., 1981.</ref>\n\n[[File:Preparing for coffee shipment.jpg|thumb|Bagging for export, at the height of the coffee cycle.]]\n\nCoffee drew many Italian immigrants to the west of S\u00e3o Paulo. Coffee wealth accentuated the differences between the Brazilian regions, especially vs the [[Northeast Region, Brazil|Northeast]].<ref name=bb/>\n\nBesides coffee, other crops increased in the 19th century, such as tobacco and [[Cocoa bean|cocoa]], in Bahia, and [[rubber]] in [[Amaz\u00f4nia]]. In 1910 rubber represented about forty percent of exports.<ref name=bb/>\n\n==== International problems ====\nBrazilian coffee production exceeded global demand at the beginning of the 20th century. This resulted in the Taubat\u00e9 Agreement, where the State began acquiring surplus for destruction and planting seedlings was forbidden&mdash;with the goal of maintaining a minimum profitable price.<ref name=bb/>\n\nRubber suffered from foreign competition. In 1870, English smugglers smuggled [[rubber tree]] seedlings out of Brazil and in 1895 began production in Asia. In the 1910s and 1920s this competition practically eliminated Brazilian production.<ref name=bb/>\n\n=== Agronomy schools ===\n\n[[File:Entrada Principal - CAC.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the [[Agricultural School in Cambori\u00fa]], of UFSC.]]\nIn 1887 during the Empire era, the first school dedicated to the training of agronomists opened in the city of [[Cruz das Almas]]. In 1883, in [[Pelotas]], Rio Grande do Sul, a second school opened.<ref name=engag>{{cite web |url=http://www.agr.feis.unesp.br/dv11112003.php |title=A Agronomia Atrav\u00e9s dos Tempos |language=Portuguese |author=TOSCANO, Luiz Fernando |work=essay originally published in Journal of Votuporanga, Year 50, n\u00b0 12.798, p. 02 (on: [[UNESP]] site) |date=11 November 2003 |accessdate=6 March 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309105407/http://www.agr.feis.unesp.br/dv11112003.php |archivedate=9 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe first school was officially recognized thirty-five years after its creation, with Decree 8.319/1910. The [[agronomist]] profession only came to be recognized in 1933. Seventy regular agronomy colleges operate in Brazil. The day the decree was publicized, 12 October, became the \"Day of the Agronomist.\"<ref name=engag/>\n\nProfessional registration is managed by Regional Engineering and Architecture Councils, integrated at the national level by CONFEA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.confea.org.br/ |title=CONFEA's official website |language=Portuguese |author=Confea |website= |date= |accessdate=12 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310020341/http://www.confea.org.br/ |archivedate=10 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Educational activity is supported by the Federation of Brazilian Agronomy Students.\n\n=== Diversification: 1960\u20131990 ===\n\n[[File:Embrapa 35 anos fundador (Jos\u00e9 Cruz ABr) 23abr2008.JPG|thumb|The former minister, Luis Fernando Cirne Lima, founder of Embrapa, speaking at the corporation's 35th anniversary conference.]]\nThe Brazilian Enterprise for Agricultural Research ([[EMBRAPA]]) was established during the [[Brazilian military government|military regime]] in 1973 with the objective of diversifying production. The body was responsible for the support of new crops, adapted to the country's diverse regions. The expansion of agricultural borders towards the [[Cerrado]] had begun, and of monocultural [[latifundium|latifundia]] with production at a semi-industrial scale of soybeans, cotton and beans.<ref name=bb/>  Czech-Brazilian researcher [[Johanna D\u00f6bereiner]] helped lead Brazil's [[Green Revolution]], winning her the [[UNESCO Science Prize]] for her work on nitrogen-fixing microorganisms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnpab.embrapa.br/aunidade/johanna.html |title=49 Anos Dedicados \u00e0 Pesquisa em Microbiologia do Solo (49 Years Dedicated to Research in Soil Microbiology) |language=Portuguese |authors=Embrapa/Agrobiologia |website= |date= |accessdate=13 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217083254/http://www.cnpab.embrapa.br/aunidade/johanna.html |archivedate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1960 four main agricultural products were exported, growing by the early 1990s to nineteen. Brazil also moved \"downstream\" to expand post-harvest processing. In the 60's unprocessed goods made up 84% of total exports, falling to 20% by 1990.<ref name=bb/>\n\nAgricultural promotion policies included subsidized credits, bank debt write-offs and exports subsidies (in some cases, reaching 50% of the product value).<ref name=bb/>\n\n=== Mechanization: 1990s ===\n\n[[File:Agriculture in Brazil.jpg|thumb|Harvester on a Brazilian cotton plantation.]]\n\nBeginning with the 1994 creation of [[Plano Real]] for monetary stabilization, Brazilian agriculture went through a radical transformation: the State cut subsidies and the market began to finance agriculture, leading to the replacement of manpower with machines. Brazil's rural population fell from 20,700,000 in 1985 to 17,900,000 in 1995, followed by a decrease in import taxes on inputs and other measures that forced Brazilian producers to adapt to global practices. The raise of productivity, mechanization (with reduction of costs) and professionalization marked that period.<ref name=bb/>\n\n== Land issues ==\nBrazil initially used a land management system known as sesmarias featured by large holdings with a small number of landowners. In 1822 sesmarias gave way to the current [[latifundium|latifundia]] (system of large estates).<ref name=\"oqeqa\">{{cite book | author = Jos\u00e9 Graziano da Silva | title = O que \u00e9 Quest\u00e3o Agr\u00e1ria (Chapter: ''O desenvolvimento recente da agricultura brasileira: a heran\u00e7a hist\u00f3rica'')  | edition = 13th | year = 1980 | publisher = [[editora Brasiliense|Brasiliense]] | volume =18 (cole\u00e7\u00e3o Primeiros Passos) | location = S\u00e3o Paulo | language = Portuguese | isbn = | chapter = | quote =| author-link = Jos\u00e9 Graziano da Silva }}</ref> In 1850 the [[Land tenure|''Law of Lands'']] was promulgated, which kept the latifundia system and remained in effect until 1964, when the [[Brazilian military government|dictatorship]] prepared the Land Statute. The high cost of agricultural production contributed to latifundia formation and the country never experienced substantial [[land reform]]. That only became part of the country's official and legal policies after the [[Constitution of Brazil|1988 Constitution]].<ref>{{cite book | author = CARRIL, Lourdes | title = Terras de Negros \u2013 heran\u00e7a de quilombos (Chap. 4: ''Terras no Brasil: uma quest\u00e3o n\u00e3o resolvida'') | year = 1997 | publisher = [[editora Scipione|Scipione]] | location = S\u00e3o Paulo | language = Portuguese | isbn =978-85-262-3225-9  | chapter = | quote =}}</ref>\n\nOf the around thirty-one million Brazilians who lived in poverty in 2014, more than half lived in rural areas. In the last twenty-five years of the 20th century, about thirty million rural dwellers abandoned or lost their land, creating some 4.8 million landless families. During that time, the majority of funding resources was directed to the [[oligarchy|oligarchs]] and great landowners, supporting the model of intensive monoculture agriculture.<ref name=fao>{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/righttofood/kc/downloads/vl/docs/AH264.pdf |title=Agrarian Reform in Brazil |authors= [[Organiza\u00e7\u00e3o das Na\u00e7\u00f5es Unidas para a Agricultura e a Alimenta\u00e7\u00e3o|FAO]] |work= Global Campaign for Agrarian Reform = ARC Fact sheet |date= May 2000 |accessdate=8 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1985 and 1988 the country's redemocratization triggered almost 9,000 social conflicts in rural areas and the murders of 1,167 people over agricultural issues. In this period a confrontation pitted unions, social movements and the [[Catholic Church]] against the landowners united in the [[Uni\u00e3o Democr\u00e1tica Ruralista|Democratic Association of Ruralists]] (UDR) which had Ronaldo Caiado as its main representative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/arquivo/180686.html |title=O trator da direita |language=Portuguese |work=[[Revista Veja]] |date=18 June 1986 |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402033508/http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/arquivo/180686.html |archivedate=2 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The most famous victim of those conflicts was the unionist [[Chico Mendes]], in [[Acre (state)|Acre]], in 1988.\n\n[[File:MST 06142007.jpg|thumb|Members of the Landless Workers' Movement (MST), the main representative group of the landless workers, during the closing of the MST's 5th Congress in Bras\u00edlia, in 2007.]]\nAccording to Man\u00e7ano rural censuses collected since 1940 indicated ongoing concentration of land ownership, accompanied by an exodus of farmers to urban areas. Reversing the trend would have required the annual settlement of 150,000 families. During [[Itamar Franco]]'s Government, the [[INCRA]] (National Institute of Colonization and Agrarian Reform) achieved about 10,000 settlements annually. A fast-track procedure for expropriation of large landholdings was established, ending long delays, one of the measure's main obstacles.<ref name=ra/>\n\nThe conflicts reached their peak in 1996 with the [[Eldorado dos Caraj\u00e1s massacre]], in [[Par\u00e1]], when the governor, Almir Gabriel, ordained the clearing of a road occupied by the landless. Casualties amounted to nineteen dead and fifty-one injured, underlining the land problem and accompanying disrespect for human rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/em_dia/carajas_capa.html |title=Sangue em Eldorado |language=Portuguese |authors=[[M\u00f4nica Bergamo|BERGAMO, M\u00f4nica]] e CAMAROTTI, Gerson |work=[[Revista Veja]] |date=24 April 1996 |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126180411/http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/em_dia/carajas_capa.html |archivedate=26 January 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn a 1996 article economist [[Maria da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o Tavares]], one of the most prominent critics of [[Fernando Henrique Cardoso]]'s Government, claimed, \"the importance of a rural reform has increased and the dispute for land, if the relations of \"dominance\" of rural properties are not regulated quickly, will lead to growing confrontations\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eco.unicamp.br/artigos/tavares/artigo44.htm |title=A Quest\u00e3o Agr\u00e1ria e as Rela\u00e7\u00f5es de Poder no Pa\u00eds |language=Portuguese |author=TAVARES, Maria da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o |work=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |date=5 May 1996 |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519201041/http://www.eco.unicamp.br/artigos/tavares/artigo44.htm |archivedate=19 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe land reform movement included about five hundred land occupations of what protesters considered to be unproductive farms. As a reaction to the invasions, President Cardoso published Provisional Measure 2.027-38, which prohibited earmarking all occupied land for agrarian reform.<ref name=ra>{{cite web |url=http://www.comciencia.br/reportagens/agraria/agr04.shtml |title=''MP da desapropria\u00e7\u00e3o dever\u00e1 ser mantida'' |language=Portuguese |author=CUNHA, Rodrigo |work=Revista ComCi\u00eancia |date= |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307175732/http://www.comciencia.br/reportagens/agraria/agr04.shtml |archivedate=7 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Irrigation ==\n[[File:Arroz 095.jpg|thumb|Rice paddy: Where irrigation first occurred in Brazil.]]\nThe first irrigation experiments in Brazil occurred in Rio Grande do Sul, for cultivating rice. The first record dates to 1881 with the construction of the Cadro dam which began in 1903.{{Clarify|reason = Did it begin in 1881 or 1903?|date = November 2014}} However, the practice broadened in the last thirty years of the 20th century between the years 1970 to 1980.<ref name=birriga>{{cite book | author =Minist\u00e9rio da Integra\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional | title =A irriga\u00e7\u00e3o no Brasil:situa\u00e7\u00e3o e diretrizes | edition = | year = 2008 | publisher =IICA | volume = | location =Bras\u00edlia | language = Portuguese | isbn =978-92-9039-908-7 | chapter = | quote =}}</ref>\n\nPrivate initiative developed Irrigation in the South and Southeast regions.\n\nIn the Northeast official bodies, such as DNOCS and CODEVASF, led the way beginning in the 1950s. In 1968, the Executive Group on Irrigation and Agrarian Development (GEIDA) was set up, and two years later it instituted the Multi-annual Program of Irrigation (PPI). The majority of resources were directed to the Northeast.<ref name=\"birriga\" /> These federal initiatives, however, did not achieve success. In 1985 a new guidance and in 1996 a new direction produced the New Model of Irrigation Project. The Project intended to broaden the use of irrigation in agriculture and drew on more than 1,500 national and foreign experts.<ref name=birriga/>\n\nAccording to the [[World Bank]], Brazil's irrigation potential is about {{Convert|29000000|ha|sqmi}}. In 1998, however, drought reduced capacity to only 2.98 million hectares.<ref name=est>{{cite web |url=http://www.agriambi.com.br/revista/v5n1/171.pdf |title=Estat\u00edsticas sobre irriga\u00e7\u00e3o no Brasil segundo o Censo Agropecu\u00e1rio 1995\u20131996 |language=Portuguese |author=Mard\u00f4nio L. Loiola1 |author2=Francisco de Souza |work=Revista Brasileira de Engenharia Agr\u00edcola e Ambiental, v.5, n.1, p. 171\u2013180 |date= |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150701/http://www.agriambi.com.br/revista/v5n1/171.pdf |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 20th century, the country primarily used [[Irrigation#Surface|surface irrigation]] (59%), followed by [[Irrigation#Sprinkler System|overhead]] (35%) and then [[Drip irrigation|targeted irrigation]]. The South represented the largest irrigated area (more than 1.1 million hectares), followed by the Southeast (800 thousand hectares) and Northeast (490 thousand hectares).<ref name=est/>\n\nCurrently, a regulatory milestone of irrigation is making its way through the [[National Congress of Brazil]], through bill 6381/2005,<ref name=birriga/> which aims at replacing the Law 6662/1979, which regulates irrigation policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/Leis/L6662.htm |title=Lei 6662 |language=Portuguese |author=Congresso Nacional |work=Revista Brasileira de Engenharia Agr\u00edcola e Ambiental, v.5, n.1, p. 171\u2013180 |date=1979 |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328100748/http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/Leis/L6662.htm |archivedate=28 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWater resources policy is regulated by Law 9433/1997, and managed by the National Council.<ref name=\"birriga\" />\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n=== Storage ===\n\n[[File:Rondon\u00f3polis transporte soja (Roosevelt Pinheiro) 28mar09.JPG|thumb|\nTrucks transporting soybean crop\n]]\n\nCrop [[Food storage|storage]] facilities require expansion in order to keep up with increasing production. Brazilian storage capacity in 2003 was 75% of grain production,<ref name=\"pesq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.finep.gov.br/PortalDPP/relatorio_setorial/impressao_relatorio.asp?lst_setor=18 |title=Relat\u00f3rio Setorial Preliminar: Armazenagem agr\u00edcola |date=7 December 2007 |accessdate=22 December 2009 |last=Martinelli |first=Orlando |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609214713/http://www.finep.gov.br/PortalDPP/relatorio_setorial/impressao_relatorio.asp?lst_setor=18 |archivedate=9 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> well short of the ideal of 120%.<ref name=\"armazex\">{{cite web |url=http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0869/m0082220.html |title=A falta que faz um armaz\u00e9m |date=1 June 2006 |last=Corr\u00eaa |first=Alessandra |work=Revista Exame |accessdate=22 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427174805/http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0869/m0082220.html |archivedate=27 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFarm-based crop storage (e.g., using [[silo]]s) is not common in Brazil. Lack of storage forces produce to be commercialized quickly. According to Conab data, only 11% of warehouses are located on farms (by comparison [[Argentina]] has 40%, the [[European Union]] has 50% and Canada has 80%). Farmers rely on third party storage services.\n\nLack of access to capital, exacerbated by financial instability from factors such as exchange rate volatility, prevents most producers from building significant storage.<ref name=\"armazex\" />\n\n=== Transport ===\n\n[[File:Safra interior Sao Paulo 01 2006 06.jpg|thumb|Transport of crops by highway]]\nCrop transport is a longstanding structural problem for Brazilian agriculture. Calmon noted that, since the Empire, \"the disposal of the harvest is difficult\" and indicated that \"the old projects of iron roads or cartable paths, linking the coast to the central mountains (...) are resisted by skeptical statesmen, quoting Thiers, who, in 1841, believed that railways were not convenient to France\".<ref>CALMON, Pedro: \"Hist\u00f3ria da Civiliza\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira\", Cia. Editora Nacional, S\u00e3o Paulo, 3\u00aa ed., 1937</ref>\n\nCrops are immediately trucked to market via highways, mostly in poor traffic conditions at high cost.<ref name=es>{{cite web |url=http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_7.doc |title=A Log\u00edstica do Escoamento da Safra Brasileira |language=Portuguese |author=FILHO, Jos\u00e9 |last2=Caixeta |first2=Vicente |work=ESALQ \u2013 USP |date= |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621172808/http://cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_7.doc |archivedate=21 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFor the 2008/2009 harvest, for example, the Federation of Agriculture and Livestock of Goi\u00e1s denounced poor road conditions in the [[Central-West Region, Brazil|Center-West region]], despite repeated requests for federal assistance over several years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faeg.com.br/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&catid=14:ultimas-noticias&id=1203:-estradas-mal-conservadas-vao-prejudicar-escoamento-da-safra-200809 |title=Problemas em estradas prejudicam escoamento de safra |language=Portuguese |author=FAEG |website= |date=13 January 2009 |accessdate=9 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the federal government issued a National Plan of Logistics and Transportation, meant to improve production flow.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.noticiacapital.com.br/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10775:plano-nacional-de-logistica-e-transportes-sera-discutido-na-fieb&catid=45:economia&Itemid=56 |title=Plano Nacional de Log\u00edstica e Transportes ser\u00e1 discutido na Fieb |language=Portuguese |work=Not\u00edcia Capital |date=4 March 2010 |accessdate=3 June 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308145608/http://www.noticiacapital.com.br/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10775:plano-nacional-de-logistica-e-transportes-sera-discutido-na-fieb&catid=45:economia&Itemid=56 |archivedate=8 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lack of investment, however, continues to be the main obstacle to distribution logistics.\n\n=== Regulatory stocks and minimum price ===\n\nA good example of the need of regulatory stocks is in the production of [[ethanol]] as a fuel from sugar cane. The elevated price variation during the harvest year, that varies for climatic and plant health reasons, justifies the formation of stocks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/pdf/Cepea_alcool_OESP.pdf |title=Estoques Reguladores de \u00c1lcool |language=Portuguese |last=Rumenos |first=Mirian |last2=Bacchi |first2=Piedade |work=O Estado de S. Paulo in:Cepea Esalq/USP |date=20 April 2006 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091222194809/http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/pdf/Cepea_alcool_OESP.pdf |archivedate=22 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Stocks also aim to stabilize farmers' revenues, and avoid price fluctuations between harvests.{{Clarify|reason = This is gibberish, but there may be a point here.|date = November 2014}}\n\nUntil the 1980s, Brazil employed the Minimum Prices Policy. That policy had lost relevance by the 1990s, due to [[globalization]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iea.sp.gov.br/out/verTexto.php?codTexto=330 |title=Estabiliza\u00e7\u00e3o De Pre\u00e7os, Renda Ou De Volume Negociado? |language=Portuguese |author=Afonso Negri Neto |work=Instituto de Economia Agr\u00edcola |date=4 December 2001 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160457/http://www.iea.sp.gov.br/out/verTexto.php?codTexto=330 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe composition of stocks at the national level is the responsibility of the National Food Supply Company (Conab).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agroplante.com.br/noticias.php?id=395 |title=Com safra recorde no Brasil, a maior da hist\u00f3ria, pode sobrar milho no mercado |language=Portuguese |website= |date=18 August 2010 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730040851/http://www.agroplante.com.br/noticias.php?id=395 |archivedate=30 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Family farming ==\n[[File:Abr horta Antonio Cruz.jpg|thumb|Vegetable plot on a family farm.]]\nOfficial definitions of a family farmer differ from country to country in [[Latin America]]. There are 3 general categories: subsistence farming, intermediate family farmers and consolidated farms.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.ifad.org/events/agriculture/doc/papers/berdegue.pdf|title = Latin America: The State of Smallholders in Agriculture|date = |accessdate = 16 November 2015|website = |publisher = International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD)|last = Berdegu\u00e9|first = Julio A.|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160221225154/http://www.ifad.org/events/agriculture/doc/papers/berdegue.pdf|archivedate = 21 February 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> In Brazil, the Family Farming Law (Law 11,326) defines family farmers through four criteria related to [[land tenure]], farm size, dependence on farm income, and the use of predominantly family labor.<ref name=\":0\" /> In Brazil, the large majority of family farms are in the northeastern, southern and southeast Brazil. Family farmers in Brazil produce more than 70%of food consumed domestically.\n\nDuring the 1990s, the Lula administration implemented a set of policies that addressed food security on federal, state and municipal levels, the aim of which was to increase federal government support to family farmers. In 1999, the Ministry of Agrarian Development (MDA) was created to support family farmers and promote land reform and sustainable land development.<ref name=\"Brazil - FAO 2014 country fact sheet on food and agriculture policy trends\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/field/009/i3759e/i3759e.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-12-05 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023052917/http://www.fao.org/docrep/field/009/i3759e/i3759e.pdf |archivedate=23 October 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A host of government policies and government-supported programs in the interest of family farmers then emerged, where the family farmer is recognized as a pillar of national development. Since then, the MDA along with other institutions were created with the family farmers and other traditional communities' interests in mind,<ref name=\":1\"/> where policies targeting family farmers were designed to introduce market incentives, promote adequate food distribution and provide technical assistance.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The FOME ZERO (Zero Hunger) Program|url = http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/ap339e/ap339e00.htm|website = www.fao.org|accessdate = 2015-12-05|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150121010400/http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/ap339e/ap339e00.htm|archivedate = 21 January 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn general, family farms are establishments that employ mostly family members<ref name=\"bn1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |title=Agricultura familiar \u2013 apresenta\u00e7\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=Banco do Nordeste |website= |date= |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091002064625/http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |archivedate=2 October 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> with up to five temporary workers.<ref name=\"ceu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_9.doc |title=Agricultura familiar |language=Portuguese |author=Geraldo Sant'Ana de Camargo Barros |work=Cepea/Esalq/USP |date=July 2006 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122191452/http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_9.doc |archivedate=22 November 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Family farms provide the majority of Brazilian staples, including 84% of [[manioc]], 67% of [[bean]]s and 49% of [[Maize|corn]].<ref name=\"bn1\" /> Family farms also have a large role in the livestock and dairy industry, producing 58% of milk, 59% of pork, 50% of poultry and 31% of cattle.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title = Policies and institutional and legal frameworks in the expansion of Brazilian biofuels|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qLak5dKS_qIC|publisher = CIFOR|first = Andrade, R. M. T., Miccolis|last = A}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''% of total crop production by family farmers''' '''(2010 statistics, Ministry of Agrarian Development, Brazil)'''\n!Crop\n!Percentage (%) produced by family farmers\n|-\n|'''Manioc'''\n|84%\n|-\n|'''Beans'''\n|67%\n|-\n|'''Corn'''\n|49%\n|-\n|'''Rice'''\n|34%\n|-\n|'''Milk'''\n|58%\n|-\n|'''Cattle'''\n|31%\n|-\n|'''Pork'''\n|59%\n|-\n|'''Poultry'''\n|50%\n|-\n|'''Wheat'''\n|21%\n|-\n|'''Soybeans'''\n|16%\n|}\nAccording to the [[IBGE]]'s 1995/96 Farming and Livestock Census, there were 4,339,859 family-run establishments in the country, the largest farm being 100 ha in area.<ref name=\"ceu\" /> In 2009, Brazil's Ministry of Agrarian Development (MDA) reported that 84.4% of all rural properties are in fact family farms.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 1990s family farms experienced productivity growth of 75%, compared to only 40% for larger-scale producers. The difference is largely due to the creation of PRONAF (National Program on Family Agriculture), which opened a special family farm credit line.\n\nUp to 2009 six Family Farming and Land Reform National Fairs were held, the first four in [[Bras\u00edlia]] and the last two in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. They highlight the importance of family farming to Brazilian economy, accounting for 70% of the country's food consumption and 10% of Brazilian [[GDP]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=2&id=2657736&action=noticias |title=Not\u00edcia |language=Portuguese |work=Canal Rural |date=15 September 2009 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523234752/http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=2&id=2657736&action=noticias |archivedate=23 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Food security in Brazil==\nInternational monitoring organizations assert that a third of Brazil's population is food insecure.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.iisd.org/publications/food-security-brazilian-case|title = Food Security: The Brazilian Case|date = 27 September 2010|accessdate = 7 December 2015|website = International Institute for Sustainable Development|publisher = IISD|last = Neves do Amaral|first = Weber Antonio|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150911085841/http://www.iisd.org/publications/food-security-brazilian-case|archivedate = 11 September 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Despite increased food production since the industrialization, a large proportion of Brazilians, especially the urban and rural poor, have difficulty meeting their nutrition needs.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.fao.org/ag/AGN/nutrition/BRA_en.stm|title = Brazil Nutrititon Profile|date = October 2000|accessdate = 7 December 2015|website = Nutrition and Consumer Protection|publisher = FAO Rome|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160321232748/http://www.fao.org/ag/agn/nutrition/bra_en.stm|archivedate = 21 March 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Small farmer, landless worker and indigenous movements that had consolidated during or after the military dictatorship mobilized nationwide, pressuring the authorities to prioritize food and nutrition security rose in the 1980s, and were able to strongly shape the direction of developmental policy.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Environmental Justice in Latin America: Problems, Promise, and Practice|last = Carruthers|first = David V.|publisher = MIT Press|year = 2008|isbn = 978-0-262-03372-5|location = }}</ref>\n\nThe notion of access to food and proper nutrition was first recorded official terminology in 1986 as ''seguran\u00e7a alimentar'' ([[food security]]).<ref name=\":02\" /> The right to food and nutrition was established on 25 August 2010, when Brazil adopted the Policy on Food Security and Nutrition (Decree 7.272).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.fao.org/righttofood/news-and-events/news-detail/en/c/44945/|title = Brazil adopts a new Policy on Food Security and Nutrition|date = 2 September 2010|work = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United States (FAO)|access-date = 7 December 2015|via = |url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160610142414/http://www.fao.org/righttofood/news-and-events/news-detail/en/c/44945/|archivedate = 10 June 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref>  Food security refers to being able to meet dietary needs through an adequate, secure supply of nutritious food.<ref name=\":2\" /> The term rose into Brazilian popular consciousness in 1993 after campaigns by a national movement called Citizens' Action Against Hunger and Poverty and for Life. In that same period, Consea (National Food and Nutritional Security Council) was established. the 1st National Conference on Food Security was organized by a combination of policy and grassroots mobilizations. Consea ran from 1993 to 1994, with little success in shaping public policies, was halted until after the establishment of the Fome Zero Program.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|title = The FOME ZERO (Zero Hunger) Program|url = http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/i3023e/i3023e00.htm|website = www.fao.org|accessdate = 2015-12-05|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150121043512/http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/i3023e/i3023e00.htm|archivedate = 21 January 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The 2010 Policy names Consea as an instrument in proposing programs that promote food security on a federal level.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== PRONAF (National Program for the Strengthening of Family Farming) ===\nDue to financial limitations, small farmers generally have difficulties securing the capital necessary to stay in rural areas and maintain production on a small scale. PRONAF was the first policy in 1994 to be created to meet the specific credit needs of family farmers. In order to stimulate agricultural production, the instrument provides incentives in the form of reduced-interest loans from national funds for rural development, targeting low-income farmers and agrarian reform farmers.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|url = http://www10.iadb.org/intal/intalcdi/PE/2009/03940.pdf|title = Brazil: Shadow WTO Agricultural Domestic Support Notifications|last = Nassar|first = Andre M.|date = May 2009|journal = International Food and Policy Research Institute (IFPRI)|doi = |pmid = |access-date = 7 December 2015}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Set against a backdrop of policies opening Brazil to [[Neoliberal]] economic forces and intense competition through [[Mercosur|Mercosul]], PRONAF marked the institutionalization of a differentiated policy approach to family farming in Brazil.<ref name=\":02\" /> The economic and social importance of family farmers and their specific needs were recognized through PRONAF, at least on paper. The creation of PRONAF has been credited to favorable political circumstances, beginning with Brazil's re-democratization in the 1980s and a receptive Cardoso administration to the mobilizations of a number of agrarian civil groups.<ref name=\":02\" /> Loans written out to family farmers through PRONAF rose from US$1 billion in 2000 to an estimated US$5.8 billion in 2008.<ref name=\":4\" /> Other credit programs targeted at family farmers that came after PRONAF include PROGER and PROCERA.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== The Fome Zero Program (The Zero Hunger Program) ===\nThe Fome Zero Program is a federal program aimed increasing food and nutrition security in rural and urban poor communities. Its main strategy was to connect local food producers with local markets, especially in rural areas, through ''inter-setorrialidade (''inter-agency cooperation'')''.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.hungercenter.org/publications/zero-hunger-evaluating-brazilian-food-security-policy-2/|title = Zero Hunger? Evaluating Brazilian Food Security Policy|date = 2011|accessdate = 3 December 2015|website = Congressional Hunger Center|last = Margolies|first = Amy|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061817/http://www.hungercenter.org/publications/zero-hunger-evaluating-brazilian-food-security-policy-2/|archivedate = 4 March 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> It was instituted in 2001 against the backdrop of increasing recognition for family farmers in Brazilian agrarian policies, and a consequence of 20 years of mobilizing by actors at different levels of society for policy change. The Program is built on four axes: food access, strengthening family farming, income generation and articulation, mobilization and social control. Family farmers play a large role in the Program's food security goals: the Family Farming Food Acquisition Program (PAA), the National School Meal Program (Pnae) and the ''Bols''a ''Fam\u00edlia'' Program (Family Grant Cash Transfer ) were implementations that aimed to encourage family farm production of staple foods through cash and program incentives, facilitate distribution of food to families and schools, and also provide conditional health care and social assistance to 42 million vulnerable Brazilians.<ref name=\":02\" /> Despite praise for the Zero Hunger Program, federal evaluation of the impact of measures such as the National School Meal Program on family farmer production and nutrition of schoolchildren have been limited, given the challenges of assessing decentralized implementation of the policy even at municipal levels.<ref name=\":5\" /> Furthermore, the Brazilian government has been cautious and controlled public and international access to the assessment reports of a number of programs, including the report for the ''Bolsa ''Fam\u00edlia'''' program.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Gathering ==\n[[File:26Movim. Interestadual Quebradeiras de Coco023.JPG|thumb|People gathering babassu, in Maranh\u00e3o.]]\nThe country's colonization began with harvesting native plants where they grew. Cultivation followed much later. The exploitation of [[Caesalpinia echinata|brazilwood]], known to the natives as ibirapitanga, and which ended up naming the land was begun by the Portuguese.<ref>Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil. Souto Maior. Unidade III \u2013 O Ciclo do Pau-Brasil. Cia Editora Nacional, S\u00e3o Paulo, 1968</ref>\n\nBrazil operates forty-nine gathering reservations and sixty-five forests protected by federal law. The gathering of plant resources is encouraged as a means of interacting with, but not degrading, the environment.<ref name=uu>{{cite web |url=http://noticias.ambientebrasil.com.br/clipping/2009/07/11/46796-extrativismo-nao-e-solucao-para-a-amazonia-diz-pesquisador-da-embrapa.html |title=Extrativismo n\u00e3o \u00e9 solu\u00e7\u00e3o para a Amaz\u00f4nia, diz pesquisador da Embrapa |language=Portuguese |last=Then\u00f3rio |first=Iber\u00ea |work=Globo Amaz\u00f4nia, in: Ambiente Brasil |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817065631/http://noticias.ambientebrasil.com.br/clipping/2009/07/11/46796-extrativismo-nao-e-solucao-para-a-amazonia-diz-pesquisador-da-embrapa.html |archivedate=17 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLack of government funding has destabilized this use of forest resources. The case of natural rubber is typical: in Acre about 4,000 families have apparently abandoned the activity, as revealed in early 2009. After undergoing acclimatization, rubber trees were grown successfully in S\u00e3o Paulo state, where more than 36,000 hectares were planted \u2013 while Acre accounts for little more than a thousand hectares.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mercadoetico.terra.com.br/arquivo/governo-nao-age-e-extrativismo-esta-a-beira-da-falencia/ |title=Extrativismo est\u00e1 \u00e0 beira da fal\u00eancia |language=Portuguese |last=Ara\u00fajo |first=Chico |work=Ag\u00eancia Amaz\u00f4nia |date=12 February 2009 |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714031227/http://mercadoetico.terra.com.br/arquivo/governo-nao-age-e-extrativismo-esta-a-beira-da-falencia/ |archivedate=14 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHomma claims that gathering rubber is economically impracticable. For example, in native forests, rubber trees are found at a density of some 1.5 trees per ha, versus hundreds of trees per ha on rubber plantations. Cultivating degraded areas with native trees has been successful with trees such as cupua\u00e7u and jaborandi.<ref name=uu/>\n\nAccording to [[IBGE]], in 2003 the gathering sector's output was divided into timber (65%) and non-wood (35%), at a value of four hundred forty-nine million Reals, with the following main products: piassaba (27%), babassu (nut \u2013 17%), a\u00e7ai (16%), yerba mate (14%), carnauba (8%) and Brazil nut (5%).<ref name=ibgemad>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=260 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o Florestal Brasileira soma R$7,869 bilh\u00f5es em 2003 |language=Portuguese |author=IBGE-Comunica\u00e7\u00e3o Social |work=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o da Extra\u00e7\u00e3o Vegetal e da Silvicultura \u2013 2003 |date=25 November 2004 |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516221127/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=260 |archivedate=16 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Soils ==\n[[File:Regolith.jpg|thumb|Regolithic soil, in granulite.]]The program of mapping and classifying the country's [[soil]]s began in 1953, with the ''Chart of Soils in Brazil''. IBGE published the first map in 2003. Soil knowledge helped allow the expansion of agricultural production from 1975. The expansion of the Center-West required new technology because the region is mainly formed by [[oxisols]], which favor mechanization from soil preparation to harvest, partly because they are nutrient-poor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/31072003mapasolos.shtm |title=Mapa de Solos do Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Comunica\u00e7\u00e3o Social IBGE |website= |date=31 July 2003 |accessdate=23 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109011301/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/31072003mapasolos.shtm |archivedate=9 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSoil classification, study and systematization are championed by Embrapa Soils, with participation from groups such as the RADAM Project, the Rural University (now [[Universidade Federal Rural do Rio de Janeiro|UFRRJ]]) and other ag[[Agronomy|ronomists]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnps.embrapa.br/unidade/historico.html |title=Hist\u00f3rico CNPS |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa Solos |website= |date= |accessdate=23 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212150554/http://www.cnps.embrapa.br/unidade/historico.html |archivedate=12 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Agribusiness ==\n[[File:Soja exportacao.jpg|thumb|Machinery in soybean production.]]\nIn 2010 Brazil was the third largest exporter of [[agricultural]] products in the world, behind only the United States and the European Union.<ref name=\"estadao\">[http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20100601192402/http://www.estadao.com.br/estadaodehoje/20100307/not_imp520620,0.php Brasil supera Canad\u00e1 e se torna o terceiro maior exportador agr\u00edcola] \u2013 \"The State of S.Paulo\", 7 March 2010 (visited on 7 March 2010)</ref><ref>[http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Economia_Negocios/0,,MUL1518968-9356,00-BRASIL+SE+TORNA+O+TERCEIRO+MAIOR+EXPORTADOR+AGRICOLA.html Brasil se torna o terceiro maior exportador agr\u00edcola] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808190427/http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Economia_Negocios/0,,MUL1518968-9356,00-BRASIL+SE+TORNA+O+TERCEIRO+MAIOR+EXPORTADOR+AGRICOLA.html |date=8 August 2014 }} \u2013 \"G1\", 7 March 2010 (visited on 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nDuring the last two decades of the 20th century, Brazil witnessed a doubling of [[yield per acre]]. This resulted from input improvements (seeds, [[fertilizer]]s, machinery), public policies that encouraged exports, reduced tax burden (such as the 1996 reduction of the [[circulation tax]]), more favorable real [[exchange rate]], which had allowed [[price stability]] (in 1999), increased Asian demand, [[productivity growth]] and reduced [[trade barrier]]s.<ref name=\"agb\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.uff.br/econ/download/tds/UFF_TD186.pdf |title=Agroneg\u00f3cio no Brasil: perspectives e limita\u00e7\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |last=Guanziroli |first=Carlos Enrique |journal=Economia Para Discuss\u00e3o, 186, Universidade Federal Fluminense |issn=1519-4612 |date=April 2006 |accessdate=3 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602041041/http://www.uff.br/econ/download/tds/UFF_TD186.pdf |archivedate=2 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFarming accounted for almost a third of [[GDP]], once everything from agricultural inputs to [[food processing]] and distribution are included.<ref name=\"agb\" />\n\nFrom 1990 to 2001, farming employment fell, although overall [[agribusiness]] employment jumped from 372 thousand to 1.82 million. The number of companies grew from 18 thousand in 1994 to almost 47 thousand in 2001.<ref name=\"ipea\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ipea.gov.br/pub/bccj/bc_60n.pdf |title=Crescimento da Agricultura |language=Portuguese |author1=GASQUES, Jos\u00e9 Garcia |author2=BASTOS, Eliana Teles |work=Boletim de Conjuntura, n\u00ba 60 |date=March 2003 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419013351/http://www.ipea.gov.br/pub/bccj/bc_60n.pdf |archivedate=19 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFactors that limit further expansion range from pests evolving to target [[monoculture]]s, [[#Transportation of production|infrastructure issues]] and environmental problems generated by practices such as [[deforestation]], etc.<ref name=\"agb\" />\n\n=== Trade balance ===\n\nThe 2007 harvest enabled gross agriculture exports yielding 68.1 billion dollars, and net exports of 57.3 billion dollars.<ref name=reu1>{{cite web |url=http://www.estadao.com.br/economia/not_eco219430,0.htm |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00e3o de soja em gr\u00e3o do Brasil soma quase US$2 bi em julho |language=Portuguese |agency=Reuters |website= |date=7 August 2008 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221131901/http://www.estadao.com.br/economia/not_eco219430,0.htm |archivedate=21 February 2009 |df=dmy-all |author-link=Reuters }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Brazil's biggest export market was the [[European Union]], while China was the largest single importing country with a 13.2% share, followed by the [[Netherlands]] with 9.5% and the US at 8.7%.<ref name=\"reu1\" />\n\n=== Regions ===\n\n[[Regions of Brazil|Brazil's regions]] offer a wide diversity of climate. Agriculture reflects this diversity. In 1995, the North produced 4.2%, the Northeast \u2013 13.6%, the Center-West \u2013 10.4%, the Southeast \u2013 41.8% and the South \u2013 30.0%. The Center-West and North regions have recently expanded their share to the total.<ref name=\"ttsc\">{{cite journal |title=A descentraliza\u00e7\u00e3o regional do agroneg\u00f3cio brasileiro. |language=Portuguese |last1=Parr\u00e9 |first1=Jos\u00e9 Luiz |last2=Guilhoto |first2=J.J. Martins. |journal=Scielo \u2013 Revista Brasileira de Economia |volume=55 |number=2 |issn=0034-7140 |date=April\u2013June 2001 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1590/S0034-71402001000200004 }}</ref>\n\n==== South ====\n[[File:Vinicola rio grande do sul (1701423442).jpg|thumb|Vineyard gaucho]]\nThe [[South Region, Brazil|southern Brazilian state]]s are [[Rio Grande do Sul]], Santa Catarina and [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]]. [[Cooperative]]s are a common feature of agriculture there. Irrigated rice and [[poultry farming|poultry]] are the two largest crops. Corn and [[beans]] are also prominent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://seer.ufrgs.br/AnaliseEconomica/article/viewFile/10655/6291 |title=A Import\u00e2ncia Econ\u00f4mica do Agroneg\u00f3cio para a Regi\u00e3o Sul do Brasil. |language=Portuguese |authors=PARR\u00c9L, Jos\u00e9 Luiz. GUILHOTO, Joaquim Jos\u00e9 Martins |work=UFRGS |date=1985 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162243/http://seer.ufrgs.br/AnaliseEconomica/article/viewFile/10655/6291 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The region is Brazil's largest tobacco producer and the world's largest exporter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25822 |title=Not\u00edcia: Regi\u00e3o Sul dever\u00e1 produzir 760 mil toneladas de fumo em 2008/2009 |language=Portuguese |work=Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio |date= |accessdate=3 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522211115/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25822 |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSanta Catarina has a high level of interdependence between the industrial and agricultural sectors.<ref name=rsa>{{cite web |url=http://www.fearp.usp.br/egna/resumos/Montoya.doc |title=O Agroneg\u00f3cio nos Estados da Regi\u00e3o Sul: uma an\u00e1lise do grau de integra\u00e7\u00e3o intersetorial entre a agropecuaria e algumas agroind\u00fastrias de 1985 a 1995. |language=Portuguese |authors=MONTOYA, Marco Antonio. VERGARA, Thelmo. OLTRAMARI, Andrea. |website= |date= |accessdate=3 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162400/http://www.fearp.usp.br/egna/resumos/Montoya.doc |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Rio Grande do Sul, family-run agribusiness is important and is descended from the colonial plantation model. Early farms survived and their families stayed on the land.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asbraer.org.br/Documentos/Biblioteca/comparacaors_brasill.pdf |title=Compara\u00e7\u00e3o entre o Agroneg\u00f3cio Familiar do Rio Grande do Sul e o do Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=GUILHOTO, J.J. Martins |work=Teoria e Evid. Econ., 14\u00aa ed., pp. 9\u201335, Passo Fundo |date=2006 |accessdate=3 September 2009 |display-authors=etal }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 the region produced 14.4% of Brazil's fruit.<ref name=iai/>\n\n==== Southeast ====\n[[File:Faz S Sofia canavial 090607 REFON.JPG|thumb|Cane plantation in Avare, S\u00e3o Paulo.]]The Southeast region includes [[Minas Gerais]], S\u00e3o Paulo, [[Rio de Janeiro]] and [[Esp\u00edrito Santo]]. In 1995 it was responsible for the largest share of Brazilian agriculture, but other regions were growing more rapidly.<ref name=\"ttsc\" />\n\nIn 2004 the Southeast produced 49.8% of the nation's fruit.<ref name=iai/> The region hosts 60% of agribusiness software companies, according to a survey carried out by Embrapa Livestock and Farming Information Technology (located in [[Campinas]]/SP).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25086 |title=Empresas de software para agroneg\u00f3cio concentram-se no Sudeste |language=Portuguese |author=Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio: not\u00edcia |website= |date=25 July 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080806212533/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25086 |archivedate=6 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Its agribusiness sector was second in the national ranking, in the period from 2000 to May 2008, representing 36% of 308 billion dollars of total exports. The biggest exports were sugar (17.27%), coffee (16.25%), paper and cellulose (14.89%), meats (11.71%) and horticultural and fruit (especially orange juice) with 10.27%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es do agroneg\u00f3cio do Brasil e das suas macro-regi\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |last=Barros |first=Geraldo |author2=Karlin Saori Ishii |website= |date=14 July 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619200232/http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |archivedate=19 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Northeast ====\n[[File:Opuntia cochenillifera Abr - Valter Campanato.jpg|thumb|Palm plantation in Urandi]]\nThe Northeast includes [[Bahia]], Sergipa, Pernambuco, Alogoas, [[Paraiba]], Rio Grande do Norte, [[Ceara]], [[Piaui]] and [[Maranhao]]. Farms are primarily family-owned; 82.9% of field labor is on family farms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es do agroneg\u00f3cio do Brasil e das suas macro-regi\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |last=Barros |first=Geraldo |author2=Karlin Saori Ishii |website= |date=14 July 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619200232/http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |archivedate=19 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}{{Cite web |url=http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |title=Not\u00edcia institucional |language= |author=Banco do Nordeste |website= |date= |accessdate=11 November 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831232249/http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |archivedate=31 August 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe region is the largest national producer of bananas, (34% of the total)<ref name=emb3>{{cite web |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Banana/BananaCeara/importancia.htm |title=Cultivo da Banana para o Agrop\u00f3lo Jaguaribe-Apodi, Cear\u00e1. |language=Portuguese |author=BORGES, Ana L\u00facia |work=Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o, 5 |issn=1678-8796 |date=January 2003 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216102219/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Banana/BananaCeara/importancia.htm |archivedate=16 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and cassava (34.7%).<ref name=embmand/> It is the second largest producer of rice, with a harvest estimated in 2008 of 1.114 million tons. Maranh\u00e3o produces the majority (668 thousand tons).<ref name=ori/> It ranks second in fruit production, with 27% share.<ref name=iai/>\n\nThe region is subject to prolonged [[drought|dry spell]]s that are worse in [[El Ni\u00f1o]] years. This causes a periodic [[rural exodus]]. Government responses include dams and the [[transfer of the S\u00e3o Francisco River]]. The worst recent droughts were in 1993, 1998 and 1999. The latter was the worst in fifty years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fundaj.gov.br/tpd/127.html |title=A realidade da produtora rural na seca nordestina |language=Portuguese |author=L\u00edgia Albuquerque de Melo |work=Trabalhos para Discuss\u00e3o n. 127 |date=November 2001 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207000644/http://www.fundaj.gov.br/tpd/127.html |archivedate=7 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== North ====\n[[File:Projeto Rondon 2009 Manacapuru.JPG|thumb|Horticulture workshop, Manacapuru, Amazonas.]]\nThe Northern region includes Acre, Amap\u00e1, [[Amazonas (Brazilian state)|Amazonas]], Par\u00e1, [[Rond\u00f4nia]], Roraima and [[Tocantins]]. The [[Amazon rainforest]] occupies a significant part of the region. The region's great challenge is to combine farming with forest preservation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2008/novembro/4a-semana/manejo-florestal-sustentavel-e-destaque-no-amazontech/ |title=Manejo florestal sustent\u00e1vel \u00e9 destaque no Amazontech |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa |work=Not\u00edcia institucional |date=27 November 2008 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706155604/http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2008/novembro/4a-semana/manejo-florestal-sustentavel-e-destaque-no-amazontech/ |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBetween the end of the 19th century and early 20th century, during the so-called [[Amazon rubber boom|Rubber Boom]], the region produced rubber, Brazil's most important export, until Asian production underpriced Brazil and shut down the industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://portalamazonia.globo.com/pscript/amazoniadeaaz/artigoAZ.php?idAz=114 |title=Hist\u00f3ria |language=Portuguese |author=L\u00edgia Albuquerque de Melo |work=Portal da Amaz\u00f4nia, Globo |date= |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091010033445/http%3A//portalamazonia.globo.com/pscript/amazoniadeaaz/artigoAZ.php?idAz%3D114 |archivedate=10 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt is the second largest Brazilian banana producer (26% share)<ref name=emb3/> and of cassava (25.9% share), lagging behind only the Northeast.<ref name=embmand/> It produces 6.1% of the nation's fruit crop.<ref name=iai/>\n\n==== Midwest ====\n[[File:Planta\u00e7\u00e3o de Alho em Catal\u00e3o.jpg|thumb|Irrigated garlic]]\nThe Midwest region includes [[Mato Grosso]], Mato Grosso do Sul, [[Goi\u00e1s]] and [[Federal District (Brazil)|Distrito Federal]]. This region's agriculture developed much later than the rest of the country. The main biome is the [[Cerrado]]. By 2004, it was responsible for 46% of Brazilian soybeans, corn, rice and beans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2003/abril/bn.2004-11-25.0389686053/ |title=Especial 30 Anos \u2013 Tecnologias mudaram a cara do Centro-Oeste brasileiro |language=Portuguese |last=Cipriano |first=Robinson |work=S\u00edtio da Embrapa |date=25 November 2004 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160253/http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2003/abril/bn.2004-11-25.0389686053/ |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOver three decades its harvest grew from 4.2 million to 49.3 million tons in 2008.<ref name=pag1>{{cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=24866 |title=Centro-Oeste deve se tornar maior produtor de gr\u00e3os do pa\u00eds |language=Portuguese |work=not\u00edcia in: Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio |date=10 July 2008 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009054539/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=24866 |archivedate=9 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIts cultivated area in 2008 was 15.1 million hectares. A big growth area was livestock. The opening of roads facilitated this growth.<ref name=pag1/>\n\nAs of 2004 this region produced only 2.7% of the nation's horticulture.<ref name=iai/>\n\n== Products ==\nThe principal agricultural products of Brazil are cattle, coffee, cotton, corn, rice, soy, wheat, sugarcane, tobacco, beans, floriculture and fruit. forestry, vegetables and cassava.\n\n=== Cattle ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cell padding=\"5\" cell spacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Cattle'''<ref>http://www.ipeadata.gov.br/ipeaweb.dll/ipeadata?SessionID=2075918462&Tick=1211151299640&VAR_FUNCAO=Ser_Temas%281410842077%29&Mod=R{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/C90C773459F8B52AE0300801FD0AF827{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1980\n| 1990\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million head'''\n| 78.54\n| 118.08\n| 147.10\n| 169.87\n| 207.15\n|}\n\nBrazil in 2005 produced around 8.7 million [[tonnes]] of beef,<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2134AF4606BE50C8E040A8C075023826{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> becoming world export leader in 2003 after surpassing Australia.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/portal/page?_pageid=33,968707&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL|title=Agroneg\u00f3cio Brasileiro<!-- Bot generated title -->|author=|date=|website=agricultura.gov.br|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502032959/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/portal/page?_pageid=33,968707&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL|archivedate=2 May 2008|df=dmy-all|access-date=19 May 2008}}</ref> Cattle herds are concentrated in [[Mato Grosso]], Mato Grosso do Sul, [[Goi\u00e1s]] and [[Minas Gerais]]. Together they account for over 46% of Brazilian cattle with more than 87 million head.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nAccording to the [[Ministry of Agriculture (Brazil)|Ministry of Agriculture]], Brazilian beef production grew on average 6.1% a year from 1990 to 2003, and reached 7.6 million [[tonnes]]. In 2003, Brazil exported over 1.4 million [[tonnes]] of beef, earning around $1.5 billion. Leather exports that year passed the $1 billion mark.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n=== Coffee ===\n{{Main|Coffee production in Brazil}}\n\n{{Expand section|date=January 2010}}\nCoffee is produced in states like S\u00e3o Paulo and Minas\n\n=== Cotton ===\n\n[[File:Algod\u00e3o Bahia 2003.jpg|thumb|Cotton planted in the cerrado region of Bahia.]]\n\nYield increases were sufficient to substantially increase output between the 1960s and the twenty-first century, despite reduced acreage.<ref name=sci1>{{cite web |url=http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0034-71402008000400002&script=sci_arttext |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o e exporta\u00e7\u00e3o de algod\u00e3o: efeitos de choques de oferta e de demanda. |language=Portuguese |authors=ALVES, Lucilio Rogerio Aparecido; BARROS, Geraldo Sant'Ana de Camargo; BACCHI, Mirian Rumenos Piedade. |work=Revista Brasileira de Economia, vol. 62, n\u00ba4, Rio de Janeiro |date=Oct\u2013Dec 2008 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514150401/http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0034-71402008000400002&script=sci_arttext |archivedate=14 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the 1990s production moved from the South and Southeast regions to the Center-West and to the West of Bahia. Exports began in 2001.<ref name=\"sci1\" /><ref name=\"abrapa\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abrapa.com.br/quemsomos.asp |title=Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Algod\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=ABRAPA |work=P\u00e1gina institucional |date= |accessdate=12 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017015144/http://www.abrapa.com.br/quemsomos.asp |archivedate=17 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil's entry in the cotton market led them to charge the US with illegal subsidies and tariffs. The Brazilian plea went to the [[World Trade Organization]] in 2002. WTO approved sanctions in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atarde.com.br/economia/noticia.jsf?id=1219976 |title=OMC habilita Brasil a aplicar san\u00e7\u00f5es aos Estados Unidos pelo algod\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=Not\u00edcia |work=Jornal [[A Tarde]] |date=31 August 2008 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903031543/http://www.atarde.com.br/economia/noticia.jsf?id=1219976 |archivedate=3 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/101126.htm |title=Algod\u00e3o: Brasil poder\u00e1 adotar retalia\u00e7\u00f5es comerciais contra Estados Unidos |language=Portuguese |last=Fiori |first=Mylena |work=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]] |date=4 June 2008 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160825/http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/101126.htm |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.abrapa.com.br/jornais/834622802122876.pdf |title=A Saga do Algod\u00e3o: das primeiras lavouras \u00e0 a\u00e7\u00e3o na OMC |language=Portuguese |author1=COSTA, S\u00e9rgio Rodrigues |author2=BUENO, Miguel Garcia. |work=Rio de Janeiro: Insight Engenharia, 144p. : il. |date=2004 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206165303/http://abrapa.com.br/jornais/834622802122876.pdf |archivedate=6 February 2009 |df=dmy-all |isbn=85-98831-01-8}} (obra integral para download)</ref>\n\n=== Corn ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Corn'''<ref name=autogenerated4>[http://www.ipeadata.gov.br/ipeaweb.dll/ipeadata?371970046 Ipeadata] <!-- Bot generated title --> {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006213026/http://www.ipeadata.gov.br/ipeaweb.dll/ipeadata?371970046 |date=6 October 2007 }}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 8.67\n| 14.21\n| 20.37\n| 26.57\n| 32.32\n| 35.13\n|}\n\n[[File:Milharal novo Avare 021205 REFON.jpg|thumb|Cornfield, S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nBrazilian corn has two harvests per year. The main harvest is during the rainy season and a second, \"dry cultivation\" harvest follows during the dry season. In the South the main harvest is in late August; while in the Southeast and Center-West, it happens in October and November and in the Northeast, by year end. The second harvest is in Paran\u00e1, S\u00e3o Paulo and in the Center-West, in February and March.\n\nIn 2006 corn was planted on about thirteen million hectares, producing 41 million tons. Brazil was the third largest world producer, accounting for 6.1% of global production. Paran\u00e1 was Brazil's biggest producer, totaling 25.72%.\n\n=== Rice ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Rice'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 4.79\n| 7.55\n| 9.77\n| 11.04\n| 11.13\n| 13.19\n|}\n\n[[File:Arroz 097.jpg|thumb|Rice harvest, Rio do Sul, Santa Catarina.]]\n\nIn the 1980s Brazil evolved from exporting to importing rice in small quantities to meet domestic demand. In the following decade, it became one of the main importers, reaching two million tons, equivalent to 10% of domestic demand by 1997-8. [[Uruguay]] and [[Argentina]] are the main suppliers of the cereal to the country.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Arroz/ArrozIrrigadoBrasil/cap18.htm |title=Consumo, Mercado e Comercializa\u00e7\u00e3o do Arroz no Brasil. |language=Portuguese |last=Alon\u00e7o |first=Airton dos Santos |journal=Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o |number=3 |issn=1806-9207 |date=November 2005 |accessdate=1 October 2009 |display-authors=etal |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213073633/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Arroz/ArrozIrrigadoBrasil/cap18.htm |archivedate=13 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, farmers planted 3.845 million ha, decreasing by 2008, to 2.847 million. Production grew from 11.582 million tons to an estimated 12.177 million tons.<ref name=ori>Tabelas do cultivo do arroz no Brasil: [http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab101.htm \u00e1rea plantada] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420204536/http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab101.htm |date=20 April 2009 }}; [http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab103.htm produ\u00e7\u00e3o] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104084621/http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab103.htm |date=4 January 2010 }}, Portal Arroz Brasileiro, Accessed 30 September 2009</ref>\n\nProductivity per hectare has grown 61% since 1990. Production is concentrated in [[Rio Grande do Sul]], producing on average 48%.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/213229F7DBD76D9CE040A8C075024B3C{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Soybean ===\n{{See also|Deforestation in Brazil#Soybean production}}\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Soybean Production'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 0.20\n| 1.50\n| 15.15\n| 24.07\n| 32.82\n| 51.18\n|}\n\nSoybean production began in 1882. From the beginning of the 20th century soy was used for animal fodder. In 1941, grain production surpassed forage use, becoming the main focus. Brazilian [[soybean]] production increased more than 3000% between 1970 and 2005. Yield increased 37.8% from 1990 to 2005.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2132DF10897FBE12E040A8C075020289{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Soybean and soybean derivatives exports in 2005 alone earned over US$9 billion for Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/03.02.08_1.XLS |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-15 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314025354/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/03.02.08_1.XLS |archivedate=14 March 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe 2007/2008 harvest produced 60.1 million tons, surpassed only by the United States.\n\nBrazil's largest producers are Mato Grosso, Paran\u00e1 and Goi\u00e1s, with fifteen, nine and six million tons, respectively, in 2004\u20132006. [[Mato Grosso]] and [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]] together grow on average over 49% of the crop.\n\n=== Wheat ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Wheat Production'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 0.71\n| 1.84\n| 2.70\n| 5.55\n| 1.72\n| 4.65\n|}\n\nTwo of Brazil's coldest states, [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]] and [[Rio Grande do Sul]], account for over 90% of wheat production.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2131AAF0F3255977E040A8C075025C45{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Brazil imports around US$700 million in wheat every year.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2134AF4606C550C8E040A8C075023826{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/06.08.XLS|title=Wayback Machine|author=|date=12 September 2008|url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912173240/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/06.08.XLS|archivedate=12 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Exporta%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20Peso%20Liquido.xls |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-05-06 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118005713/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Exporta%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20Peso%20Liquido.xls |archivedate=18 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Importa%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20US$%20FOB.xls |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-05-06 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118005915/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Importa%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20US$%20FOB.xls |archivedate=18 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Sugarcane ===\n{{See also|Ethanol fuel in Brazil}}\n\n[[File:Canaviais Sao Paulo 01 2008 06.jpg|thumb|Cane field in S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nDuring the colonial period, Brazil depended heavily on sugarcane and continued to lead world sugarcane production into the twenty-first century.\n\nProduction is concentrated (90%) in S\u00e3o Paulo, Alagoas, Pernambuco, Minas Gerais, Mato Grosso, Mato Grosso do Sul, Goi\u00e1s and Paran\u00e1.<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://odia.terra.com.br/economia/htm/geral_120564.asp|title=O Dia Online<!-- Bot generated title -->|author=|date=|website=terra.com.br|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070902135312/http://odia.terra.com.br/economia/htm/geral_120564.asp|archivedate=2 September 2007|df=dmy-all|access-date=30 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nBrazil harvested 558 million tonnes of sugarcane in 2007, representing a growth of 17.62% over 2006. For 2008, Brazil harvested 648,921,280 tonnes, of which total 89% was used for sugar and [[ethanol]] production. The other 11% was used for ''[[cacha\u00e7a]]'' and ''rapadura'' production, as animal feed and as seeds.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/dinheiro/ult91u396881.shtml Folha Online \u2013 Dinheiro \u2013 Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de \u00e1lcool e de a\u00e7\u00facar bater\u00e1 recorde em 2008, prev\u00ea Conab \u2013 29 April 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Ethanol]] production in 2008 was predicted to reach 26.4 billion litres.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nCompanhia Nacional de Abastecimento (CONAB)said that in 2007, sugarcane cultivated land increased by 12.3%, to 69,000 square kilometres.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Sugarcane Production'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1990\n| 2000\n| 2007\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 56.92\n| 79.75\n| 148.65\n| 262.67\n| 326.12\n| 558.50\n|}\n\n=== Tobacco ===\n\nBrazil is the world's second largest tobacco producer, and the largest exporter since 1993, with about 1.7 billion dollars of turnover.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=8473 |title=Tabaco representa 2% da exporta\u00e7\u00e3o brasileira, not\u00edcia, Andreoli MS&L, 14-08-2009 |language=Portuguese |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150806/http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=8473 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The largest export region is Rio Grande do Sul. The Southern region accounts for 95% of external production. It exports 60 to 70% of output.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cepa.epagri.sc.gov.br/agroindicadores/opiniao/analise_fumo.htm |title=Aspectos da Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Fumo em Santa Catarina |language=Portuguese |last=Marcondes |first=Tabajara |work=EPAGRI-SC |date= |accessdate=2 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402150048/http://cepa.epagri.sc.gov.br/agroindicadores/opiniao/analise_fumo.htm |archivedate=2 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Beans ===\n\n[[File:Feij\u00e3o MacLee 270506 2.JPG|thumb|Irrigated beans in Avare, S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nBrazil is the world's largest producer of beans, accounting for 16.3% of the total, 18.7 million tons in 2005, according to [[FAO]]. Historically most beans came from small producers. Yield in some cases exceeded three thousand kilos per ha.<ref name=emb2>{{cite journal |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Feijao/FeijaoIrrigadoNoroesteMG/index.htm |title=Cultivo do Feij\u00e3o Irrigado na Regi\u00e3o Noroeste de Minas Gerais |language=Portuguese |last=Wander |first=Alcido Elenor. |journal=Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o |number=5 |date=December 2005 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215095712/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Feijao/FeijaoIrrigadoNoroesteMG/index.htm |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBean acreage decreased from 1984 to 2004 by 25%, while output increased by 16%. It is cultivated throughout the country and harvests come year round.<ref name=emb2/>\n\nBrazil imports 100 thousand tons of beans per year.<ref name=emb2/>\n\n=== Floriculture and ornamentals ===\n\n[[File:Yellow and pink rose - Bras\u00edlia, Brazil.jpg|thumb|Example of Brazilian rose, in Brasilia.]]\n\nSome three thousand six hundred producers cultivate flowers and ornamental plants in an area of 4,800 ha.<ref name=sober>{{cite web |url=http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/12/01P062.pdf |title=Log\u00edstica de exporta\u00e7\u00e3o de flores no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Carlos Armando Soncin |website= |date= |accessdate=17 December 2009 |display-authors=etal |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101145652/http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/12/01P062.pdf |archivedate=1 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt employs about one hundred twenty thousand people, of which 80% are women, and about 18% are family farms.<ref name=florr>{{cite web |url=http://www.fit.ufsc.br/disciplinas_download.php?cod=954 |title=Panorama do agroneg\u00f3cio de flores e plantas ornamentais no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=FRAN\u00c7A, Carlos A. Machado de |author2=MAIA, Moacyr B. Rodrigues |work=Sociedade Brasileira de Economia, Administra\u00e7\u00e3o e Sociologia Rural |date=20\u201323 July 2008 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162222/http://www.fit.ufsc.br/disciplinas_download.php?cod=954 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe producers from fifteen states are represented by the Brazilian Institute of Floriculture (IBRAFLOR), with government support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibraflor.org/sis.interna.asp?pasta=1&pagina=1 |title=Hist\u00f3rico |language=Portuguese |author=institucional IBRAFLOR |website= |date= |accessdate=17 December 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFloriculture began in the 1870s, led by the son of {{Interlanguage link|Jean Baptiste Binot|pt}}, who had come to the country to decorate the [[Imperial Museum of Brazil|Imperial Palace]], and whose [[vivarium|orchidarium]] was internationally acknowledged. In 1893, Reggie Dierberger founded a flower company, which later became the Boettcher, pioneers of [[rose]] production.<ref name=florr/>\n\nIn 1948 Dutch immigrants founded a [[cooperative]] in [[Holambra]], a city that still hosts flower production.<ref name=florr/>\n\nSince 2000 the Program of Development of Flowers and Ornamental Plants of the Ministry of Agriculture began. The largest producer is S\u00e3o Paulo state, followed by Santa Catarina, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Cear\u00e1, Rio Grande do Sul, Minas Gerais, Rio de Janeiro, Paran\u00e1, Goi\u00e1s, Bahia, Esp\u00edrito Santo, Amazonas and Par\u00e1.<ref name=florr/>\n\n=== Fruits and perennials ===\n\n[[File:Planta\u00e7\u00e3o de pinhas.jpg|thumb|[[Sugar-apple]] plantation with an irrigated system, at the banks of the S\u00e3o Francisco River, Bahia.]]\n\nThe main fruits grown in Brazil are, in alphabetical order: [[Abiu]], [[a\u00e7a\u00ed]], [[acerola]], [[alligator-apple]], apple, [[atemoya]], [[bacaba]], [[bacuri]], banana, [[biriba]], [[blueberry]], [[brazil plum]], [[brazil nut]], [[breadfruit]], [[caj\u00e1]], [[camu camu]], [[cantaloupe]], [[cashew]], citrus (orange, lemon, [[Lime (fruit)|lime]], etc.), [[coconut]], [[cupua\u00e7u]], [[Common fig|fig]], [[guava]], [[grapes]], [[jambo]], [[jocote]], [[kiwi]], [[mangaba]], [[mango]], [[mangosteen]], [[mulberry]], [[muruci]], [[nectarine]], [[papaya]], [[passionfruit]], [[patawa]], [[peach]], pear, [[pequi]], [[persimmon]], [[physalis]], [[pineapple]], [[pine nut]]s, [[plum]], [[rambutan]], [[raspberry]], [[sapodilla]], [[sapote]], [[sorva]], [[soursop]], [[starfruit]], [[strawberry]], tucuma, [[walnut]], and [[watermelon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embrapa.br/kw_storage/keyword.2007-06-04.3509047076 |title=Rela\u00e7\u00e3o dos cultivares estudados |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa fruticultura |website= |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091219084110/http://www.embrapa.br/kw_storage/keyword.2007-06-04.3509047076 |archivedate=19 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 the fruit sector grossed 9.6 billion dollars \u2013 18% of Brazil's total. National production is higher than 38 million tons, cultivated on 3.4 million hectares. Between 1990 and 2004 exports grew 183% in value, 277% in quantity and 915% net.<ref name=ttu>{{cite web |url=http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/2/747.pdf |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es Brasileiras de Frutas: diversifica\u00e7\u00e3o ou concentra\u00e7\u00e3o de produtos e destinos? |language=Portuguese |authors=FILHO, Miguel Henrique da Cunha. CARVALHO, Rosemeiry Melo. |work=Palestra, Sober.org |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129073557/http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/2/747.pdf |archivedate=29 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nEvery ten thousand dollars invested in fruit production generates three direct jobs and two indirect jobs.<ref name=ttu/>\n\nBrazil is the world's third largest fruit producer, behind China (157 million tons) and India (with 54 million). Oranges and bananas account for 60% of Brazilian output.<ref name=iai>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.redetec.org.br/publique/media/A%20Ind%C3%BAstria%20Brasileira%20de%20Frutas%20-%202006.doc |title=A Ind\u00fastria Brasileira das Frutas \u2013 Amplia\u00e7\u00e3o e Conquista de Mercados |language=Portuguese |website= |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706161306/http://www.redetec.org.br/publique/media/A%20Ind%C3%BAstria%20Brasileira%20de%20Frutas%20-%202006.doc |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Brazilian Agency for the Promotion of Exports and Investments (Apex-Brasil), the IBRAF and [[Carrefour]] supermarket partnered to develop the Brazilian Fruit Festival, with editions in countries such as [[Poland]] and [[Portugal]], from 2004 to 2007.<ref name=iai/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brazilianfruit.org.br/brazilian_fruit_festival/brazilian_fruit_festival.asp |title=Programa Horizontal de Promo\u00e7\u00e3o das Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es Brasileiras |language=Portuguese |work=p\u00e1gina oficial do Brazilian Fruit Festival |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612192040/http://www.brazilianfruit.org.br/brazilian_fruit_festival/brazilian_fruit_festival.asp |archivedate=12 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Banana ====\n[[File:Musa 031.jpg|thumb|Banana plantation in irrigation project, Rio S. Francisco, Bahia.]]\n\n[[Banana]] is produced across the country.<ref name=emb3/> It is the second-largest fruit crop. In 2003, 510 thousand hectares were planted, yielding 6.5 million tons, repeated in 2004.<ref name=\"iai\" /> In descending order, the largest producers were S\u00e3o Paulo (with one million one hundred seventy-eight thousand tons), Bahia (764 thousand tons) and Par\u00e1 (697 thousand tons).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0100-29452005000100037&script=sci_arttext |title=Nehmi et al., 2003, citados em \"An\u00e1lises t\u00e9cnica e econ\u00f4mica da cultura da bananeira 'Ma\u00e7\u00e3' (Musa spp.) na regi\u00e3o noroeste do Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo\". |language=Portuguese |author=ALMEIDA, Mariley de Castro Almeida da |author2=TARSITANO, Maria Aparecida Anselmo |author3=BOLIANI, Aparecida Concei\u00e7\u00e3o |work=Revista Brasileira de Fruticultura, vol. 27, n\u00ba 1, Jaboticabal |date=April 2005 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514151608/http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0100-29452005000100037&script=sci_arttext |archivedate=14 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Cocoa ====\n[[File:Cacao.jpeg|thumb|Cocoa plant in Ilheus, Bahia.]]\n\nCocoa was once one of Brazil's main export crops, particularly for Bahia. Production gradually diminished. In 2002 Bahia accounted for 84% of Brazil's cocoa, according to IBGE, planting more than 548 thousand hectares planted with the crop.<ref name=cacao>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpatc.embrapa.br/publicacoes_2004/doc-72.pdf |title=Import\u00e2ncia Econ\u00f4mica e Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o da Cultura do Cacau no Brasil e na Regi\u00e3o dos Tabuleiros Costeiros da Bahia entre 1990 e 2002. |language=Portuguese |author1=CUENCA, Manuel Alberto Guti\u00e9rrez |author2=NAZ\u00c1RIO, Cristiano Campos |work=Documentos / Embrapa Tabuleiros Costeiros, Aracaju, 25 p. : il. |date=2004 |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122180008/http://www.cpatc.embrapa.br/publicacoes_2004/doc-72.pdf |archivedate=22 November 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil changed from exporting to importing cocoa in 1992. According to FAO the country, between 1990 and 2003, fell from ninth to seventeenth in the main world producers' ranking.<ref name=cacao/>\n\nBahian cocoa shows how a pest and the lack of plant health care may affect a crop. In this case a disease called [[witch's broom]] was directly responsible for falling production, which started in the year 1989.<ref name=ceplac1>{{cite web |url=http://www.ceplac.gov.br/radar/mercado_cacau.htm |title=Mercado de Cacau. |language=Portuguese |author=Antonio C\u00e9sar Costa Zugaib |author2=Almir Martins dos Santos |author3=Lindolfo Pereira dos Santos Filho |website= |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402071808/http://www.ceplac.gov.br/radar/mercado_cacau.htm |archivedate=2 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A severe decline endured until 1999, when resistant varieties were introduced. Despite this, in 2007 Bahian production started to decline again, whilst the Paraense raised its share.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagri.ba.gov.br/noticias.asp?qact=view&notid=11201 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de cacau recua 68% |language=Portuguese |author=Seagri |website= |date=15 August 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706155527/http://www.seagri.ba.gov.br/noticias.asp?qact=view&notid=11201 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecoviagem.uol.com.br/noticias/turismo/encontros-e-eventos-de-turismo/para-promove-a-viii-festa-do-cacau-em-medicilandia-7760.asp |title=Par\u00e1 promove a VIII Festa do Cacau em Medicil\u00e2ndia |language=Portuguese |author=Ecoviagem |website= |date=16 November 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706154943/http://ecoviagem.uol.com.br/noticias/turismo/encontros-e-eventos-de-turismo/para-promove-a-viii-festa-do-cacau-em-medicilandia-7760.asp |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Citrus ====\n[[File:Laranjal Cutrale 050806 REFON 3.jpg|thumb|Orange field, in S. Paulo]]\n\n[[Citrus]] includes oranges, [[Lime (fruit)|lime]]s, [[tangerine]]s, lemons, etc. Oranges are the most relevant in agriculture.<ref name=iaclar>{{cite web |url=http://www.iac.sp.gov.br/Tecnologias/Citros/Citros.htm |title=CITROS: principais informa\u00e7\u00f5es e recomenda\u00e7\u00f5es de cultivo |language=Portuguese |authors=Dirceu de Mattos Junior, Jos\u00e9 Dagoberto De Negri, Jos\u00e9 Orlando de Figueiredo e Jorgino Pompeu Junior |work=IAC |date=26 April 2005 |accessdate=12 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426082641/http://www.iac.sp.gov.br/Tecnologias/Citros/Citros.htm |archivedate=26 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 Brazil produced 18.3 million tons of oranges, 45% of the fruit harvest.<ref name=iai/>\n\nS\u00e3o Paulo state accounts for 79% of orange production and is the largest producer and exporter of [[orange juice]], responsible for half of global production. 97% is exported.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=259 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o Agr\u00edcola Municipal \u2013 2003 |language=Portuguese |author=IBGE |work=Not\u00edcia: Milho tem maior aumento, mas soja continua em primeiro lugar no ranking da produ\u00e7\u00e3o agr\u00edcola brasileira de 2003 |date= |accessdate=12 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516221040/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=259 |archivedate=16 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil and the US are the world's largest citrus producers, with 45% of the total, while South Africa, Spain and [[Israel]] compete in oranges and tangerines.<ref name=iaclar/>\n\nBrazilian orange juice is equivalent to 80% of world exports, the largest market share for any Brazilian agricultural product.<ref name=\"estadao\" />\n\n=== Forestry and wood ===\n\n[[File:Fazenda pinus.JPG|thumb|Pine plantation for cellulose production, Bocaina do Sul, Santa Catarina.]]\n\nCommercial forestry produced 65% of Brazilian wood products in 2003, up from 52% the year earlier as it gradually replaced traditional gathering.<ref name=ibgemad/>\n\n[[Eucalyptus]] is the most popular species for reforestation. It is harvested for [[plywood]] and [[cellulose]] production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ipef.br/publicacoes/scientia/nr20/cap05.pdf |title=Crescimento e Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Madeira de Eucalipto |language=Portuguese |authors=SIM\u00d5ES, Jo\u00e3o Walter. et allii |work=IPEF n.20, p. 77\u201397 |date=June 1980 |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728115548/http://www.ipef.br/publicacoes/scientia/nr20/cap05.pdf |archivedate=28 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2001 the country cultivated three million hectares with this tree; another 1.8 million hectares were planted with [[pine]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbs.org.br/setor_florestal.htm |title=Setor Florestal Brasileiro, dados socio-econ\u00f4micos |language=Portuguese |author=Sociedade Brasileira de Silvicultura |website= |date=2001 |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090906185658/http://www.sbs.org.br/setor_florestal.htm |archivedate=6 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> a species better adapted to the climate of the South and Southeast.<ref name=hist>{{cite web |url=http://www.almg.gov.br/Publicacoes/Eucalipto/brasil_minas.pdf |title=O Eucalipto no Brasil |language=Portuguese |work=Publica\u00e7\u00f5es; ALMG (institucional) |date= |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922113910/http://www.almg.gov.br/Publicacoes/Eucalipto/brasil_minas.pdf |archivedate=22 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nNative species have received increasing attention as an alternative to eucalyptus and pine. In 2007, the National Plan of Forestry with Native Species and Agroforestry Systems (PENSAF) was launched, in an integrated effort between the [[Ministry of the Environment (Brazil)|Ministry of the Environment]] (MMA) and the [[Ministry of Agriculture (Brazil)|Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock and Food Supply]] (MAPA), among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ideflor.pa.gov.br/files/u1/Plano_Nacional_de_Silvicultura.pdf|title=Ideflor-bio|author=|date=|website=Ideflor-bio|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205083633/http://www.ideflor.pa.gov.br/files/u1/Plano_Nacional_de_Silvicultura.pdf|archivedate=5 December 2014|df=dmy-all|access-date=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 the country produced 2.149 million tons of wood for [[charcoal]]; 75% from Minas Gerais. Charcoal from vegetable gathering added 2.227 million tons, the largest part (35%) from Par\u00e1. Firewood production occupied 47.232 million square meters, with Bahia the biggest producer.<ref name=ibgemad/>\n\nBrazil is the seventh largest global producer of cellulose of all kinds, and the largest of short fiber cellulose. In 2005 the country exported 5.2 million tons and produced 6 million, generating revenues of 3.4 billion dollars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://noticias.qprocura.com.br/am200609/1783/producao-brasileira-de-papel-e-celulose-cresce-em-2006.html |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o brasileira de papel e celulose cresce em 2006 |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |work=QProcura |date=23 September 2006 |accessdate=14 October 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the Management of Public Forests Law was enacted. It subsidizes legal wood production to reduce illegal deforestation, and encouraging the timber sector to adopt sustainable practices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greenpeace.org/brasil/pt/Noticias/lula-sanciona-lei-que-estimula/ |title=Lula sanciona lei que estimula produ\u00e7\u00e3o de madeira legal e a presen\u00e7a do Estado na Amaz\u00f4nia |language=Portuguese |work=Greenpeace |date=3 March 2006 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728035533/http://www.greenpeace.org/brasil/pt/Noticias/lula-sanciona-lei-que-estimula/ |archivedate=28 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Vegetables ===\n\n[[File:Horticulture in Almirante Tamandar\u00e9 countryside.JPG|thumb|Horticulture in Almirante Tamandar\u00e9 countryside.]]\n\nBrazilian vegetable production in 2004 was estimated at 11.696 billion [[Reais]]. It occupied 176 thousand hectares, yielding 16.86 million tons. The major producing regions were the South and Southeast, with 75% of the total. This sector employs between eight and ten million workers.<ref name=horta>{{cite web |url=http://www.abhorticultura.com.br/Biblioteca/Default.asp?id=4925 |title=Panorama Atual da Cadeia de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Hortali\u00e7as no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Paulo C\u00e9sar Tavares de Melo |work=palestra |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150613/http://www.abhorticultura.com.br/Biblioteca/Default.asp?id=4925 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe vegetable section of Embrapa, with headquarters in Distrito Federal, was created in 1978 and in 1981 renamed the National Center of Research on Vegetables (CNPH).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/historico.htm |title=Hist\u00f3rico, Embrapa Hortali\u00e7as |language=Portuguese |author=institucional |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091211214338/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/historico.htm |archivedate=11 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It occupies 487 ha with laboratories, administrative and support buildings, with 45 ha devoted to experimental vegetable production, of which 7 support organic production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/instalacoes.htm |title=Instala\u00e7\u00f5es, Embrapa Hortali\u00e7as |language=Portuguese |work=institucional |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215111033/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/instalacoes.htm |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Brazil exported 366,213 tons of vegetable crops, which yielded 240 million dollars. Among these, thirteen thousand tons of potatoes, twenty thousand tons of tomatoes, 37 thousand tons of onions. Other export vegetables included [[ginger]], [[pea]]s, [[cucumber]]s, [[capsicum]], [[Mustard plant|mustard]], carrots and garlic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/hortalicas_em_numeros/exportacoes_brasileiras_hortalicas_2000_2007.pdf |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es Brasileiras de Hortali\u00e7as, 2000\u20132007, dados, Embrapa |language=Portuguese |work=institucional |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209101627/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/hortalicas_em_numeros/exportacoes_brasileiras_hortalicas_2000_2007.pdf |archivedate=9 December 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Tomato ====\n[[File:Planta\u00e7\u00e3o tomate 250306 2.JPG|thumb|Tomato plantation, Arandu]]\n\nBrazilian tomato production ranked sixth globally and first in South America in 2000. 1999 output reached a record of 1.29 million tons for tomato pulp.<ref name=tometeemb>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpafro.embrapa.br/embrapa/Artigos/tomateiro.htm |title=O tomateiro tipo industrial no Brasil. |language=Portuguese |authors=CARVALHO, Jos\u00e9 Orestes M. et allii., Embrapa |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215075058/http://www.cpafro.embrapa.br/embrapa/Artigos/tomateiro.htm |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, production increased to 3.3 million tons, ranking ninth globally behind China, US, [[Turkey]], Italy, [[Egypt]], [[India]], Spain and [[Iran]]. The largest states in 2004 were Goi\u00e1s (871 thousand tons), S\u00e3o Paulo (749 thousand tons), Minas Gerais (622 thousand), Rio de Janeiro (203 thousand) and Bahia (193 thousand).<ref name=tomate>{{cite web |url=http://www.conab.gov.br/conabweb/download/cas/especiais/Tomate_21_08_2006.pdf |title=A Cultura do Tomate. |language=Portuguese |author=CHAVES, Alex Musialowski. |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923210059/http://www.conab.gov.br/conabweb/download/cas/especiais/Tomate_21_08_2006.pdf |archivedate=23 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSuccess in Goi\u00e1s' and Minas Gerais' Cerrado allowed the region to expand from 31% to 84% of production, from 1996 to 2001. The development of localized hybrid varieties raised productivity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unicamp.br/unicamp/unicamp_hoje/ju/dezembro2004/ju276pag08.html |title=Tese de doutorado revela conflitos e interesses na produ\u00e7\u00e3o de tomate |language=Portuguese |author=not\u00edcia por Carmo Gallo Neto |work=Jornal da [[Unicamp]], ed. 276 |date=13\u201323 December 2004 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925021819/http://www.unicamp.br/unicamp/unicamp_hoje/ju/dezembro2004/ju276pag08.html |archivedate=25 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Onion ====\n[[File:Cebola roxa.JPG|thumb|Sample of red onions.]]\n\nSmall farmers are responsible for more than half of the country's production.<ref name=embceb>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/sistprod/cebola/mercado_e_comercializacao.htm |title=Sistema de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Cebola (Allium cepa L) Mercado e Comercializa\u00e7\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |authors=VILELA, Nirlene Junqueira. et allii. |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217075705/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/sistprod/cebola/mercado_e_comercializacao.htm |archivedate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Juazeiro]], in Bahia, and [[Petrolina]], in Pernambuco are neighboring towns, separated by [[S\u00e3o Francisco River]]. They have the highest yield, using irrigation to achieve 24 tons per hectare, versus the Brazilian average of seventeen.<ref name=embceb/> In 2006, the two cities 200 thousand tons surpassed that of the other states, behind only Santa Catarina (355 thousand tons).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=2240 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de cebola da Bahia e Pernambuco em 2006 ser\u00e1 a segunda maior do pa\u00eds |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa |website= |date=16 May 2006 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150802/http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=2240 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Cassava ===\n\nBrazil is the world's second largest cassava producer, at 12.7%. Exports comprise only .5%. Average exports in 2000 and 2001 were thirteen million, one hundred thousand tons, generating revenue above six hundred million dollars.<ref name=embmand>{{cite journal |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Mandioca/mandioca_cerrados/importancia.htm |series=Cultivo da Mandioca para a Regi\u00e3o do Cerrado |language=Portuguese |author1=Luciano da Silva Souza |author2=Josefino de Freitas Fialho |title=Import\u00e2ncia Econ\u00f4mida |journal=Embrapa Mandioca e Fruticultura. Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o |number=8 |issn=1678-8796 |date=January 2003 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214040834/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Mandioca/mandioca_cerrados/importancia.htm |archivedate=14 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt is cultivated in all regions and is used for both human and animal consumption. [[Manioc]] is farmed for human consumption, including flour and [[starch]]. That production chain generates about a million direct jobs,<ref name=embmand/> and some ten million jobs overall.<ref name=entmand>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.diap.org.br/index.php/agencia-diap/7854-producao-da-mandioca-gera-10-milhoes-de-empregos-diretos-e-indiretos |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o da mandioca gera 10 milh\u00f5es de empregos diretos e indiretos |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia DIAP |work=Departamento Intersindical de Assessoria Parlamentar |date=1 March 2009 |accessdate=20 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727234851/http://www.diap.org.br/index.php/agencia-diap/7854-producao-da-mandioca-gera-10-milhoes-de-empregos-diretos-e-indiretos |archivedate=27 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nForecasts for 2002 were for 22.6 million tons on 1.7 million hectares. The largest producers were Par\u00e1 (17.9%), Bahia (16.7%), Paran\u00e1 (14.5%), Rio Grande do Sul (5.6%) and Amazonas (4.3%) .<ref name=embmand/>\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== Slave and child labor ===\n\n[[File:CarvoariaIrregularByMarcoEvangelista.jpg|thumb|Inspectors from the Ministry of Labor and Federal Police officers at the scene of a clandestine charcoal operation, places where most illegal working situations occur.]]\n\nAccording to data from the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor of the United States]], twenty-first century Brazil ranks third in occurrences of illegal working arrangements (tied with [[India]] and [[Bangladesh]]). Eight of thirteen violations were prevalent in agribusiness, especially in livestock, [[sisal]], sugar cane, rice, tobacco and charcoal. Despite its position, the country's performance was praised, and between 1995 and 2009 approximately 35,000 workers were freed from degrading conditions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=1&local=1&id=2650266&action=noticias |title=Brasil \u00e9 terceiro com maior \u00edndice de trabalho escravo e infantil |language=Portuguese |last=Kohlmann |first=Luciane |work=RBS |date=11 September 2009 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090913004521/http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=1&local=1&id=2650266&action=noticias |archivedate=13 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO) recognized the Brazilian effort to fight such practices, which focus on preventing/correcting misbehavior via a system of fines.\n\nAmong the causes of illegal working arrangements were poverty and misinformation.\n\nA Constitutional Amendment Proposal (PEC), would compensate landowners for losses resulting from ending such practices.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.reporterbrasil.com.br/clipping.php?id=700 |title=OIT reconhece esfor\u00e7os do Brasil no combate ao trabalho escravo e infantil, diz ministro do TST. |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |work=Rep\u00f3rter Brasil |date=1 March 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706154243/http://www.reporterbrasil.com.br/clipping.php?id=700 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 however, the [[Bureau of International Labor Affairs]] issued a ''[[List of Goods Produced by Child Labor or Forced Labor]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dol.gov/ilab/reports/child-labor/list-of-goods/|title=List of Goods Produced by Child Labor or Forced Labor|author=|date=|website=www.dol.gov|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610003351/http://www.dol.gov/ilab/reports/child-labor/list-of-goods/|archivedate=10 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> where Brazil was classified as one of the 74 countries involved in [[child labor]] and [[forced labor]] practices. The report lists 16 products including [[cotton]], cashews, pineapples, rice and sugarcane the production of which still employs children.\n\n=== Environmental impacts ===\n{{See|Environmental issues in Brazil}}\n{{See|Deforestation in Brazil}}\n[[File:Vo\u00e7oroca (23 12 24S - 48 47 59W) - REFON 4.JPG|thumb|Gully in the state of S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nBrazil's agricultural sector and [[deforestation]] account for 75% of its gas emissions responsible for [[climate change]].<ref name=\"Brighter Green\">Mia MacDonald and Justine Simon (2010) Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change: Brazil's Agricultural Revolution. [http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 Brighter Green] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063336/http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 |date=6 June 2011 }}, 2.</ref> For this reason, initiatives were adopted to reduce emissions, mostly by reducing deforestation. The so-called \"Soybean Moratorium\", the Agroecological Zoning for Sugar Cane, and the use of [[fertigation]] are examples.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ictsd.org/i/news/pontes/57140/ |title=O papel da agricultura brasileira nas mudan\u00e7as clim\u00e1ticas |language=Portuguese |author=Luiz Fernando do Amaral |work=Pontes \u2022 Volume 5 \u2022 N\u00famero 4 |date=October 2009 |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726170939/http://ictsd.org/i/news/pontes/57140/ |archivedate=26 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil's [[greenhouse gas]] emissions from agriculture increased 41 percent between 1990 and 2005.<ref>\"Brazil Throws Out Another Climate Challenge Updating Greenhouse Gas Inventory,\" World Wildlife Fund, 27 November 2009. http://wwf.panda.org {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110813183721/http://wwf.panda.org |date=13 August 2011 }}.</ref> Cattle are a major factor. An estimate carried out by [[Friends of the Earth|Friends of the Earth-Amazonia]] ({{Interlanguage link multi|Amigos da Terra - Amaz\u00f4nia Brasileira|pt}}), the Brazilian National Institute for Space Research (INPE) and the [[University of Bras\u00edlia]] concluded that fully half came from cattle.<ref>Bustamante, Mercedes, C. Nobre, and R. Smeraldi. \"Estimating Recent Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Cattle Raising in Brazil,\" S\u00e3o Paulo: Amigos da Terra \u2013 Amaz\u00f4nia Brasileira, National Institute for Space Research, Universidad de Bras\u00edlia, 2009, 1.</ref> If all parts of the \"cattle chain\" had been included, the researchers add, an even higher proportion of greenhouse gases would have been attributed to cattle.<ref name=\"Brighter Green\"/>\n\nCattle and soy production are concentrated in the [[Legal Amazon]] and [[Cerrado]] grasslands regions, and have resulted in considerable [[biodiversity loss]], [[deforestation]] and [[water pollution]].<ref>Mia MacDonald and Justine Simon (2010) Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change: Brazil's Agricultural Revolution. [http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 Brighter Green] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063336/http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 |date=6 June 2011 }}, 1.</ref> As of 2007, about 74 million cattle, or 40 percent of Brazil's herd, were living in what is known as the \"Legal Amazon.\"<ref>Smeraldi, Roberto and Peter H. May. \"The Cattle Realm: A New Phase in the Livestock Colonization of Brazilian Amazonia,\" Highlights in English. S\u00e3o Paulo: Amigos da Terra \u2013 Amaz\u00f4nia Brasileira, 2008, 4. [http://www.amazonia.org.br www.amazonia.org.br.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115022408/http://amazonia.org.br/ |date=15 January 2011 }}</ref> Almost one million square km (386,000 sq mi), or nearly half of the [[Cerrado]], has been burned and is now cattle pasture, or is cultivated for soybeans, corn (both primary ingredients in livestock feed), and sugarcane.<ref>Simone de Lima and Justine Simon (2010) Brazil: Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change. [https://www.youtube.com/user/BrighterGreenNY#p/u/2/_X7FWuvsWi0 Brighter Green] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324211918/https://www.youtube.com/user/BrighterGreenNY |date=24 March 2017 }}, 1.</ref> According to Washington Novaes, \"if we consider the viable fragments of the Cerrado, those with at least two continuous hectares (5 acres), only 5 percent of it is left. It's a very severe level of habitat loss.\"<ref>Mia MacDonald and Justine Simon (2010) \"Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change: Brazil's Agricultural Revolution\". [http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 Brighter Green] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063336/http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 |date=6 June 2011 }}, 10.</ref> At least one quarter of Brazilian grain is grown in [[Cerrado]].\n\n==== Soil erosion ====\nA large part of the Southeast and Northeast region of the country is made up of [[granite|granitic]] and [[gneiss]] rock formations, covered by a layer of [[regolith]], very susceptible to [[soil erosion]] and [[gully]] formation. Bertoni and Neto point out this condition as one of Brazil's highest environmental dangers, and a large part of them result from human activities.<ref name=ddi>{{Cite journal |title=An\u00e1lise da erodibilidade de saprolitos de gnaisse |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=1055\u20131062 |language=Portuguese |author1=F. MoraisI |author2=L. A. P. BacellarII |author3=F. G. Sobreira |journal=Revista Brasileira de Ci\u00eancia do Solo vol.28 no.6 Vi\u00e7osa |date=Nov\u2013Dec 2004 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1590/S0100-06832004000600014 }}</ref>\n\n[[Soil erosion]] removes nutrients and causes the loss of structure, texture and the decrease of infiltration rates and water retention.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnpma.embrapa.br/analise_econ/ |title=Custos econ\u00f4micos da eros\u00e3o do solo: estimativa pelo m\u00e9todo do custo de reposi\u00e7\u00e3o de nutrientes |language=Portuguese |author1=Jo\u00e3o Fernando Marques |author2=Carlos Benjamin Pazzianotto |website= |date= |accessdate=5 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215105420/http://www.cnpma.embrapa.br/analise_econ/ |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[plough|Plowing]] and [[herbicide]]s to control undesirable weeds leave the soil exposed and susceptible to erosion \u2013 either by loss of topsoil (which is richer in nutrients), or from gullies. The lost soil fills rivers and reservoirs with [[silt]]. One solution is [[no-till farming]], a practice not in wide use.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agrisus.org.br/artigos.asp?cod=19 |title=Plantio Direto e Desenvolvimento Sustent\u00e1vel |language=Portuguese |author=Bernardo Van Raij |website= |date= |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301115817/http://www.agrisus.org.br/artigos.asp?cod=19 |archivedate=1 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Pesticide ====\nThe world's four thousand agrochemicals are produced in about 15,000 different formulations, 8,000 of which are licensed in Brazil. They include [[insecticide]]s, [[fungicide]]s, [[herbicide]]s, [[vermifuge]]s, and also [[solvent]]s and sanitizers. They are widely used to protect crops from pests, disease and invading species. Indiscriminate use causes unnecessary accumulation of those substances in the soil, water (springs, [[groundwater]], reservoirs) and air.<ref name=tudotox>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sigrh.sp.gov.br/sigrh/ARQS/RELATORIO/CRH/CBH-ALPA/1121/uso_de_agrotoxicos_na_agricultura.html |title=Uso de agrot\u00f3xicos na agricultura |language=Portuguese |author=Relatorio SIGRH-SP |website= |date= |accessdate=12 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160444/http://www.sigrh.sp.gov.br/sigrh/ARQS/RELATORIO/CRH/CBH-ALPA/1121/uso_de_agrotoxicos_na_agricultura.html |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil uses an average of 3.2&nbsp;kg of agrochemicals per hectare \u2013 ranking tenth globally, in some studies, and fifth, in others. S\u00e3o Paulo state is Brazil's largest user, and the largest producer, comprising 80% of the total. Mitigation techniques include farmer education, and the development of resistant species, better farming techniques, biological pest control, among others.<ref name=tudotox/>\n\nIn 2007 tomatoes, lettuce and strawberries showed the highest rates of contamination by agrochemicals. Farmer awareness is low and few comply with rules on the use of these substances, such as Individual Protection Equipment (EPI).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rel-uita.org/sindicatos/trabalhador_rural_agrotoxicos.htm |title=Trabalhador rural \u00e9 o mais atingido por contamina\u00e7\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=Bernardo Van Raij |website= |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727211840/http://www.rel-uita.org/sindicatos/trabalhador_rural_agrotoxicos.htm |archivedate=27 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to information from [[National Health Surveillance Agency|Anvisa]], Brazilian farming uses at least ten types of agrochemicals prohibited in other markets, such as the [[European Union]] and the US.<ref>FORMENTI, L\u00edgia. (30 de maio de 2010). \"Brasil se torna o principal destino de agrot\u00f3xicos banidos no exterior\". The State of S.Paulo</ref> In September 2019, Brazil's Agriculture Ministry approved 63 pesticides for commercial use as the government seeks to decrease a backlog of applications for new agricultural chemicals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-agriculture-pesticides-idUSKBN1W22HQ|title=Brazil clears new pesticides as government aims to speed approvals|date=2019-09-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-18|language=en}}</ref> According to an investigation by Unearthed, more than 1,200 pesticides and weedkillers, including 193 containing chemicals banned in the EU, have been registered in Brazil between 2016 and 2019.<ref>[https://unearthed.greenpeace.org/2019/06/12/jair-bolsonaro-brazil-pesticides/ Brazil pesticide approvals soar]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/jun/12/hundreds-new-pesticides-approved-brazil-under-bolsonaro Hundreds of new pesticides approved]</ref>\n\n==== Genetically modified crops ====\n{{Main|Genetically modified crops}}[[File:Manifesta\u00e7\u00e3o pro milho transg\u00eanico (Antonio Cruz) 20mar07.jpg|thumb|Brasilia, 2007: Protesters call for liberation from transgenic maize.]]\n\nThe country is the third largest user in the world in growing [[genetically modified crops]]. The main commodities using this [[biotechnology]] are soy, cotton and, since 2008, maize.<ref name=deftrans>{{Cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=28329 |title=Estudo confirma que agricultura transg\u00eanica beneficia meio ambiente no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio (not\u00edcia) |website= |date=9 February 2009 |accessdate=12 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522211134/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=28329 |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSeveral national and international [[NGOs]], such as [[Greenpeace]], [[Landless Workers' Movement|MST]] or Contag, are opposed to the practice. Criticisms include market loss, negative environmental impacts and dominance by large businesses. Entities linked to agribusiness, however, counter with the results of studies carried out by the Brazilian Association of Seeds and Saplings (Abrasem) in 2007 and 2008, affirming \"social-environmental advantages observed in the other countries which have adopted agricultural biotechnology far longer\".<ref name=deftrans/>\n\nFederal Justice decided that foods containing more than 1 percent of modified genes must be labeled to inform consumers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.direito2.com.br/abr/2007/nov/30/consumo-consciente-de-informacoes |title=Consumo consciente de informa\u00e7\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |website= |date=30 November 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519223339/http://www.direito2.com.br/abr/2007/nov/30/consumo-consciente-de-informacoes |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Future risks for agriculture and environment ====\nThe deforestation of the Amazon Rainforest has many negative impacts, among others, on the Agriculture in Brazil who is one of those who promote the deforestation. One of the problems is that in some point the deforestation can reach a tipping point after which it will continue by itself and can not be stopped. This is because half of the rain of the forest is produced by the forest so, when there is less forest there is less rain what harm the forest. It is difficult to say when exactly it will be passed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=A. Nobre |first1=Carlos |last2=Sampaio |first2=Gilvan |last3=Borma |first3=Laura |last4=Carlos Castilla-Rubio |first4=Juan |last5=S. Silva |first5=Jos\u00e9 |last6=Cardoso |first6=Manoel |title=Land-use and climate change risks in the Amazon and the need of a novel sustainable development paradigm |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=113 |issue=39 |pages=10759\u201310768 |date=27 September 2016 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1605516113 |pmid=27638214 |pmc=5047175 |bibcode=2016PNAS..11310759N }}</ref>\n\n===== Impacts on water supply =====\nThe Amazon river basin alone, which covers 48% of the country's territory, accounts for 75% of Brazil's freshwater resources.<ref name=\"alto tiete, p.8\">Formiga Johnson ''et al.'' (June 2005), ''op. cit.'', p.8</ref> The deforestation of the Amazon rainforest has big impacts on the freshwater supply of [[Brazil]]. This harm among others, the agriculture in Brazil which is one of those who promote the deforestation. In the future, it can impact more severely, water supply in Brazil and to other countries: [[Uruguay]], [[Argentina]], [[Paraguay]] and the [[United States]]. This is for two causes:\n\n1. The rainforest provides much of the rainfall in [[Brazil]] even in areas far from it. Deforestation, have already increased the impacts of the droughts of 2005, 2010, and [[2014\u201317 Brazilian drought]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=WELCH |first1=CRAIG |title=How Amazon forest loss may affect water\u2014and climate\u2014far away |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2018/11/how-cutting-the-amazon-forest-could-affect-weather/ |website=National Geographic Society |publisher=National Geographic Society |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n2. The rainforest by inducing rainfall and helping water storage provide water to the rivers that give water to Brazil and others countries.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Joe |last2=Sanchez |first2=Erica |title=World's Water Could Become Scarce if the Amazon Rainforest Is Destroyed |url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/amazon-rainforest-water-crisis/ |website=Global Citizen |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Larson |first1=Christina |last2=Savarese |first2=Mauricio |title=Scientists warn new Brazil president may smother rainforest |url=https://phys.org/news/2018-11-scientists-brazil-smother-rainforest.html |website=Fhys.org |publisher=Science X Network |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Amazon rainforest create 50-75 percent of its own precipitation. It supllies water well beyond the Amazon Basin: Amazon rainfall and rivers feeding regions that generate 70 percent of South America's GDP. Models indicate that moisture from the Amazon influences rainfall as far away as the Western United States and Central America.<ref>{{cite web |last1=A. Butler |first1=Rhett |title=The Importance of the Amazon Rainforest |url=https://rainforests.mongabay.com/amazon/amazon_importance.htm |website=Mongabay |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[2014\u201317 Brazilian drought]] have a big impact on the agriculture in Brazil. \"The Agricultural Economy Institute\" stated that 2014 accounted for S\u00e3o Paulo's worst agricultural losses in half a century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.as-coa.org/articles/brazil-update-historic-drought-takes-toll-agriculture|title=Brazil Update: Historic Drought Takes Toll on Agriculture|last=Glickhouse|first=Rachel|website=AS/COA|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nThe irregular rainfall pattern contributed to a reduction in crop production through the drought period, due to an atmospheric blockage which prevented a cold front from advancing over key crop regions in Brazil, the world's largest exporter of coffee, sugar, soy and beef. In 2014 the drought wiped out a third of the country's coffee crop in some areas, which caused global [[Coffea arabica|coffee arabica]] prices to rise 50% over the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wfo-oma.org/news/the-effects-of-drought-in-brazil.html|title=The effects of drought in Brazil|last=Generale|first=O. M. A.|website=www.wfo-oma.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> In 2015 coffee trees had not recovered from the extreme heat and drought quick enough, triggering another arabica price rally. Crop production of soy, one of the country's largest export crops, decreased by 17% during the drought.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/brazil-water-supply-crops-still-at-risk-a-year-after-epic-drought/|title=Brazil Water Supply, Crops Still at Risk a Year after Epic Drought|website=Scientific American|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> <br />The Cemaden's Rain Monitoring System showed that severe droughts were observed \u00a0in the states of [[Mato Grosso]] and [[Mato Grosso do Sul]], they are both the largest regions for [[soybean]] production and fourth-largest beef producers in Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brazilian.report/money/2018/07/24/brazil-agribusiness-drought-season/|title=Brazil's agribusiness to suffer from worst drought season|date=2018-07-24|website=The Brazilian Report|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\n===== Impact on local temperature =====\nIn 2019 a group of scientists published a research who says that in \"Business as usual\" scenario the deforestation of the Amazon Rainforest will raise the temperature in Brazil by 0.11 degree in average, while in many places the rise will be up to 1.45 degree. The scientists claim that: \" Increased temperatures in already hot locations may increase [[Mortality rate|human mortality rates]] and [[electricity demand]]s, reduce [[agricultural yield]]s and [[water resources]], and contribute to [[Biodiversity|biodiversity collapse]], particularly in tropical regions . Furthermore, local warming may cause shifts in species distributions , including for species involved in [[Infectious Disease|infectious disease transmissions]] .\" The authors of the paper also say that deforestation is already causing a rise in the temperature.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=A. Prevedello |first1=Jayme |last2=R. Winck |first2=Gisele |last3=M. Weber |first3=Marcelo |last4=Nichols |first4=Elizabeth |last5=Sinervo |first5=Barry |title=Impacts of forestation and deforestation on local temperature across the globe |journal=PLOS One|volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=e0213368 |date=20 March 2019 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0213368 |pmid=30893352 |pmc=6426338 |bibcode=2019PLoSO..1413368P }}</ref>\n\n===== Impact on genetic diversity =====\nThe Amazon rainforest is a source of essential genes for crops, livestock, pollination, biological control, cleaning water and [[soil regeneration]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quevedo |first1=Lincoln |title=THE AMAZON FOREST IS DISAPPEARING |url=http://www.deborahhealey.com/s60/lincoln.html |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Possible solutions ====\n===== Organic farming =====\n\n[[File:P\u00e9 de berinjela.jpg|thumb|Organic cultivation of eggplant.]]\n\n[[Organic farming]] aims to produce food without the use of synthetic fertilizers, pesticides or other agrochemicals.<ref>Paull, John (2016) [https://www.academia.edu/26803383/Organics_Olympiad_2016_Global_Indices_of_Leadership_in_Organic_Agriculture Organics Olympiad 2016: Global Indices of Leadership in Organic Agriculture] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112005847/http://www.academia.edu/26803383/Organics_Olympiad_2016_Global_Indices_of_Leadership_in_Organic_Agriculture |date=12 November 2017 }}, Journal of Social and Development Sciences. 7(2):79-87</ref> The IBGE's 2006 Agricultural Census reported the existence of ninety thousand organic farms in Brazil, comprising 2% of the total; however, only 5,106 are certified.<ref name=orgbr>{{cite journal | authorlink = Fabricia Resende; Ticyana Banzato, orgs. | title = Org\u00e2nicos: Brasil j\u00e1 possui 90 mil estabelecimentos que declaram praticar agricultura org\u00e2nica, segundo IBGE | journal = Hortifruti Brasil | number = 85 | publisher = CEPEA ESALQ/USP | volume = 8 | location = Piracicaba | pages = 6\u201317 | date = November 2009 | language = Portuguese | url = http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/hfbrasil |url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140719215915/http://cepea.esalq.usp.br/hfbrasil/ | archivedate = 19 July 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOrganics are present mostly in small and medium properties. The majority of producers are organized in associations or cooperatives. The state with the largest number of producers is Bahia (223), followed by Minas Gerais (192), S\u00e3o Paulo (86), Rio Grande do Sul (83), Paran\u00e1 (79), Esp\u00edrito Santo (64) and others.<ref name=orgbr/>\n\nThe Brazil Organics program, constituted in 2005, promotes the sector.<ref name=orgbr/>\n\nBrazil is the twenty-largest exporter in the world, according to data from the Ministry of Development, Industry and Foreign Trade in a\u00e7ai, cacha\u00e7a, cattle, nuts, melons, guaran\u00e1, and beef.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===== Sustainable agriculture =====\nOne possible solution is sustainable farming in the Amazonas Rainforest<ref>{{cite web |last1=ZIENCHUK |first1=JUDI |title=Sustainable Farming In The Amazon Rainforest |url=https://epicureandculture.com/sustainable-farming-in-the-amazon-rainforest/ |website=Epicure & Culture |accessdate=3 May 2019|date=20 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Economy of Brazil}}\n\n{{Brazil topics}}\n\n{{South America topic|Agriculture in}}\n\n[[Category:Agriculture in Brazil| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Major economic sector in Brazil}}\n{{Update|date = November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox\n| abovestyle  = background:lightblue\n| headerstyle = background:lightblue\n| above       = Agriculture in [[Brazil]]\n| image1      = [[File:Brasil celeiro.png|300px]]\n| caption1    = Brazil, \"breadbasket of the world\"<ref>Expression coined during the [[Vargas Era]]</ref>\n| image2      = {{flagicon|Brazil|size=100px}}\n| label1      = Area cultivated\n| data1       = 65,338,804 ha.<ref name=\"ibge08\">Thais Leit\u00e3o (ABr) (17 October 2009). [http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/212125.htm \"Produ\u00e7\u00e3o agr\u00edcola brasileira registrar recorded em 2008 com alta de 9,1%.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725071250/http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/212125.htm |date=25 July 2014 }} \u2013 in Portuguese. Paged visited on 30 March 2014.</ref>\n| label2      = Cropland (% of land area)\n| data2       = 31%\n| label3      = Rural population\n| data3       = 5,965,000 families\n| label4      = Main products\n| data4       = sugarcane, coffee, soybeans, corn.\n| header5     = Production\n| label6      = Grains (2008)\n| data6       = 145.4 million tons<ref name=ibge08/>\n| header7     = Major products\n| label8      = Cane and derivatives (2007/08)\n| data8       = 493.4 million tons\n| label9      = Soy (2008)\n| data9       = 59.2 million tons<ref name=ibge08/>\n| label10     = Corn (2008)\n| data10      = 58.9 million tons<ref name=ibge08/>\n| header11    = Participation in the [[Economy of Brazil|economy]] \u2013 2008\n| label12     = Crop value\n| data12      = R$148.4 billion ($65.56 bil. USD)<ref name=ibge08/>\n| label13     = Contribution to GDP\n| data13      = 4.53%<ref name=cepea>CEPEA/USP/CNA Data [http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/pib/ download] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401225352/http://cepea.esalq.usp.br/pib/ |date=1 April 2014 }}, \u2013 in Portuguese. Searched 18 October 2009.</ref>\n| label14     = Agribusiness GDP (Rural industry and trade, livestock and agriculture)\n| data14      = 26.46%<ref name=cepea/>\n}}\nThe '''agriculture of Brazil''' is historically one of the principal bases of [[Economy of Brazil|Brazil's economy]].  While its initial focus was on [[sugarcane]], Brazil eventually became the world's largest exporter of coffee, [[soybeans]], beef, and crop-based [[ethanol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/148928/page/2|title=Brazil Surges Ahead with Commodities Wealth - Newsweek International Edition - Newsweek.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|author=|date=|website=newsweek.com|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807041819/http://www.newsweek.com/id/148928/page/2|archivedate=7 August 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBrazil exported 41,000 tons of processed cashew nuts valued at US$193,900 in 2018.<ref>thebrazilbusiness.com/article/fruit-market-in-brazil</ref>\n\nThe success of agriculture during the [[Vargas Era|Estado Novo]] (New State), with [[Get\u00falio Vargas]], led to the expression, \"Brazil, breadbasket of the world\".<ref name=cc>{{cite magazine | authorlink = Felipe Seibel | title = O novo salto do agroneg\u00f3cio | magazine = [[Exame (magazine)|Exame]] | date = 14 June 2007 | language = Portuguese | url = http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0895/m0131023.html | accessdate = 5 March 2009 |url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080526161346/http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0895/m0131023.html | archivedate = 26 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2009, Brazil had about {{convert|106000000|ha}} of undeveloped fertile land \u2013 a territory larger than the combined area of France and Spain.<ref name=\"veja04\">{{cite magazine | authorlink = Alexandre Secco | title = O tamanho do Brasil que p\u00f5e a mesa | magazine = [[Veja (magazine)|Veja]] | issue = 1843 | page = 78 | publisher = Abril | date = 3 March 2004 | language = Portuguese | url = http://veja.abril.com.br/030304/p_078.html | accessdate = 18 October 2009 |url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090331042823/http://veja.abril.com.br/030304/p_078.html | archivedate = 31 March 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2008 [[IBGE]] study, despite the [[Great Recession|world financial crisis]], Brazil had record agricultural production, with growth of 9.1%, principally motivated by favorable weather.  The production of grains in the year reached an unprecedented 145,400,000 tons.<ref name=\"ibge08\" /> That record output employed an additional 4.8% in planted area, totalling 65,338,000 hectares and producing $148 billion Reals.  The principal products were corn (13.1% growth) and soy (2.4% growth).<ref name=ibge08/>\n\nThe southern one-half to two-thirds of Brazil has a semi-temperate climate, higher rainfall, more fertile soil, more advanced technology and input use, adequate infrastructure and more experienced farmers.  This region produces most of Brazil's grains, [[oilseeds]] (and exports).\n\nThe drought-ridden northeast region and Amazon basin lack well-distributed rainfall, good soil, adequate infrastructure and development capital. Although mostly occupied by subsistence farmers, both regions are increasingly important as exporters of forest products, cocoa and tropical fruits. Central Brazil contains substantial areas of [[grassland]].  Brazilian grasslands are far less fertile than those of North America, and are generally suited only for grazing.\n\nAgriculture in Brazil presents challenges, including the ongoing practice of [[slave labour]],<ref>[http://www.oit.org.br/trabalho_forcado/ ''Combating Forced Labour'', ILO Programme (United Nations)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706161239/http://www.oit.org.br/trabalho_forcado/ |date=6 July 2011 }} \u2013 in Portuguese</ref><ref>Le Breton, B. (2003). ''Trapped: modern-day slavery in the Brazilian Amazon''. Kumarian Press. {{ISBN|1-56549-155-6}}</ref> [[Land reform|agrarian reform]], fire, production financing, and a rural exodus fueled by economic stress on family farming.\n\nHalf of Brazil is covered by forests.  The world's largest [[rain forest]] is in the Amazon Basin.  Migrations into the Amazon and large-scale forest burning have challenged the government's management capabilities.  The [[Lula da Silva|Lula]] administration reduced incentives for such activity and implemented a broader environmental plan.<code><nowiki>{{Citation needed|reason=</nowiki>''Needs reliable source on how the supposed implementation happened.''<nowiki>|date=September 2019}}</nowiki></code>It also adopted an Environmental Crimes Law that established serious penalties for infractions.\n\nSince 1985, 1772 activists for agrarian reform were murdered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bastamag.net/Le-Bresil-risque-de-subir-l-une-des-plus-grandes-regressions-ecologiques-et|title=Le Br\u00e9sil risque de subir l'une des plus grandes r\u00e9gressions \u00e9cologiques et sociales de son histoire|first=Laurent|last=Delcourt|date=|website=Basta !|url-status = live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170731215540/https://www.bastamag.net/Le-Bresil-risque-de-subir-l-une-des-plus-grandes-regressions-ecologiques-et|archivedate=31 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBrazil is now working towards more development in 2019.\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Brazil}}{{quotation|However, the air of the country is very healthful, fresh, and as temperate as that of Entre Douro e Minho, we have found the two climates alike at this season. There is great plenty, an infinitude of waters. The country is so well-favoured that if it were rightly cultivated it would yield everything, because of its waters.<ref>{{cite book| authorlink =Henrique Campos Sim\u00f5es| title =The Letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha| publisher =Temple University| page =10| url =http://isc.temple.edu/evanson/LASC050/Readings/PeroVaz.pdf|url-status = dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120528200117/http://isc.temple.edu/evanson/LASC050/Readings/PeroVaz.pdf| archivedate =28 May 2012| df =dmy-all| access-date =2 April 2014}}</ref>|2=[[Pero Vaz de Caminha]]|3=[[Carta de P\u00earo Vaz de Caminha]]|4=[[s:Carta a El Rei D. Manuel (ortografia atualizada)|Full text on Wikisource \u2013 in Portuguese]] }}\n\n=== Early farming ===\n\n[[File:Brazilian Fruits.jpg|thumb|Brazilian fruits in a painting by [[Albert Eckhout]].]]\nBrazilians (\"Indians\") began farming some 12,000 years ago. They farmed [[cassava]], peanuts, tobacco, [[sweet potato]]es and maize, in addition to extracting the essence from other local plants such as the [[Caryocar brasiliense|pequi]] and the [[Attalea speciosa|babassu]]. Production was for food, [[straw]] or [[madeira]].  They cultivated local fruits such as [[jabuticaba]], [[cashew]]s, [[Spondias mombin]] and [[Goiaba]]s.\n\nThe Indians both influenced and were influenced by the Europeans who arrived in the fifteenth century. The Portuguese \"nourished themselves with wood-flour, slaughtered the big game to eat, packed their nets and imitated the rough, free life\" in the words of Pedro Calmon.<ref>CALMON, Pedro: ''Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil'', S\u00e3o Paulo, 1939, vol. 1</ref>\n\nUntil other crops began to be exported, [[brazilwood]] was the main reason Portugal wanted control in Brazil.<ref>{{cite book | last = ARRUDA | first = Jos\u00e9 Jobson  | title = Hist\u00f3ria Integrada: da Idade M\u00e9dia ao nascimento do mundo moderno  | edition = 2\u00aa | year = 1996 | publisher = [[editora \u00c1tica|\u00c1tica]] | place = S\u00e3o Paulo | isbn = 85-08-05399-1 | pages = 126, 129  | chapter = Cap. 21 \u2013 ''Os primeiros tempos: a explora\u00e7\u00e3o do pau-brasil'' | quote = Foi com o objetivo de explorar o com\u00e9rcio dessa madeira que os portugueses fundaram uma s\u00e9rie de benfeitorias(...) Os europeus dependiam dos \u00edndios para a extra\u00e7\u00e3o das madeiras(...) A partir de 1530 a crise do com\u00e9rcio de especiarias... for\u00e7aram Portugal a ocupar definitivamente(...)}}</ref>\n\n==== Fires ====\n[[File:Queimada ABr 02.jpg|thumb|Fires are one of the problems still present in Brazilian agriculture.]]\nOne practice of indigenous Brazilians was to clear land for cultivation by burning it. This provided arable land and ashes for use as fertilizer and soil cover.\n\nScholars such as [[Monteiro Lobato]] considered this practice to be harmful. However, burning only became a problem when the Europeans adopted the practice aggressively around 1500, divided land into farms, began monocropping, etc. The combination of burning with these new farming methods decimated native flora.<ref name=aa>{{cite journal |title=O uso do fogo: o manejo ind\u00edgena e a piromania da monocultura |volume=14 |issue=40 |pages=231\u2013250 |language=pt |author=Leonel, Mauro |journal=Estudos Avan\u00e7ados |date=Sep\u2013Dec 2000 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1590/S0103-40142000000300019 |doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nIndian land management included garden areas in locations selected to allow interaction with their surroundings. Indians conserved the environment in exchange for hunting the animals and protecting themselves against pests.  This approach was lost, as [[Darcy Ribeiro]] stated, \"Thus they passed millennia, until they came up against the armed agents of our civilization, with their capacity to attack and mortally wound the miraculous balance achieved by those complex lifeforms''.\"''<ref name=aa/>\n\n=== Colonial Brazil: sugarcane ===\n\n[[File:Guilherme Piso engenho 1648.jpg|thumb|Sugar attracted the colonizer who brought slaves from Africa, and it led to invasion of the territory.<br />The picture depicts a Dutch sugar mill in the work [[Historia Naturalis Brasiliae]], 1648.]]\n\nThe discovery of sugarcane in the Northeast region transformed Brazil. [[Sugar plantations in the Caribbean|Plantation]] monoculture enriched the Europeans, but brought little benefit to Brazilians.<ref name=bb>BAER, Werner: ''A Economia Brasileira'', Nobel, S\u00e3o Paulo, 2nd ed, 2003, {{ISBN|85-213-1197-4}}, {{ISBN|978-85-213-1197-3}}</ref>\n\nSugarcane wealth was concentrated under the colonizers, generating a [[feudalism|quasi-feudal]] social system organized around large landholdings. Brazilian sugar was thirty percent less expensive than sugar from elsewhere, creating major export opportunities.\n\nA decline in the second half of the 17th century led many producer regions to diversify production, expanding cotton or, in [[Ba\u00eda de Todos os Santos|Reconcavo Baiano]], tobacco or cocoa. The archaic social structure and obsolete technology outlasted cane production in those regions.<ref name=bb/>\n\n==== Slave labor ====\n{{Main|Slavery in Brazil}}[[File:Jos\u00e9 Mariano da Conceicao Velloso - O fazendeiro do Brazil - cultivador.jpg|thumb|In the illustration of \"O Fazendeiro do Brasil\" (The Farmer in Brazil), 1806, [[Jos\u00e9 Mariano da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o Veloso]] describes the steps and tools used in the cultivation of indigo in Brazil.]]\n\nInitially, plantation owners attempted to use local labor in their fields. While laws prohibited their enslavement, in many areas the law was not respected. Locals responded by rebelling, flight or simply dying. European diseases took a heavy toll on indigenous peoples.\n\nThe settlers then switched to enslaving and importing Africans to do the work.<ref name=\"hh\">SILVA, Joaquim, PENNA, J. B. Damasco: ''Hist\u00f3ria Geral'', Cia. Editora Nacional, S\u00e3o Paulo, 1972</ref> The Portuguese and others imported 4 million Africans to carry out cultivation, using what came to be called the [[plantation economy|plantation system]].\n\nIn the first century, after European arrival the slave population had already surpassed that of the locals, decimated by disease. Antonil stated: \"the slaves are the hands and feet of the mill, because without them in Brazil, it is not possible to make, maintain or expand the farm or have a running mill.\"<ref name=\"hh\" />\n\nThe slaves cleared the agricultural frontiers, such as in the west for coffee [[plantation]]s. By the end of the Second Reign, Brazil accounted for more than half the world's coffee production.<ref name=\"hh\" />\n\nOn 13 May 1888 Brazil adopted the [[Lei \u00c1urea]] ('Golden Law'), which abolished slavery in Brazil. In the preceding years, 75% of the Africans and mulattoes had been freed by [[manumission]].<ref name=\"Bergad\">Bergad, Laird W. 2007. The Comparative Histories of Slavery in Brazil, Cuba, and the United States. New York: Cambridge University Press.\n</ref> According to Jo\u00e3o Ribeiro, \"more than anything humane and Christian, [[Lei \u00c1urea]] ('Golden Law') menaced the work and gravely injured the interests of the farmers; there still had been in Brazil more than seven hundred thousand slaves (...) Many of the farmers turned to the Republican party or became indifferent to the attack of the institutions...\"\n\nThe law did not provide an accompanying land distribution to the ex-captives. It led to a [[rural exodus]], both from the workers and from the now-bankrupt landlords. Slavery and its end formed the root of future problems such as slums, violence and poverty in urban centres.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/contexto_1.html |title=''Um velho desafio brasileiro \u2013 A import\u00e2ncia da reforma agr\u00e1ria para o futuro do pa\u00eds'' |language= |work=Revista Veja |date= |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613130440/http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/contexto_1.html |archivedate=13 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Brazilian Empire: coffee ===\n\nIn the late colonial era coffee was introduced to the country. After [[Independence of Brazil|independence]] production consolidated in the [[Southeast Region, Brazil|Southeast region]], mainly in the state of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. At the beginning of the 19th century, exports totaled 19.6 tons, growing to 3,063,660 tons in the 1880\u20131890 period, growing to about sixty three percent of Brazil's total exports.<ref name=\"bb\" />\n\n[[File:Coffee plantation in Brazil.jpg|thumb|Brazilian coffee plantation in the early twentieth century.]]\n\nCoffee was responsible for the appearance of a new dominant [[oligarchy]] in Brazil, the so-called Coffee Barons. It hastened immigration following the end of slavery. The era reached its peak with [[Caf\u00e9 com leite politics]], ending with the [[Manuel Ferraz de Campos Sales|Campos Sales]] administration. The [[Great Depression]] closed this cycle at the end of the 1930s with industrialization, capitalized by profits from coffee production.<ref>ARRUDA, Jos\u00e9 Jobson de A.: ''Hist\u00f3ria Moderna e Contempor\u00e2nea''. \u00c1tica, S\u00e3o Paulo, 13th ed., 1981.</ref>\n\n[[File:Preparing for coffee shipment.jpg|thumb|Bagging for export, at the height of the coffee cycle.]]\n\nCoffee drew many Italian immigrants to the west of S\u00e3o Paulo. Coffee wealth accentuated the differences between the Brazilian regions, especially vs the [[Northeast Region, Brazil|Northeast]].<ref name=bb/>\n\nBesides coffee, other crops increased in the 19th century, such as tobacco and [[Cocoa bean|cocoa]], in Bahia, and [[rubber]] in [[Amaz\u00f4nia]]. In 1910 rubber represented about forty percent of exports.<ref name=bb/>\n\n==== International problems ====\nBrazilian coffee production exceeded global demand at the beginning of the 20th century. This resulted in the Taubat\u00e9 Agreement, where the State began acquiring surplus for destruction and planting seedlings was forbidden&mdash;with the goal of maintaining a minimum profitable price.<ref name=bb/>\n\nRubber suffered from foreign competition. In 1870, English smugglers smuggled [[rubber tree]] seedlings out of Brazil and in 1895 began production in Asia. In the 1910s and 1920s this competition practically eliminated Brazilian production.<ref name=bb/>\n\n=== Agronomy schools ===\n\n[[File:Entrada Principal - CAC.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the [[Agricultural School in Cambori\u00fa]], of UFSC.]]\nIn 1887 during the Empire era, the first school dedicated to the training of agronomists opened in the city of [[Cruz das Almas]]. In 1883, in [[Pelotas]], Rio Grande do Sul, a second school opened.<ref name=engag>{{cite web |url=http://www.agr.feis.unesp.br/dv11112003.php |title=A Agronomia Atrav\u00e9s dos Tempos |language=Portuguese |author=TOSCANO, Luiz Fernando |work=essay originally published in Journal of Votuporanga, Year 50, n\u00b0 12.798, p. 02 (on: [[UNESP]] site) |date=11 November 2003 |accessdate=6 March 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309105407/http://www.agr.feis.unesp.br/dv11112003.php |archivedate=9 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe first school was officially recognized thirty-five years after its creation, with Decree 8.319/1910. The [[agronomist]] profession only came to be recognized in 1933. Seventy regular agronomy colleges operate in Brazil. The day the decree was publicized, 12 October, became the \"Day of the Agronomist.\"<ref name=engag/>\n\nProfessional registration is managed by Regional Engineering and Architecture Councils, integrated at the national level by CONFEA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.confea.org.br/ |title=CONFEA's official website |language=Portuguese |author=Confea |website= |date= |accessdate=12 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310020341/http://www.confea.org.br/ |archivedate=10 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Educational activity is supported by the Federation of Brazilian Agronomy Students.\n\n=== Diversification: 1960\u20131990 ===\n\n[[File:Embrapa 35 anos fundador (Jos\u00e9 Cruz ABr) 23abr2008.JPG|thumb|The former minister, Luis Fernando Cirne Lima, founder of Embrapa, speaking at the corporation's 35th anniversary conference.]]\nThe Brazilian Enterprise for Agricultural Research ([[EMBRAPA]]) was established during the [[Brazilian military government|military regime]] in 1973 with the objective of diversifying production. The body was responsible for the support of new crops, adapted to the country's diverse regions. The expansion of agricultural borders towards the [[Cerrado]] had begun, and of monocultural [[latifundium|latifundia]] with production at a semi-industrial scale of soybeans, cotton and beans.<ref name=bb/>  Czech-Brazilian researcher [[Johanna D\u00f6bereiner]] helped lead Brazil's [[Green Revolution]], winning her the [[UNESCO Science Prize]] for her work on nitrogen-fixing microorganisms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnpab.embrapa.br/aunidade/johanna.html |title=49 Anos Dedicados \u00e0 Pesquisa em Microbiologia do Solo (49 Years Dedicated to Research in Soil Microbiology) |language=Portuguese |authors=Embrapa/Agrobiologia |website= |date= |accessdate=13 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217083254/http://www.cnpab.embrapa.br/aunidade/johanna.html |archivedate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1960 four main agricultural products were exported, growing by the early 1990s to nineteen. Brazil also moved \"downstream\" to expand post-harvest processing. In the 60's unprocessed goods made up 84% of total exports, falling to 20% by 1990.<ref name=bb/>\n\nAgricultural promotion policies included subsidized credits, bank debt write-offs and exports subsidies (in some cases, reaching 50% of the product value).<ref name=bb/>\n\n=== Mechanization: 1990s ===\n\n[[File:Agriculture in Brazil.jpg|thumb|Harvester on a Brazilian cotton plantation.]]\n\nBeginning with the 1994 creation of [[Plano Real]] for monetary stabilization, Brazilian agriculture went through a radical transformation: the State cut subsidies and the market began to finance agriculture, leading to the replacement of manpower with machines. Brazil's rural population fell from 20,700,000 in 1985 to 17,900,000 in 1995, followed by a decrease in import taxes on inputs and other measures that forced Brazilian producers to adapt to global practices. The raise of productivity, mechanization (with reduction of costs) and professionalization marked that period.<ref name=bb/>\n\n== Land issues ==\nBrazil initially used a land management system known as sesmarias featured by large holdings with a small number of landowners. In 1822 sesmarias gave way to the current [[latifundium|latifundia]] (system of large estates).<ref name=\"oqeqa\">{{cite book | author = Jos\u00e9 Graziano da Silva | title = O que \u00e9 Quest\u00e3o Agr\u00e1ria (Chapter: ''O desenvolvimento recente da agricultura brasileira: a heran\u00e7a hist\u00f3rica'')  | edition = 13th | year = 1980 | publisher = [[editora Brasiliense|Brasiliense]] | volume =18 (cole\u00e7\u00e3o Primeiros Passos) | location = S\u00e3o Paulo | language = Portuguese | isbn = | chapter = | quote =| author-link = Jos\u00e9 Graziano da Silva }}</ref> In 1850 the [[Land tenure|''Law of Lands'']] was promulgated, which kept the latifundia system and remained in effect until 1964, when the [[Brazilian military government|dictatorship]] prepared the Land Statute. The high cost of agricultural production contributed to latifundia formation and the country never experienced substantial [[land reform]]. That only became part of the country's official and legal policies after the [[Constitution of Brazil|1988 Constitution]].<ref>{{cite book | author = CARRIL, Lourdes | title = Terras de Negros \u2013 heran\u00e7a de quilombos (Chap. 4: ''Terras no Brasil: uma quest\u00e3o n\u00e3o resolvida'') | year = 1997 | publisher = [[editora Scipione|Scipione]] | location = S\u00e3o Paulo | language = Portuguese | isbn =978-85-262-3225-9  | chapter = | quote =}}</ref>\n\nOf the around thirty-one million Brazilians who lived in poverty in 2014, more than half lived in rural areas. In the last twenty-five years of the 20th century, about thirty million rural dwellers abandoned or lost their land, creating some 4.8 million landless families. During that time, the majority of funding resources was directed to the [[oligarchy|oligarchs]] and great landowners, supporting the model of intensive monoculture agriculture.<ref name=fao>{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/righttofood/kc/downloads/vl/docs/AH264.pdf |title=Agrarian Reform in Brazil |authors= [[Organiza\u00e7\u00e3o das Na\u00e7\u00f5es Unidas para a Agricultura e a Alimenta\u00e7\u00e3o|FAO]] |work= Global Campaign for Agrarian Reform = ARC Fact sheet |date= May 2000 |accessdate=8 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1985 and 1988 the country's redemocratization triggered almost 9,000 social conflicts in rural areas and the murders of 1,167 people over agricultural issues. In this period a confrontation pitted unions, social movements and the [[Catholic Church]] against the landowners united in the [[Uni\u00e3o Democr\u00e1tica Ruralista|Democratic Association of Ruralists]] (UDR) which had Ronaldo Caiado as its main representative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/arquivo/180686.html |title=O trator da direita |language=Portuguese |work=[[Revista Veja]] |date=18 June 1986 |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402033508/http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/reforma_agraria/arquivo/180686.html |archivedate=2 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The most famous victim of those conflicts was the unionist [[Chico Mendes]], in [[Acre (state)|Acre]], in 1988.\n\n[[File:MST 06142007.jpg|thumb|Members of the Landless Workers' Movement (MST), the main representative group of the landless workers, during the closing of the MST's 5th Congress in Bras\u00edlia, in 2007.]]\nAccording to Man\u00e7ano rural censuses collected since 1940 indicated ongoing concentration of land ownership, accompanied by an exodus of farmers to urban areas. Reversing the trend would have required the annual settlement of 150,000 families. During [[Itamar Franco]]'s Government, the [[INCRA]] (National Institute of Colonization and Agrarian Reform) achieved about 10,000 settlements annually. A fast-track procedure for expropriation of large landholdings was established, ending long delays, one of the measure's main obstacles.<ref name=ra/>\n\nThe conflicts reached their peak in 1996 with the [[Eldorado dos Caraj\u00e1s massacre]], in [[Par\u00e1]], when the governor, Almir Gabriel, ordained the clearing of a road occupied by the landless. Casualties amounted to nineteen dead and fifty-one injured, underlining the land problem and accompanying disrespect for human rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/em_dia/carajas_capa.html |title=Sangue em Eldorado |language=Portuguese |authors=[[M\u00f4nica Bergamo|BERGAMO, M\u00f4nica]] e CAMAROTTI, Gerson |work=[[Revista Veja]] |date=24 April 1996 |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126180411/http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/em_dia/carajas_capa.html |archivedate=26 January 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn a 1996 article economist [[Maria da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o Tavares]], one of the most prominent critics of [[Fernando Henrique Cardoso]]'s Government, claimed, \"the importance of a rural reform has increased and the dispute for land, if the relations of \"dominance\" of rural properties are not regulated quickly, will lead to growing confrontations\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eco.unicamp.br/artigos/tavares/artigo44.htm |title=A Quest\u00e3o Agr\u00e1ria e as Rela\u00e7\u00f5es de Poder no Pa\u00eds |language=Portuguese |author=TAVARES, Maria da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o |work=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |date=5 May 1996 |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519201041/http://www.eco.unicamp.br/artigos/tavares/artigo44.htm |archivedate=19 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe land reform movement included about five hundred land occupations of what protesters considered to be unproductive farms. As a reaction to the invasions, President Cardoso published Provisional Measure 2.027-38, which prohibited earmarking all occupied land for agrarian reform.<ref name=ra>{{cite web |url=http://www.comciencia.br/reportagens/agraria/agr04.shtml |title=''MP da desapropria\u00e7\u00e3o dever\u00e1 ser mantida'' |language=Portuguese |author=CUNHA, Rodrigo |work=Revista ComCi\u00eancia |date= |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307175732/http://www.comciencia.br/reportagens/agraria/agr04.shtml |archivedate=7 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Irrigation ==\n[[File:Arroz 095.jpg|thumb|Rice paddy: Where irrigation first occurred in Brazil.]]\nThe first irrigation experiments in Brazil occurred in Rio Grande do Sul, for cultivating rice. The first record dates to 1881 with the construction of the Cadro dam which began in 1903.{{Clarify|reason = Did it begin in 1881 or 1903?|date = November 2014}} However, the practice broadened in the last thirty years of the 20th century between the years 1970 to 1980.<ref name=birriga>{{cite book | author =Minist\u00e9rio da Integra\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional | title =A irriga\u00e7\u00e3o no Brasil:situa\u00e7\u00e3o e diretrizes | edition = | year = 2008 | publisher =IICA | volume = | location =Bras\u00edlia | language = Portuguese | isbn =978-92-9039-908-7 | chapter = | quote =}}</ref>\n\nPrivate initiative developed Irrigation in the South and Southeast regions.\n\nIn the Northeast official bodies, such as DNOCS and CODEVASF, led the way beginning in the 1950s. In 1968, the Executive Group on Irrigation and Agrarian Development (GEIDA) was set up, and two years later it instituted the Multi-annual Program of Irrigation (PPI). The majority of resources were directed to the Northeast.<ref name=\"birriga\" /> These federal initiatives, however, did not achieve success. In 1985 a new guidance and in 1996 a new direction produced the New Model of Irrigation Project. The Project intended to broaden the use of irrigation in agriculture and drew on more than 1,500 national and foreign experts.<ref name=birriga/>\n\nAccording to the [[World Bank]], Brazil's irrigation potential is about {{Convert|29000000|ha|sqmi}}. In 1998, however, drought reduced capacity to only 2.98 million hectares.<ref name=est>{{cite web |url=http://www.agriambi.com.br/revista/v5n1/171.pdf |title=Estat\u00edsticas sobre irriga\u00e7\u00e3o no Brasil segundo o Censo Agropecu\u00e1rio 1995\u20131996 |language=Portuguese |author=Mard\u00f4nio L. Loiola1 |author2=Francisco de Souza |work=Revista Brasileira de Engenharia Agr\u00edcola e Ambiental, v.5, n.1, p. 171\u2013180 |date= |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150701/http://www.agriambi.com.br/revista/v5n1/171.pdf |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 20th century, the country primarily used [[Irrigation#Surface|surface irrigation]] (59%), followed by [[Irrigation#Sprinkler System|overhead]] (35%) and then [[Drip irrigation|targeted irrigation]]. The South represented the largest irrigated area (more than 1.1 million hectares), followed by the Southeast (800 thousand hectares) and Northeast (490 thousand hectares).<ref name=est/>\n\nCurrently, a regulatory milestone of irrigation is making its way through the [[National Congress of Brazil]], through bill 6381/2005,<ref name=birriga/> which aims at replacing the Law 6662/1979, which regulates irrigation policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/Leis/L6662.htm |title=Lei 6662 |language=Portuguese |author=Congresso Nacional |work=Revista Brasileira de Engenharia Agr\u00edcola e Ambiental, v.5, n.1, p. 171\u2013180 |date=1979 |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328100748/http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/Leis/L6662.htm |archivedate=28 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWater resources policy is regulated by Law 9433/1997, and managed by the National Council.<ref name=\"birriga\" />\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n=== Storage ===\n\n[[File:Rondon\u00f3polis transporte soja (Roosevelt Pinheiro) 28mar09.JPG|thumb|\nTrucks transporting soybean crop\n]]\n\nCrop [[Food storage|storage]] facilities require expansion in order to keep up with increasing production. Brazilian storage capacity in 2003 was 75% of grain production,<ref name=\"pesq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.finep.gov.br/PortalDPP/relatorio_setorial/impressao_relatorio.asp?lst_setor=18 |title=Relat\u00f3rio Setorial Preliminar: Armazenagem agr\u00edcola |date=7 December 2007 |accessdate=22 December 2009 |last=Martinelli |first=Orlando |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609214713/http://www.finep.gov.br/PortalDPP/relatorio_setorial/impressao_relatorio.asp?lst_setor=18 |archivedate=9 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> well short of the ideal of 120%.<ref name=\"armazex\">{{cite web |url=http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0869/m0082220.html |title=A falta que faz um armaz\u00e9m |date=1 June 2006 |last=Corr\u00eaa |first=Alessandra |work=Revista Exame |accessdate=22 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427174805/http://portalexame.abril.com.br/static/aberto/anuarioagronegocio/edicoes_0869/m0082220.html |archivedate=27 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFarm-based crop storage (e.g., using [[silo]]s) is not common in Brazil. Lack of storage forces produce to be commercialized quickly. According to Conab data, only 11% of warehouses are located on farms (by comparison [[Argentina]] has 40%, the [[European Union]] has 50% and Canada has 80%). Farmers rely on third party storage services.\n\nLack of access to capital, exacerbated by financial instability from factors such as exchange rate volatility, prevents most producers from building significant storage.<ref name=\"armazex\" />\n\n=== Transport ===\n\n[[File:Safra interior Sao Paulo 01 2006 06.jpg|thumb|Transport of crops by highway]]\nCrop transport is a longstanding structural problem for Brazilian agriculture. Calmon noted that, since the Empire, \"the disposal of the harvest is difficult\" and indicated that \"the old projects of iron roads or cartable paths, linking the coast to the central mountains (...) are resisted by skeptical statesmen, quoting Thiers, who, in 1841, believed that railways were not convenient to France\".<ref>CALMON, Pedro: \"Hist\u00f3ria da Civiliza\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira\", Cia. Editora Nacional, S\u00e3o Paulo, 3\u00aa ed., 1937</ref>\n\nCrops are immediately trucked to market via highways, mostly in poor traffic conditions at high cost.<ref name=es>{{cite web |url=http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_7.doc |title=A Log\u00edstica do Escoamento da Safra Brasileira |language=Portuguese |author=FILHO, Jos\u00e9 |last2=Caixeta |first2=Vicente |work=ESALQ \u2013 USP |date= |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621172808/http://cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_7.doc |archivedate=21 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFor the 2008/2009 harvest, for example, the Federation of Agriculture and Livestock of Goi\u00e1s denounced poor road conditions in the [[Central-West Region, Brazil|Center-West region]], despite repeated requests for federal assistance over several years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faeg.com.br/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&catid=14:ultimas-noticias&id=1203:-estradas-mal-conservadas-vao-prejudicar-escoamento-da-safra-200809 |title=Problemas em estradas prejudicam escoamento de safra |language=Portuguese |author=FAEG |website= |date=13 January 2009 |accessdate=9 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the federal government issued a National Plan of Logistics and Transportation, meant to improve production flow.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.noticiacapital.com.br/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10775:plano-nacional-de-logistica-e-transportes-sera-discutido-na-fieb&catid=45:economia&Itemid=56 |title=Plano Nacional de Log\u00edstica e Transportes ser\u00e1 discutido na Fieb |language=Portuguese |work=Not\u00edcia Capital |date=4 March 2010 |accessdate=3 June 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308145608/http://www.noticiacapital.com.br/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10775:plano-nacional-de-logistica-e-transportes-sera-discutido-na-fieb&catid=45:economia&Itemid=56 |archivedate=8 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lack of investment, however, continues to be the main obstacle to distribution logistics.\n\n=== Regulatory stocks and minimum price ===\n\nA good example of the need of regulatory stocks is in the production of [[ethanol]] as a fuel from sugar cane. The elevated price variation during the harvest year, that varies for climatic and plant health reasons, justifies the formation of stocks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/pdf/Cepea_alcool_OESP.pdf |title=Estoques Reguladores de \u00c1lcool |language=Portuguese |last=Rumenos |first=Mirian |last2=Bacchi |first2=Piedade |work=O Estado de S. Paulo in:Cepea Esalq/USP |date=20 April 2006 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091222194809/http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/pdf/Cepea_alcool_OESP.pdf |archivedate=22 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Stocks also aim to stabilize farmers' revenues, and avoid price fluctuations between harvests.{{Clarify|reason = This is gibberish, but there may be a point here.|date = November 2014}}\n\nUntil the 1980s, Brazil employed the Minimum Prices Policy. That policy had lost relevance by the 1990s, due to [[globalization]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iea.sp.gov.br/out/verTexto.php?codTexto=330 |title=Estabiliza\u00e7\u00e3o De Pre\u00e7os, Renda Ou De Volume Negociado? |language=Portuguese |author=Afonso Negri Neto |work=Instituto de Economia Agr\u00edcola |date=4 December 2001 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160457/http://www.iea.sp.gov.br/out/verTexto.php?codTexto=330 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe composition of stocks at the national level is the responsibility of the National Food Supply Company (Conab).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agroplante.com.br/noticias.php?id=395 |title=Com safra recorde no Brasil, a maior da hist\u00f3ria, pode sobrar milho no mercado |language=Portuguese |website= |date=18 August 2010 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730040851/http://www.agroplante.com.br/noticias.php?id=395 |archivedate=30 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Family farming ==\n[[File:Abr horta Antonio Cruz.jpg|thumb|Vegetable plot on a family farm.]]\nOfficial definitions of a family farmer differ from country to country in [[Latin America]]. There are 3 general categories: subsistence farming, intermediate family farmers and consolidated farms.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.ifad.org/events/agriculture/doc/papers/berdegue.pdf|title = Latin America: The State of Smallholders in Agriculture|date = |accessdate = 16 November 2015|website = |publisher = International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD)|last = Berdegu\u00e9|first = Julio A.|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160221225154/http://www.ifad.org/events/agriculture/doc/papers/berdegue.pdf|archivedate = 21 February 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> In Brazil, the Family Farming Law (Law 11,326) defines family farmers through four criteria related to [[land tenure]], farm size, dependence on farm income, and the use of predominantly family labor.<ref name=\":0\" /> In Brazil, the large majority of family farms are in the northeastern, southern and southeast Brazil. Family farmers in Brazil produce more than 70%of food consumed domestically.\n\nDuring the 1990s, the Lula administration implemented a set of policies that addressed food security on federal, state and municipal levels, the aim of which was to increase federal government support to family farmers. In 1999, the Ministry of Agrarian Development (MDA) was created to support family farmers and promote land reform and sustainable land development.<ref name=\"Brazil - FAO 2014 country fact sheet on food and agriculture policy trends\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/field/009/i3759e/i3759e.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-12-05 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023052917/http://www.fao.org/docrep/field/009/i3759e/i3759e.pdf |archivedate=23 October 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A host of government policies and government-supported programs in the interest of family farmers then emerged, where the family farmer is recognized as a pillar of national development. Since then, the MDA along with other institutions were created with the family farmers and other traditional communities' interests in mind,<ref name=\":1\"/> where policies targeting family farmers were designed to introduce market incentives, promote adequate food distribution and provide technical assistance.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The FOME ZERO (Zero Hunger) Program|url = http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/ap339e/ap339e00.htm|website = www.fao.org|accessdate = 2015-12-05|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150121010400/http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/ap339e/ap339e00.htm|archivedate = 21 January 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn general, family farms are establishments that employ mostly family members<ref name=\"bn1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |title=Agricultura familiar \u2013 apresenta\u00e7\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=Banco do Nordeste |website= |date= |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091002064625/http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |archivedate=2 October 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> with up to five temporary workers.<ref name=\"ceu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_9.doc |title=Agricultura familiar |language=Portuguese |author=Geraldo Sant'Ana de Camargo Barros |work=Cepea/Esalq/USP |date=July 2006 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122191452/http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/especialagro/EspecialAgroCepea_9.doc |archivedate=22 November 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Family farms provide the majority of Brazilian staples, including 84% of [[manioc]], 67% of [[bean]]s and 49% of [[Maize|corn]].<ref name=\"bn1\" /> Family farms also have a large role in the livestock and dairy industry, producing 58% of milk, 59% of pork, 50% of poultry and 31% of cattle.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title = Policies and institutional and legal frameworks in the expansion of Brazilian biofuels|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qLak5dKS_qIC|publisher = CIFOR|first = Andrade, R. M. T., Miccolis|last = A}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''% of total crop production by family farmers''' '''(2010 statistics, Ministry of Agrarian Development, Brazil)'''\n!Crop\n!Percentage (%) produced by family farmers\n|-\n|'''Manioc'''\n|84%\n|-\n|'''Beans'''\n|67%\n|-\n|'''Corn'''\n|49%\n|-\n|'''Rice'''\n|34%\n|-\n|'''Milk'''\n|58%\n|-\n|'''Cattle'''\n|31%\n|-\n|'''Pork'''\n|59%\n|-\n|'''Poultry'''\n|50%\n|-\n|'''Wheat'''\n|21%\n|-\n|'''Soybeans'''\n|16%\n|}\nAccording to the [[IBGE]]'s 1995/96 Farming and Livestock Census, there were 4,339,859 family-run establishments in the country, the largest farm being 100 ha in area.<ref name=\"ceu\" /> In 2009, Brazil's Ministry of Agrarian Development (MDA) reported that 84.4% of all rural properties are in fact family farms.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 1990s family farms experienced productivity growth of 75%, compared to only 40% for larger-scale producers. The difference is largely due to the creation of PRONAF (National Program on Family Agriculture), which opened a special family farm credit line.\n\nUp to 2009 six Family Farming and Land Reform National Fairs were held, the first four in [[Bras\u00edlia]] and the last two in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. They highlight the importance of family farming to Brazilian economy, accounting for 70% of the country's food consumption and 10% of Brazilian [[GDP]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=2&id=2657736&action=noticias |title=Not\u00edcia |language=Portuguese |work=Canal Rural |date=15 September 2009 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523234752/http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=2&id=2657736&action=noticias |archivedate=23 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Food security in Brazil==\nInternational monitoring organizations assert that a third of Brazil's population is food insecure.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.iisd.org/publications/food-security-brazilian-case|title = Food Security: The Brazilian Case|date = 27 September 2010|accessdate = 7 December 2015|website = International Institute for Sustainable Development|publisher = IISD|last = Neves do Amaral|first = Weber Antonio|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150911085841/http://www.iisd.org/publications/food-security-brazilian-case|archivedate = 11 September 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Despite increased food production since the industrialization, a large proportion of Brazilians, especially the urban and rural poor, have difficulty meeting their nutrition needs.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.fao.org/ag/AGN/nutrition/BRA_en.stm|title = Brazil Nutrititon Profile|date = October 2000|accessdate = 7 December 2015|website = Nutrition and Consumer Protection|publisher = FAO Rome|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160321232748/http://www.fao.org/ag/agn/nutrition/bra_en.stm|archivedate = 21 March 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Small farmer, landless worker and indigenous movements that had consolidated during or after the military dictatorship mobilized nationwide, pressuring the authorities to prioritize food and nutrition security rose in the 1980s, and were able to strongly shape the direction of developmental policy.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Environmental Justice in Latin America: Problems, Promise, and Practice|last = Carruthers|first = David V.|publisher = MIT Press|year = 2008|isbn = 978-0-262-03372-5|location = }}</ref>\n\nThe notion of access to food and proper nutrition was first recorded official terminology in 1986 as ''seguran\u00e7a alimentar'' ([[food security]]).<ref name=\":02\" /> The right to food and nutrition was established on 25 August 2010, when Brazil adopted the Policy on Food Security and Nutrition (Decree 7.272).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.fao.org/righttofood/news-and-events/news-detail/en/c/44945/|title = Brazil adopts a new Policy on Food Security and Nutrition|date = 2 September 2010|work = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United States (FAO)|access-date = 7 December 2015|via = |url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160610142414/http://www.fao.org/righttofood/news-and-events/news-detail/en/c/44945/|archivedate = 10 June 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref>  Food security refers to being able to meet dietary needs through an adequate, secure supply of nutritious food.<ref name=\":2\" /> The term rose into Brazilian popular consciousness in 1993 after campaigns by a national movement called Citizens' Action Against Hunger and Poverty and for Life. In that same period, Consea (National Food and Nutritional Security Council) was established. the 1st National Conference on Food Security was organized by a combination of policy and grassroots mobilizations. Consea ran from 1993 to 1994, with little success in shaping public policies, was halted until after the establishment of the Fome Zero Program.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|title = The FOME ZERO (Zero Hunger) Program|url = http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/i3023e/i3023e00.htm|website = www.fao.org|accessdate = 2015-12-05|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150121043512/http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/i3023e/i3023e00.htm|archivedate = 21 January 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The 2010 Policy names Consea as an instrument in proposing programs that promote food security on a federal level.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== PRONAF (National Program for the Strengthening of Family Farming) ===\nDue to financial limitations, small farmers generally have difficulties securing the capital necessary to stay in rural areas and maintain production on a small scale. PRONAF was the first policy in 1994 to be created to meet the specific credit needs of family farmers. In order to stimulate agricultural production, the instrument provides incentives in the form of reduced-interest loans from national funds for rural development, targeting low-income farmers and agrarian reform farmers.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|url = http://www10.iadb.org/intal/intalcdi/PE/2009/03940.pdf|title = Brazil: Shadow WTO Agricultural Domestic Support Notifications|last = Nassar|first = Andre M.|date = May 2009|journal = International Food and Policy Research Institute (IFPRI)|doi = |pmid = |access-date = 7 December 2015}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Set against a backdrop of policies opening Brazil to [[Neoliberal]] economic forces and intense competition through [[Mercosur|Mercosul]], PRONAF marked the institutionalization of a differentiated policy approach to family farming in Brazil.<ref name=\":02\" /> The economic and social importance of family farmers and their specific needs were recognized through PRONAF, at least on paper. The creation of PRONAF has been credited to favorable political circumstances, beginning with Brazil's re-democratization in the 1980s and a receptive Cardoso administration to the mobilizations of a number of agrarian civil groups.<ref name=\":02\" /> Loans written out to family farmers through PRONAF rose from US$1 billion in 2000 to an estimated US$5.8 billion in 2008.<ref name=\":4\" /> Other credit programs targeted at family farmers that came after PRONAF include PROGER and PROCERA.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== The Fome Zero Program (The Zero Hunger Program) ===\nThe Fome Zero Program is a federal program aimed increasing food and nutrition security in rural and urban poor communities. Its main strategy was to connect local food producers with local markets, especially in rural areas, through ''inter-setorrialidade (''inter-agency cooperation'')''.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.hungercenter.org/publications/zero-hunger-evaluating-brazilian-food-security-policy-2/|title = Zero Hunger? Evaluating Brazilian Food Security Policy|date = 2011|accessdate = 3 December 2015|website = Congressional Hunger Center|last = Margolies|first = Amy|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061817/http://www.hungercenter.org/publications/zero-hunger-evaluating-brazilian-food-security-policy-2/|archivedate = 4 March 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> It was instituted in 2001 against the backdrop of increasing recognition for family farmers in Brazilian agrarian policies, and a consequence of 20 years of mobilizing by actors at different levels of society for policy change. The Program is built on four axes: food access, strengthening family farming, income generation and articulation, mobilization and social control. Family farmers play a large role in the Program's food security goals: the Family Farming Food Acquisition Program (PAA), the National School Meal Program (Pnae) and the ''Bols''a ''Fam\u00edlia'' Program (Family Grant Cash Transfer ) were implementations that aimed to encourage family farm production of staple foods through cash and program incentives, facilitate distribution of food to families and schools, and also provide conditional health care and social assistance to 42 million vulnerable Brazilians.<ref name=\":02\" /> Despite praise for the Zero Hunger Program, federal evaluation of the impact of measures such as the National School Meal Program on family farmer production and nutrition of schoolchildren have been limited, given the challenges of assessing decentralized implementation of the policy even at municipal levels.<ref name=\":5\" /> Furthermore, the Brazilian government has been cautious and controlled public and international access to the assessment reports of a number of programs, including the report for the ''Bolsa ''Fam\u00edlia'''' program.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Gathering ==\n[[File:26Movim. Interestadual Quebradeiras de Coco023.JPG|thumb|People gathering babassu, in Maranh\u00e3o.]]\nThe country's colonization began with harvesting native plants where they grew. Cultivation followed much later. The exploitation of [[Caesalpinia echinata|brazilwood]], known to the natives as ibirapitanga, and which ended up naming the land was begun by the Portuguese.<ref>Hist\u00f3ria do Brasil. Souto Maior. Unidade III \u2013 O Ciclo do Pau-Brasil. Cia Editora Nacional, S\u00e3o Paulo, 1968</ref>\n\nBrazil operates forty-nine gathering reservations and sixty-five forests protected by federal law. The gathering of plant resources is encouraged as a means of interacting with, but not degrading, the environment.<ref name=uu>{{cite web |url=http://noticias.ambientebrasil.com.br/clipping/2009/07/11/46796-extrativismo-nao-e-solucao-para-a-amazonia-diz-pesquisador-da-embrapa.html |title=Extrativismo n\u00e3o \u00e9 solu\u00e7\u00e3o para a Amaz\u00f4nia, diz pesquisador da Embrapa |language=Portuguese |last=Then\u00f3rio |first=Iber\u00ea |work=Globo Amaz\u00f4nia, in: Ambiente Brasil |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817065631/http://noticias.ambientebrasil.com.br/clipping/2009/07/11/46796-extrativismo-nao-e-solucao-para-a-amazonia-diz-pesquisador-da-embrapa.html |archivedate=17 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLack of government funding has destabilized this use of forest resources. The case of natural rubber is typical: in Acre about 4,000 families have apparently abandoned the activity, as revealed in early 2009. After undergoing acclimatization, rubber trees were grown successfully in S\u00e3o Paulo state, where more than 36,000 hectares were planted \u2013 while Acre accounts for little more than a thousand hectares.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mercadoetico.terra.com.br/arquivo/governo-nao-age-e-extrativismo-esta-a-beira-da-falencia/ |title=Extrativismo est\u00e1 \u00e0 beira da fal\u00eancia |language=Portuguese |last=Ara\u00fajo |first=Chico |work=Ag\u00eancia Amaz\u00f4nia |date=12 February 2009 |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714031227/http://mercadoetico.terra.com.br/arquivo/governo-nao-age-e-extrativismo-esta-a-beira-da-falencia/ |archivedate=14 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHomma claims that gathering rubber is economically impracticable. For example, in native forests, rubber trees are found at a density of some 1.5 trees per ha, versus hundreds of trees per ha on rubber plantations. Cultivating degraded areas with native trees has been successful with trees such as cupua\u00e7u and jaborandi.<ref name=uu/>\n\nAccording to [[IBGE]], in 2003 the gathering sector's output was divided into timber (65%) and non-wood (35%), at a value of four hundred forty-nine million Reals, with the following main products: piassaba (27%), babassu (nut \u2013 17%), a\u00e7ai (16%), yerba mate (14%), carnauba (8%) and Brazil nut (5%).<ref name=ibgemad>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=260 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o Florestal Brasileira soma R$7,869 bilh\u00f5es em 2003 |language=Portuguese |author=IBGE-Comunica\u00e7\u00e3o Social |work=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o da Extra\u00e7\u00e3o Vegetal e da Silvicultura \u2013 2003 |date=25 November 2004 |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516221127/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=260 |archivedate=16 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Soils ==\n[[File:Regolith.jpg|thumb|Regolithic soil, in granulite.]]The program of mapping and classifying the country's [[soil]]s began in 1953, with the ''Chart of Soils in Brazil''. IBGE published the first map in 2003. Soil knowledge helped allow the expansion of agricultural production from 1975. The expansion of the Center-West required new technology because the region is mainly formed by [[oxisols]], which favor mechanization from soil preparation to harvest, partly because they are nutrient-poor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/31072003mapasolos.shtm |title=Mapa de Solos do Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Comunica\u00e7\u00e3o Social IBGE |website= |date=31 July 2003 |accessdate=23 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109011301/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/31072003mapasolos.shtm |archivedate=9 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSoil classification, study and systematization are championed by Embrapa Soils, with participation from groups such as the RADAM Project, the Rural University (now [[Universidade Federal Rural do Rio de Janeiro|UFRRJ]]) and other ag[[Agronomy|ronomists]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnps.embrapa.br/unidade/historico.html |title=Hist\u00f3rico CNPS |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa Solos |website= |date= |accessdate=23 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212150554/http://www.cnps.embrapa.br/unidade/historico.html |archivedate=12 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Agribusiness ==\n[[File:Soja exportacao.jpg|thumb|Machinery in soybean production.]]\nIn 2010 Brazil was the third largest exporter of [[agricultural]] products in the world, behind only the United States and the European Union.<ref name=\"estadao\">[http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20100601192402/http://www.estadao.com.br/estadaodehoje/20100307/not_imp520620,0.php Brasil supera Canad\u00e1 e se torna o terceiro maior exportador agr\u00edcola] \u2013 \"The State of S.Paulo\", 7 March 2010 (visited on 7 March 2010)</ref><ref>[http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Economia_Negocios/0,,MUL1518968-9356,00-BRASIL+SE+TORNA+O+TERCEIRO+MAIOR+EXPORTADOR+AGRICOLA.html Brasil se torna o terceiro maior exportador agr\u00edcola] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808190427/http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Economia_Negocios/0,,MUL1518968-9356,00-BRASIL+SE+TORNA+O+TERCEIRO+MAIOR+EXPORTADOR+AGRICOLA.html |date=8 August 2014 }} \u2013 \"G1\", 7 March 2010 (visited on 9 March 2010)</ref>\n\nDuring the last two decades of the 20th century, Brazil witnessed a doubling of [[yield per acre]]. This resulted from input improvements (seeds, [[fertilizer]]s, machinery), public policies that encouraged exports, reduced tax burden (such as the 1996 reduction of the [[circulation tax]]), more favorable real [[exchange rate]], which had allowed [[price stability]] (in 1999), increased Asian demand, [[productivity growth]] and reduced [[trade barrier]]s.<ref name=\"agb\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.uff.br/econ/download/tds/UFF_TD186.pdf |title=Agroneg\u00f3cio no Brasil: perspectives e limita\u00e7\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |last=Guanziroli |first=Carlos Enrique |journal=Economia Para Discuss\u00e3o, 186, Universidade Federal Fluminense |issn=1519-4612 |date=April 2006 |accessdate=3 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602041041/http://www.uff.br/econ/download/tds/UFF_TD186.pdf |archivedate=2 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFarming accounted for almost a third of [[GDP]], once everything from agricultural inputs to [[food processing]] and distribution are included.<ref name=\"agb\" />\n\nFrom 1990 to 2001, farming employment fell, although overall [[agribusiness]] employment jumped from 372 thousand to 1.82 million. The number of companies grew from 18 thousand in 1994 to almost 47 thousand in 2001.<ref name=\"ipea\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ipea.gov.br/pub/bccj/bc_60n.pdf |title=Crescimento da Agricultura |language=Portuguese |author1=GASQUES, Jos\u00e9 Garcia |author2=BASTOS, Eliana Teles |work=Boletim de Conjuntura, n\u00ba 60 |date=March 2003 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419013351/http://www.ipea.gov.br/pub/bccj/bc_60n.pdf |archivedate=19 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFactors that limit further expansion range from pests evolving to target [[monoculture]]s, [[#Transportation of production|infrastructure issues]] and environmental problems generated by practices such as [[deforestation]], etc.<ref name=\"agb\" />\n\n=== Trade balance ===\n\nThe 2007 harvest enabled gross agriculture exports yielding 68.1 billion dollars, and net exports of 57.3 billion dollars.<ref name=reu1>{{cite web |url=http://www.estadao.com.br/economia/not_eco219430,0.htm |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00e3o de soja em gr\u00e3o do Brasil soma quase US$2 bi em julho |language=Portuguese |agency=Reuters |website= |date=7 August 2008 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221131901/http://www.estadao.com.br/economia/not_eco219430,0.htm |archivedate=21 February 2009 |df=dmy-all |author-link=Reuters }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Brazil's biggest export market was the [[European Union]], while China was the largest single importing country with a 13.2% share, followed by the [[Netherlands]] with 9.5% and the US at 8.7%.<ref name=\"reu1\" />\n\n=== Regions ===\n\n[[Regions of Brazil|Brazil's regions]] offer a wide diversity of climate. Agriculture reflects this diversity. In 1995, the North produced 4.2%, the Northeast \u2013 13.6%, the Center-West \u2013 10.4%, the Southeast \u2013 41.8% and the South \u2013 30.0%. The Center-West and North regions have recently expanded their share to the total.<ref name=\"ttsc\">{{cite journal |title=A descentraliza\u00e7\u00e3o regional do agroneg\u00f3cio brasileiro. |language=Portuguese |last1=Parr\u00e9 |first1=Jos\u00e9 Luiz |last2=Guilhoto |first2=J.J. Martins. |journal=Scielo \u2013 Revista Brasileira de Economia |volume=55 |number=2 |issn=0034-7140 |date=April\u2013June 2001 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1590/S0034-71402001000200004 }}</ref>\n\n==== South ====\n[[File:Vinicola rio grande do sul (1701423442).jpg|thumb|Vineyard gaucho]]\nThe [[South Region, Brazil|southern Brazilian state]]s are [[Rio Grande do Sul]], Santa Catarina and [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]]. [[Cooperative]]s are a common feature of agriculture there. Irrigated rice and [[poultry farming|poultry]] are the two largest crops. Corn and [[beans]] are also prominent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://seer.ufrgs.br/AnaliseEconomica/article/viewFile/10655/6291 |title=A Import\u00e2ncia Econ\u00f4mica do Agroneg\u00f3cio para a Regi\u00e3o Sul do Brasil. |language=Portuguese |authors=PARR\u00c9L, Jos\u00e9 Luiz. GUILHOTO, Joaquim Jos\u00e9 Martins |work=UFRGS |date=1985 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162243/http://seer.ufrgs.br/AnaliseEconomica/article/viewFile/10655/6291 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The region is Brazil's largest tobacco producer and the world's largest exporter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25822 |title=Not\u00edcia: Regi\u00e3o Sul dever\u00e1 produzir 760 mil toneladas de fumo em 2008/2009 |language=Portuguese |work=Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio |date= |accessdate=3 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522211115/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25822 |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSanta Catarina has a high level of interdependence between the industrial and agricultural sectors.<ref name=rsa>{{cite web |url=http://www.fearp.usp.br/egna/resumos/Montoya.doc |title=O Agroneg\u00f3cio nos Estados da Regi\u00e3o Sul: uma an\u00e1lise do grau de integra\u00e7\u00e3o intersetorial entre a agropecuaria e algumas agroind\u00fastrias de 1985 a 1995. |language=Portuguese |authors=MONTOYA, Marco Antonio. VERGARA, Thelmo. OLTRAMARI, Andrea. |website= |date= |accessdate=3 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162400/http://www.fearp.usp.br/egna/resumos/Montoya.doc |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Rio Grande do Sul, family-run agribusiness is important and is descended from the colonial plantation model. Early farms survived and their families stayed on the land.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asbraer.org.br/Documentos/Biblioteca/comparacaors_brasill.pdf |title=Compara\u00e7\u00e3o entre o Agroneg\u00f3cio Familiar do Rio Grande do Sul e o do Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=GUILHOTO, J.J. Martins |work=Teoria e Evid. Econ., 14\u00aa ed., pp. 9\u201335, Passo Fundo |date=2006 |accessdate=3 September 2009 |display-authors=etal }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 the region produced 14.4% of Brazil's fruit.<ref name=iai/>\n\n==== Southeast ====\n[[File:Faz S Sofia canavial 090607 REFON.JPG|thumb|Cane plantation in Avare, S\u00e3o Paulo.]]The Southeast region includes [[Minas Gerais]], S\u00e3o Paulo, [[Rio de Janeiro]] and [[Esp\u00edrito Santo]]. In 1995 it was responsible for the largest share of Brazilian agriculture, but other regions were growing more rapidly.<ref name=\"ttsc\" />\n\nIn 2004 the Southeast produced 49.8% of the nation's fruit.<ref name=iai/> The region hosts 60% of agribusiness software companies, according to a survey carried out by Embrapa Livestock and Farming Information Technology (located in [[Campinas]]/SP).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25086 |title=Empresas de software para agroneg\u00f3cio concentram-se no Sudeste |language=Portuguese |author=Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio: not\u00edcia |website= |date=25 July 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080806212533/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=25086 |archivedate=6 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Its agribusiness sector was second in the national ranking, in the period from 2000 to May 2008, representing 36% of 308 billion dollars of total exports. The biggest exports were sugar (17.27%), coffee (16.25%), paper and cellulose (14.89%), meats (11.71%) and horticultural and fruit (especially orange juice) with 10.27%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es do agroneg\u00f3cio do Brasil e das suas macro-regi\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |last=Barros |first=Geraldo |author2=Karlin Saori Ishii |website= |date=14 July 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619200232/http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |archivedate=19 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Northeast ====\n[[File:Opuntia cochenillifera Abr - Valter Campanato.jpg|thumb|Palm plantation in Urandi]]\nThe Northeast includes [[Bahia]], Sergipa, Pernambuco, Alogoas, [[Paraiba]], Rio Grande do Norte, [[Ceara]], [[Piaui]] and [[Maranhao]]. Farms are primarily family-owned; 82.9% of field labor is on family farms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es do agroneg\u00f3cio do Brasil e das suas macro-regi\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |last=Barros |first=Geraldo |author2=Karlin Saori Ishii |website= |date=14 July 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619200232/http://www.boiapasto.com.br/exportacoes-do-agronegocio-do-brasil-e-das-suas-macro-regioes/ |archivedate=19 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}{{Cite web |url=http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |title=Not\u00edcia institucional |language= |author=Banco do Nordeste |website= |date= |accessdate=11 November 2016 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831232249/http://www.bnb.gov.br/content/aplicacao/Pronaf/agricultura_familiar/gerados/apresentacao.asp |archivedate=31 August 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe region is the largest national producer of bananas, (34% of the total)<ref name=emb3>{{cite web |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Banana/BananaCeara/importancia.htm |title=Cultivo da Banana para o Agrop\u00f3lo Jaguaribe-Apodi, Cear\u00e1. |language=Portuguese |author=BORGES, Ana L\u00facia |work=Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o, 5 |issn=1678-8796 |date=January 2003 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216102219/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Banana/BananaCeara/importancia.htm |archivedate=16 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and cassava (34.7%).<ref name=embmand/> It is the second largest producer of rice, with a harvest estimated in 2008 of 1.114 million tons. Maranh\u00e3o produces the majority (668 thousand tons).<ref name=ori/> It ranks second in fruit production, with 27% share.<ref name=iai/>\n\nThe region is subject to prolonged [[drought|dry spell]]s that are worse in [[El Ni\u00f1o]] years. This causes a periodic [[rural exodus]]. Government responses include dams and the [[transfer of the S\u00e3o Francisco River]]. The worst recent droughts were in 1993, 1998 and 1999. The latter was the worst in fifty years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fundaj.gov.br/tpd/127.html |title=A realidade da produtora rural na seca nordestina |language=Portuguese |author=L\u00edgia Albuquerque de Melo |work=Trabalhos para Discuss\u00e3o n. 127 |date=November 2001 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207000644/http://www.fundaj.gov.br/tpd/127.html |archivedate=7 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== North ====\n[[File:Projeto Rondon 2009 Manacapuru.JPG|thumb|Horticulture workshop, Manacapuru, Amazonas.]]\nThe Northern region includes Acre, Amap\u00e1, [[Amazonas (Brazilian state)|Amazonas]], Par\u00e1, [[Rond\u00f4nia]], Roraima and [[Tocantins]]. The [[Amazon rainforest]] occupies a significant part of the region. The region's great challenge is to combine farming with forest preservation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2008/novembro/4a-semana/manejo-florestal-sustentavel-e-destaque-no-amazontech/ |title=Manejo florestal sustent\u00e1vel \u00e9 destaque no Amazontech |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa |work=Not\u00edcia institucional |date=27 November 2008 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706155604/http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2008/novembro/4a-semana/manejo-florestal-sustentavel-e-destaque-no-amazontech/ |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBetween the end of the 19th century and early 20th century, during the so-called [[Amazon rubber boom|Rubber Boom]], the region produced rubber, Brazil's most important export, until Asian production underpriced Brazil and shut down the industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://portalamazonia.globo.com/pscript/amazoniadeaaz/artigoAZ.php?idAz=114 |title=Hist\u00f3ria |language=Portuguese |author=L\u00edgia Albuquerque de Melo |work=Portal da Amaz\u00f4nia, Globo |date= |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091010033445/http%3A//portalamazonia.globo.com/pscript/amazoniadeaaz/artigoAZ.php?idAz%3D114 |archivedate=10 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt is the second largest Brazilian banana producer (26% share)<ref name=emb3/> and of cassava (25.9% share), lagging behind only the Northeast.<ref name=embmand/> It produces 6.1% of the nation's fruit crop.<ref name=iai/>\n\n==== Midwest ====\n[[File:Planta\u00e7\u00e3o de Alho em Catal\u00e3o.jpg|thumb|Irrigated garlic]]\nThe Midwest region includes [[Mato Grosso]], Mato Grosso do Sul, [[Goi\u00e1s]] and [[Federal District (Brazil)|Distrito Federal]]. This region's agriculture developed much later than the rest of the country. The main biome is the [[Cerrado]]. By 2004, it was responsible for 46% of Brazilian soybeans, corn, rice and beans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2003/abril/bn.2004-11-25.0389686053/ |title=Especial 30 Anos \u2013 Tecnologias mudaram a cara do Centro-Oeste brasileiro |language=Portuguese |last=Cipriano |first=Robinson |work=S\u00edtio da Embrapa |date=25 November 2004 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160253/http://www.embrapa.gov.br/imprensa/noticias/2003/abril/bn.2004-11-25.0389686053/ |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOver three decades its harvest grew from 4.2 million to 49.3 million tons in 2008.<ref name=pag1>{{cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=24866 |title=Centro-Oeste deve se tornar maior produtor de gr\u00e3os do pa\u00eds |language=Portuguese |work=not\u00edcia in: Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio |date=10 July 2008 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009054539/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=24866 |archivedate=9 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIts cultivated area in 2008 was 15.1 million hectares. A big growth area was livestock. The opening of roads facilitated this growth.<ref name=pag1/>\n\nAs of 2004 this region produced only 2.7% of the nation's horticulture.<ref name=iai/>\n\n== Products ==\nThe principal agricultural products of Brazil are cattle, coffee, cotton, corn, rice, soy, wheat, sugarcane, tobacco, beans, floriculture and fruit. forestry, vegetables and cassava.\n\n=== Cattle ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cell padding=\"5\" cell spacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Cattle'''<ref>http://www.ipeadata.gov.br/ipeaweb.dll/ipeadata?SessionID=2075918462&Tick=1211151299640&VAR_FUNCAO=Ser_Temas%281410842077%29&Mod=R{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/C90C773459F8B52AE0300801FD0AF827{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1980\n| 1990\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million head'''\n| 78.54\n| 118.08\n| 147.10\n| 169.87\n| 207.15\n|}\n\nBrazil in 2005 produced around 8.7 million [[tonnes]] of beef,<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2134AF4606BE50C8E040A8C075023826{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> becoming world export leader in 2003 after surpassing Australia.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/portal/page?_pageid=33,968707&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL|title=Agroneg\u00f3cio Brasileiro<!-- Bot generated title -->|author=|date=|website=agricultura.gov.br|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502032959/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/portal/page?_pageid=33,968707&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL|archivedate=2 May 2008|df=dmy-all|access-date=19 May 2008}}</ref> Cattle herds are concentrated in [[Mato Grosso]], Mato Grosso do Sul, [[Goi\u00e1s]] and [[Minas Gerais]]. Together they account for over 46% of Brazilian cattle with more than 87 million head.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nAccording to the [[Ministry of Agriculture (Brazil)|Ministry of Agriculture]], Brazilian beef production grew on average 6.1% a year from 1990 to 2003, and reached 7.6 million [[tonnes]]. In 2003, Brazil exported over 1.4 million [[tonnes]] of beef, earning around $1.5 billion. Leather exports that year passed the $1 billion mark.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n=== Coffee ===\n{{Main|Coffee production in Brazil}}\n\n{{Expand section|date=January 2010}}\nCoffee is produced in states like S\u00e3o Paulo and Minas\n\n=== Cotton ===\n\n[[File:Algod\u00e3o Bahia 2003.jpg|thumb|Cotton planted in the cerrado region of Bahia.]]\n\nYield increases were sufficient to substantially increase output between the 1960s and the twenty-first century, despite reduced acreage.<ref name=sci1>{{cite web |url=http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0034-71402008000400002&script=sci_arttext |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o e exporta\u00e7\u00e3o de algod\u00e3o: efeitos de choques de oferta e de demanda. |language=Portuguese |authors=ALVES, Lucilio Rogerio Aparecido; BARROS, Geraldo Sant'Ana de Camargo; BACCHI, Mirian Rumenos Piedade. |work=Revista Brasileira de Economia, vol. 62, n\u00ba4, Rio de Janeiro |date=Oct\u2013Dec 2008 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514150401/http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0034-71402008000400002&script=sci_arttext |archivedate=14 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the 1990s production moved from the South and Southeast regions to the Center-West and to the West of Bahia. Exports began in 2001.<ref name=\"sci1\" /><ref name=\"abrapa\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abrapa.com.br/quemsomos.asp |title=Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Algod\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=ABRAPA |work=P\u00e1gina institucional |date= |accessdate=12 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017015144/http://www.abrapa.com.br/quemsomos.asp |archivedate=17 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil's entry in the cotton market led them to charge the US with illegal subsidies and tariffs. The Brazilian plea went to the [[World Trade Organization]] in 2002. WTO approved sanctions in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atarde.com.br/economia/noticia.jsf?id=1219976 |title=OMC habilita Brasil a aplicar san\u00e7\u00f5es aos Estados Unidos pelo algod\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=Not\u00edcia |work=Jornal [[A Tarde]] |date=31 August 2008 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903031543/http://www.atarde.com.br/economia/noticia.jsf?id=1219976 |archivedate=3 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/101126.htm |title=Algod\u00e3o: Brasil poder\u00e1 adotar retalia\u00e7\u00f5es comerciais contra Estados Unidos |language=Portuguese |last=Fiori |first=Mylena |work=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]] |date=4 June 2008 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160825/http://www.agrosoft.org.br/agropag/101126.htm |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.abrapa.com.br/jornais/834622802122876.pdf |title=A Saga do Algod\u00e3o: das primeiras lavouras \u00e0 a\u00e7\u00e3o na OMC |language=Portuguese |author1=COSTA, S\u00e9rgio Rodrigues |author2=BUENO, Miguel Garcia. |work=Rio de Janeiro: Insight Engenharia, 144p. : il. |date=2004 |accessdate=30 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206165303/http://abrapa.com.br/jornais/834622802122876.pdf |archivedate=6 February 2009 |df=dmy-all |isbn=85-98831-01-8}} (obra integral para download)</ref>\n\n=== Corn ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Corn'''<ref name=autogenerated4>[http://www.ipeadata.gov.br/ipeaweb.dll/ipeadata?371970046 Ipeadata] <!-- Bot generated title --> {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006213026/http://www.ipeadata.gov.br/ipeaweb.dll/ipeadata?371970046 |date=6 October 2007 }}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 8.67\n| 14.21\n| 20.37\n| 26.57\n| 32.32\n| 35.13\n|}\n\n[[File:Milharal novo Avare 021205 REFON.jpg|thumb|Cornfield, S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nBrazilian corn has two harvests per year. The main harvest is during the rainy season and a second, \"dry cultivation\" harvest follows during the dry season. In the South the main harvest is in late August; while in the Southeast and Center-West, it happens in October and November and in the Northeast, by year end. The second harvest is in Paran\u00e1, S\u00e3o Paulo and in the Center-West, in February and March.\n\nIn 2006 corn was planted on about thirteen million hectares, producing 41 million tons. Brazil was the third largest world producer, accounting for 6.1% of global production. Paran\u00e1 was Brazil's biggest producer, totaling 25.72%.\n\n=== Rice ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Rice'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 4.79\n| 7.55\n| 9.77\n| 11.04\n| 11.13\n| 13.19\n|}\n\n[[File:Arroz 097.jpg|thumb|Rice harvest, Rio do Sul, Santa Catarina.]]\n\nIn the 1980s Brazil evolved from exporting to importing rice in small quantities to meet domestic demand. In the following decade, it became one of the main importers, reaching two million tons, equivalent to 10% of domestic demand by 1997-8. [[Uruguay]] and [[Argentina]] are the main suppliers of the cereal to the country.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Arroz/ArrozIrrigadoBrasil/cap18.htm |title=Consumo, Mercado e Comercializa\u00e7\u00e3o do Arroz no Brasil. |language=Portuguese |last=Alon\u00e7o |first=Airton dos Santos |journal=Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o |number=3 |issn=1806-9207 |date=November 2005 |accessdate=1 October 2009 |display-authors=etal |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213073633/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Arroz/ArrozIrrigadoBrasil/cap18.htm |archivedate=13 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, farmers planted 3.845 million ha, decreasing by 2008, to 2.847 million. Production grew from 11.582 million tons to an estimated 12.177 million tons.<ref name=ori>Tabelas do cultivo do arroz no Brasil: [http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab101.htm \u00e1rea plantada] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420204536/http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab101.htm |date=20 April 2009 }}; [http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab103.htm produ\u00e7\u00e3o] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104084621/http://www.arroz.agr.br/site/estatisticas/html/tab103.htm |date=4 January 2010 }}, Portal Arroz Brasileiro, Accessed 30 September 2009</ref>\n\nProductivity per hectare has grown 61% since 1990. Production is concentrated in [[Rio Grande do Sul]], producing on average 48%.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/213229F7DBD76D9CE040A8C075024B3C{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Soybean ===\n{{See also|Deforestation in Brazil#Soybean production}}\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Soybean Production'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 0.20\n| 1.50\n| 15.15\n| 24.07\n| 32.82\n| 51.18\n|}\n\nSoybean production began in 1882. From the beginning of the 20th century soy was used for animal fodder. In 1941, grain production surpassed forage use, becoming the main focus. Brazilian [[soybean]] production increased more than 3000% between 1970 and 2005. Yield increased 37.8% from 1990 to 2005.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2132DF10897FBE12E040A8C075020289{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Soybean and soybean derivatives exports in 2005 alone earned over US$9 billion for Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/03.02.08_1.XLS |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-15 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314025354/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/03.02.08_1.XLS |archivedate=14 March 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe 2007/2008 harvest produced 60.1 million tons, surpassed only by the United States.\n\nBrazil's largest producers are Mato Grosso, Paran\u00e1 and Goi\u00e1s, with fifteen, nine and six million tons, respectively, in 2004\u20132006. [[Mato Grosso]] and [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]] together grow on average over 49% of the crop.\n\n=== Wheat ===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Wheat Production'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1989\n| 2000\n| 2005\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 0.71\n| 1.84\n| 2.70\n| 5.55\n| 1.72\n| 4.65\n|}\n\nTwo of Brazil's coldest states, [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]] and [[Rio Grande do Sul]], account for over 90% of wheat production.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2131AAF0F3255977E040A8C075025C45{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Brazil imports around US$700 million in wheat every year.<ref>http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/url/ITEM/2134AF4606C550C8E040A8C075023826{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/06.08.XLS|title=Wayback Machine|author=|date=12 September 2008|url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912173240/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/MAPA/ESTATISTICAS/AGRICULTURA_EM_NUMEROS_2005/06.08.XLS|archivedate=12 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Exporta%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20Peso%20Liquido.xls |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-05-06 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118005713/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Exporta%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20Peso%20Liquido.xls |archivedate=18 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Importa%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20US$%20FOB.xls |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-05-06 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118005915/http://www.agricultura.gov.br/arq_editor/file/vegetal/Estatistica/Importa%C3%A7%C3%B5es%20agropecu%C3%A1rias%20-%20Produtos%20selecionados%20-%20US$%20FOB.xls |archivedate=18 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Sugarcane ===\n{{See also|Ethanol fuel in Brazil}}\n\n[[File:Canaviais Sao Paulo 01 2008 06.jpg|thumb|Cane field in S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nDuring the colonial period, Brazil depended heavily on sugarcane and continued to lead world sugarcane production into the twenty-first century.\n\nProduction is concentrated (90%) in S\u00e3o Paulo, Alagoas, Pernambuco, Minas Gerais, Mato Grosso, Mato Grosso do Sul, Goi\u00e1s and Paran\u00e1.<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://odia.terra.com.br/economia/htm/geral_120564.asp|title=O Dia Online<!-- Bot generated title -->|author=|date=|website=terra.com.br|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070902135312/http://odia.terra.com.br/economia/htm/geral_120564.asp|archivedate=2 September 2007|df=dmy-all|access-date=30 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nBrazil harvested 558 million tonnes of sugarcane in 2007, representing a growth of 17.62% over 2006. For 2008, Brazil harvested 648,921,280 tonnes, of which total 89% was used for sugar and [[ethanol]] production. The other 11% was used for ''[[cacha\u00e7a]]'' and ''rapadura'' production, as animal feed and as seeds.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/dinheiro/ult91u396881.shtml Folha Online \u2013 Dinheiro \u2013 Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de \u00e1lcool e de a\u00e7\u00facar bater\u00e1 recorde em 2008, prev\u00ea Conab \u2013 29 April 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Ethanol]] production in 2008 was predicted to reach 26.4 billion litres.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nCompanhia Nacional de Abastecimento (CONAB)said that in 2007, sugarcane cultivated land increased by 12.3%, to 69,000 square kilometres.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Sugarcane Production'''<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Year'''\n| 1960\n| 1970\n| 1980\n| 1990\n| 2000\n| 2007\n|-\n| '''Million metric tons'''\n| 56.92\n| 79.75\n| 148.65\n| 262.67\n| 326.12\n| 558.50\n|}\n\n=== Tobacco ===\n\nBrazil is the world's second largest tobacco producer, and the largest exporter since 1993, with about 1.7 billion dollars of turnover.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=8473 |title=Tabaco representa 2% da exporta\u00e7\u00e3o brasileira, not\u00edcia, Andreoli MS&L, 14-08-2009 |language=Portuguese |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150806/http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=8473 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The largest export region is Rio Grande do Sul. The Southern region accounts for 95% of external production. It exports 60 to 70% of output.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cepa.epagri.sc.gov.br/agroindicadores/opiniao/analise_fumo.htm |title=Aspectos da Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Fumo em Santa Catarina |language=Portuguese |last=Marcondes |first=Tabajara |work=EPAGRI-SC |date= |accessdate=2 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402150048/http://cepa.epagri.sc.gov.br/agroindicadores/opiniao/analise_fumo.htm |archivedate=2 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Beans ===\n\n[[File:Feij\u00e3o MacLee 270506 2.JPG|thumb|Irrigated beans in Avare, S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nBrazil is the world's largest producer of beans, accounting for 16.3% of the total, 18.7 million tons in 2005, according to [[FAO]]. Historically most beans came from small producers. Yield in some cases exceeded three thousand kilos per ha.<ref name=emb2>{{cite journal |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Feijao/FeijaoIrrigadoNoroesteMG/index.htm |title=Cultivo do Feij\u00e3o Irrigado na Regi\u00e3o Noroeste de Minas Gerais |language=Portuguese |last=Wander |first=Alcido Elenor. |journal=Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o |number=5 |date=December 2005 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215095712/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Feijao/FeijaoIrrigadoNoroesteMG/index.htm |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBean acreage decreased from 1984 to 2004 by 25%, while output increased by 16%. It is cultivated throughout the country and harvests come year round.<ref name=emb2/>\n\nBrazil imports 100 thousand tons of beans per year.<ref name=emb2/>\n\n=== Floriculture and ornamentals ===\n\n[[File:Yellow and pink rose - Bras\u00edlia, Brazil.jpg|thumb|Example of Brazilian rose, in Brasilia.]]\n\nSome three thousand six hundred producers cultivate flowers and ornamental plants in an area of 4,800 ha.<ref name=sober>{{cite web |url=http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/12/01P062.pdf |title=Log\u00edstica de exporta\u00e7\u00e3o de flores no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Carlos Armando Soncin |website= |date= |accessdate=17 December 2009 |display-authors=etal |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101145652/http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/12/01P062.pdf |archivedate=1 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt employs about one hundred twenty thousand people, of which 80% are women, and about 18% are family farms.<ref name=florr>{{cite web |url=http://www.fit.ufsc.br/disciplinas_download.php?cod=954 |title=Panorama do agroneg\u00f3cio de flores e plantas ornamentais no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=FRAN\u00c7A, Carlos A. Machado de |author2=MAIA, Moacyr B. Rodrigues |work=Sociedade Brasileira de Economia, Administra\u00e7\u00e3o e Sociologia Rural |date=20\u201323 July 2008 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162222/http://www.fit.ufsc.br/disciplinas_download.php?cod=954 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe producers from fifteen states are represented by the Brazilian Institute of Floriculture (IBRAFLOR), with government support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibraflor.org/sis.interna.asp?pasta=1&pagina=1 |title=Hist\u00f3rico |language=Portuguese |author=institucional IBRAFLOR |website= |date= |accessdate=17 December 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFloriculture began in the 1870s, led by the son of {{Interlanguage link|Jean Baptiste Binot|pt}}, who had come to the country to decorate the [[Imperial Museum of Brazil|Imperial Palace]], and whose [[vivarium|orchidarium]] was internationally acknowledged. In 1893, Reggie Dierberger founded a flower company, which later became the Boettcher, pioneers of [[rose]] production.<ref name=florr/>\n\nIn 1948 Dutch immigrants founded a [[cooperative]] in [[Holambra]], a city that still hosts flower production.<ref name=florr/>\n\nSince 2000 the Program of Development of Flowers and Ornamental Plants of the Ministry of Agriculture began. The largest producer is S\u00e3o Paulo state, followed by Santa Catarina, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Cear\u00e1, Rio Grande do Sul, Minas Gerais, Rio de Janeiro, Paran\u00e1, Goi\u00e1s, Bahia, Esp\u00edrito Santo, Amazonas and Par\u00e1.<ref name=florr/>\n\n=== Fruits and perennials ===\n\n[[File:Planta\u00e7\u00e3o de pinhas.jpg|thumb|[[Sugar-apple]] plantation with an irrigated system, at the banks of the S\u00e3o Francisco River, Bahia.]]\n\nThe main fruits grown in Brazil are, in alphabetical order: [[Abiu]], [[a\u00e7a\u00ed]], [[acerola]], [[alligator-apple]], apple, [[atemoya]], [[bacaba]], [[bacuri]], banana, [[biriba]], [[blueberry]], [[brazil plum]], [[brazil nut]], [[breadfruit]], [[caj\u00e1]], [[camu camu]], [[cantaloupe]], [[cashew]], citrus (orange, lemon, [[Lime (fruit)|lime]], etc.), [[coconut]], [[cupua\u00e7u]], [[Common fig|fig]], [[guava]], [[grapes]], [[jambo]], [[jocote]], [[kiwi]], [[mangaba]], [[mango]], [[mangosteen]], [[mulberry]], [[muruci]], [[nectarine]], [[papaya]], [[passionfruit]], [[patawa]], [[peach]], pear, [[pequi]], [[persimmon]], [[physalis]], [[pineapple]], [[pine nut]]s, [[plum]], [[rambutan]], [[raspberry]], [[sapodilla]], [[sapote]], [[sorva]], [[soursop]], [[starfruit]], [[strawberry]], tucuma, [[walnut]], and [[watermelon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embrapa.br/kw_storage/keyword.2007-06-04.3509047076 |title=Rela\u00e7\u00e3o dos cultivares estudados |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa fruticultura |website= |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091219084110/http://www.embrapa.br/kw_storage/keyword.2007-06-04.3509047076 |archivedate=19 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 the fruit sector grossed 9.6 billion dollars \u2013 18% of Brazil's total. National production is higher than 38 million tons, cultivated on 3.4 million hectares. Between 1990 and 2004 exports grew 183% in value, 277% in quantity and 915% net.<ref name=ttu>{{cite web |url=http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/2/747.pdf |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es Brasileiras de Frutas: diversifica\u00e7\u00e3o ou concentra\u00e7\u00e3o de produtos e destinos? |language=Portuguese |authors=FILHO, Miguel Henrique da Cunha. CARVALHO, Rosemeiry Melo. |work=Palestra, Sober.org |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129073557/http://www.sober.org.br/palestra/2/747.pdf |archivedate=29 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nEvery ten thousand dollars invested in fruit production generates three direct jobs and two indirect jobs.<ref name=ttu/>\n\nBrazil is the world's third largest fruit producer, behind China (157 million tons) and India (with 54 million). Oranges and bananas account for 60% of Brazilian output.<ref name=iai>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.redetec.org.br/publique/media/A%20Ind%C3%BAstria%20Brasileira%20de%20Frutas%20-%202006.doc |title=A Ind\u00fastria Brasileira das Frutas \u2013 Amplia\u00e7\u00e3o e Conquista de Mercados |language=Portuguese |website= |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706161306/http://www.redetec.org.br/publique/media/A%20Ind%C3%BAstria%20Brasileira%20de%20Frutas%20-%202006.doc |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Brazilian Agency for the Promotion of Exports and Investments (Apex-Brasil), the IBRAF and [[Carrefour]] supermarket partnered to develop the Brazilian Fruit Festival, with editions in countries such as [[Poland]] and [[Portugal]], from 2004 to 2007.<ref name=iai/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brazilianfruit.org.br/brazilian_fruit_festival/brazilian_fruit_festival.asp |title=Programa Horizontal de Promo\u00e7\u00e3o das Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es Brasileiras |language=Portuguese |work=p\u00e1gina oficial do Brazilian Fruit Festival |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612192040/http://www.brazilianfruit.org.br/brazilian_fruit_festival/brazilian_fruit_festival.asp |archivedate=12 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Banana ====\n[[File:Musa 031.jpg|thumb|Banana plantation in irrigation project, Rio S. Francisco, Bahia.]]\n\n[[Banana]] is produced across the country.<ref name=emb3/> It is the second-largest fruit crop. In 2003, 510 thousand hectares were planted, yielding 6.5 million tons, repeated in 2004.<ref name=\"iai\" /> In descending order, the largest producers were S\u00e3o Paulo (with one million one hundred seventy-eight thousand tons), Bahia (764 thousand tons) and Par\u00e1 (697 thousand tons).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0100-29452005000100037&script=sci_arttext |title=Nehmi et al., 2003, citados em \"An\u00e1lises t\u00e9cnica e econ\u00f4mica da cultura da bananeira 'Ma\u00e7\u00e3' (Musa spp.) na regi\u00e3o noroeste do Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo\". |language=Portuguese |author=ALMEIDA, Mariley de Castro Almeida da |author2=TARSITANO, Maria Aparecida Anselmo |author3=BOLIANI, Aparecida Concei\u00e7\u00e3o |work=Revista Brasileira de Fruticultura, vol. 27, n\u00ba 1, Jaboticabal |date=April 2005 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514151608/http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0100-29452005000100037&script=sci_arttext |archivedate=14 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Cocoa ====\n[[File:Cacao.jpeg|thumb|Cocoa plant in Ilheus, Bahia.]]\n\nCocoa was once one of Brazil's main export crops, particularly for Bahia. Production gradually diminished. In 2002 Bahia accounted for 84% of Brazil's cocoa, according to IBGE, planting more than 548 thousand hectares planted with the crop.<ref name=cacao>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpatc.embrapa.br/publicacoes_2004/doc-72.pdf |title=Import\u00e2ncia Econ\u00f4mica e Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o da Cultura do Cacau no Brasil e na Regi\u00e3o dos Tabuleiros Costeiros da Bahia entre 1990 e 2002. |language=Portuguese |author1=CUENCA, Manuel Alberto Guti\u00e9rrez |author2=NAZ\u00c1RIO, Cristiano Campos |work=Documentos / Embrapa Tabuleiros Costeiros, Aracaju, 25 p. : il. |date=2004 |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122180008/http://www.cpatc.embrapa.br/publicacoes_2004/doc-72.pdf |archivedate=22 November 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil changed from exporting to importing cocoa in 1992. According to FAO the country, between 1990 and 2003, fell from ninth to seventeenth in the main world producers' ranking.<ref name=cacao/>\n\nBahian cocoa shows how a pest and the lack of plant health care may affect a crop. In this case a disease called [[witch's broom]] was directly responsible for falling production, which started in the year 1989.<ref name=ceplac1>{{cite web |url=http://www.ceplac.gov.br/radar/mercado_cacau.htm |title=Mercado de Cacau. |language=Portuguese |author=Antonio C\u00e9sar Costa Zugaib |author2=Almir Martins dos Santos |author3=Lindolfo Pereira dos Santos Filho |website= |date= |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402071808/http://www.ceplac.gov.br/radar/mercado_cacau.htm |archivedate=2 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A severe decline endured until 1999, when resistant varieties were introduced. Despite this, in 2007 Bahian production started to decline again, whilst the Paraense raised its share.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagri.ba.gov.br/noticias.asp?qact=view&notid=11201 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de cacau recua 68% |language=Portuguese |author=Seagri |website= |date=15 August 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706155527/http://www.seagri.ba.gov.br/noticias.asp?qact=view&notid=11201 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecoviagem.uol.com.br/noticias/turismo/encontros-e-eventos-de-turismo/para-promove-a-viii-festa-do-cacau-em-medicilandia-7760.asp |title=Par\u00e1 promove a VIII Festa do Cacau em Medicil\u00e2ndia |language=Portuguese |author=Ecoviagem |website= |date=16 November 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706154943/http://ecoviagem.uol.com.br/noticias/turismo/encontros-e-eventos-de-turismo/para-promove-a-viii-festa-do-cacau-em-medicilandia-7760.asp |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Citrus ====\n[[File:Laranjal Cutrale 050806 REFON 3.jpg|thumb|Orange field, in S. Paulo]]\n\n[[Citrus]] includes oranges, [[Lime (fruit)|lime]]s, [[tangerine]]s, lemons, etc. Oranges are the most relevant in agriculture.<ref name=iaclar>{{cite web |url=http://www.iac.sp.gov.br/Tecnologias/Citros/Citros.htm |title=CITROS: principais informa\u00e7\u00f5es e recomenda\u00e7\u00f5es de cultivo |language=Portuguese |authors=Dirceu de Mattos Junior, Jos\u00e9 Dagoberto De Negri, Jos\u00e9 Orlando de Figueiredo e Jorgino Pompeu Junior |work=IAC |date=26 April 2005 |accessdate=12 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426082641/http://www.iac.sp.gov.br/Tecnologias/Citros/Citros.htm |archivedate=26 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 Brazil produced 18.3 million tons of oranges, 45% of the fruit harvest.<ref name=iai/>\n\nS\u00e3o Paulo state accounts for 79% of orange production and is the largest producer and exporter of [[orange juice]], responsible for half of global production. 97% is exported.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=259 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o Agr\u00edcola Municipal \u2013 2003 |language=Portuguese |author=IBGE |work=Not\u00edcia: Milho tem maior aumento, mas soja continua em primeiro lugar no ranking da produ\u00e7\u00e3o agr\u00edcola brasileira de 2003 |date= |accessdate=12 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516221040/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/presidencia/noticias/noticia_visualiza.php?id_noticia=259 |archivedate=16 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil and the US are the world's largest citrus producers, with 45% of the total, while South Africa, Spain and [[Israel]] compete in oranges and tangerines.<ref name=iaclar/>\n\nBrazilian orange juice is equivalent to 80% of world exports, the largest market share for any Brazilian agricultural product.<ref name=\"estadao\" />\n\n=== Forestry and wood ===\n\n[[File:Fazenda pinus.JPG|thumb|Pine plantation for cellulose production, Bocaina do Sul, Santa Catarina.]]\n\nCommercial forestry produced 65% of Brazilian wood products in 2003, up from 52% the year earlier as it gradually replaced traditional gathering.<ref name=ibgemad/>\n\n[[Eucalyptus]] is the most popular species for reforestation. It is harvested for [[plywood]] and [[cellulose]] production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ipef.br/publicacoes/scientia/nr20/cap05.pdf |title=Crescimento e Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Madeira de Eucalipto |language=Portuguese |authors=SIM\u00d5ES, Jo\u00e3o Walter. et allii |work=IPEF n.20, p. 77\u201397 |date=June 1980 |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728115548/http://www.ipef.br/publicacoes/scientia/nr20/cap05.pdf |archivedate=28 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2001 the country cultivated three million hectares with this tree; another 1.8 million hectares were planted with [[pine]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbs.org.br/setor_florestal.htm |title=Setor Florestal Brasileiro, dados socio-econ\u00f4micos |language=Portuguese |author=Sociedade Brasileira de Silvicultura |website= |date=2001 |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090906185658/http://www.sbs.org.br/setor_florestal.htm |archivedate=6 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> a species better adapted to the climate of the South and Southeast.<ref name=hist>{{cite web |url=http://www.almg.gov.br/Publicacoes/Eucalipto/brasil_minas.pdf |title=O Eucalipto no Brasil |language=Portuguese |work=Publica\u00e7\u00f5es; ALMG (institucional) |date= |accessdate=14 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922113910/http://www.almg.gov.br/Publicacoes/Eucalipto/brasil_minas.pdf |archivedate=22 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nNative species have received increasing attention as an alternative to eucalyptus and pine. In 2007, the National Plan of Forestry with Native Species and Agroforestry Systems (PENSAF) was launched, in an integrated effort between the [[Ministry of the Environment (Brazil)|Ministry of the Environment]] (MMA) and the [[Ministry of Agriculture (Brazil)|Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock and Food Supply]] (MAPA), among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ideflor.pa.gov.br/files/u1/Plano_Nacional_de_Silvicultura.pdf|title=Ideflor-bio|author=|date=|website=Ideflor-bio|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205083633/http://www.ideflor.pa.gov.br/files/u1/Plano_Nacional_de_Silvicultura.pdf|archivedate=5 December 2014|df=dmy-all|access-date=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 the country produced 2.149 million tons of wood for [[charcoal]]; 75% from Minas Gerais. Charcoal from vegetable gathering added 2.227 million tons, the largest part (35%) from Par\u00e1. Firewood production occupied 47.232 million square meters, with Bahia the biggest producer.<ref name=ibgemad/>\n\nBrazil is the seventh largest global producer of cellulose of all kinds, and the largest of short fiber cellulose. In 2005 the country exported 5.2 million tons and produced 6 million, generating revenues of 3.4 billion dollars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://noticias.qprocura.com.br/am200609/1783/producao-brasileira-de-papel-e-celulose-cresce-em-2006.html |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o brasileira de papel e celulose cresce em 2006 |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |work=QProcura |date=23 September 2006 |accessdate=14 October 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the Management of Public Forests Law was enacted. It subsidizes legal wood production to reduce illegal deforestation, and encouraging the timber sector to adopt sustainable practices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greenpeace.org/brasil/pt/Noticias/lula-sanciona-lei-que-estimula/ |title=Lula sanciona lei que estimula produ\u00e7\u00e3o de madeira legal e a presen\u00e7a do Estado na Amaz\u00f4nia |language=Portuguese |work=Greenpeace |date=3 March 2006 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728035533/http://www.greenpeace.org/brasil/pt/Noticias/lula-sanciona-lei-que-estimula/ |archivedate=28 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Vegetables ===\n\n[[File:Horticulture in Almirante Tamandar\u00e9 countryside.JPG|thumb|Horticulture in Almirante Tamandar\u00e9 countryside.]]\n\nBrazilian vegetable production in 2004 was estimated at 11.696 billion [[Reais]]. It occupied 176 thousand hectares, yielding 16.86 million tons. The major producing regions were the South and Southeast, with 75% of the total. This sector employs between eight and ten million workers.<ref name=horta>{{cite web |url=http://www.abhorticultura.com.br/Biblioteca/Default.asp?id=4925 |title=Panorama Atual da Cadeia de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Hortali\u00e7as no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Paulo C\u00e9sar Tavares de Melo |work=palestra |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150613/http://www.abhorticultura.com.br/Biblioteca/Default.asp?id=4925 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe vegetable section of Embrapa, with headquarters in Distrito Federal, was created in 1978 and in 1981 renamed the National Center of Research on Vegetables (CNPH).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/historico.htm |title=Hist\u00f3rico, Embrapa Hortali\u00e7as |language=Portuguese |author=institucional |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091211214338/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/historico.htm |archivedate=11 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It occupies 487 ha with laboratories, administrative and support buildings, with 45 ha devoted to experimental vegetable production, of which 7 support organic production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/instalacoes.htm |title=Instala\u00e7\u00f5es, Embrapa Hortali\u00e7as |language=Portuguese |work=institucional |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215111033/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/a_unidade/instalacoes.htm |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Brazil exported 366,213 tons of vegetable crops, which yielded 240 million dollars. Among these, thirteen thousand tons of potatoes, twenty thousand tons of tomatoes, 37 thousand tons of onions. Other export vegetables included [[ginger]], [[pea]]s, [[cucumber]]s, [[capsicum]], [[Mustard plant|mustard]], carrots and garlic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/hortalicas_em_numeros/exportacoes_brasileiras_hortalicas_2000_2007.pdf |title=Exporta\u00e7\u00f5es Brasileiras de Hortali\u00e7as, 2000\u20132007, dados, Embrapa |language=Portuguese |work=institucional |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209101627/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/paginas/hortalicas_em_numeros/exportacoes_brasileiras_hortalicas_2000_2007.pdf |archivedate=9 December 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Tomato ====\n[[File:Planta\u00e7\u00e3o tomate 250306 2.JPG|thumb|Tomato plantation, Arandu]]\n\nBrazilian tomato production ranked sixth globally and first in South America in 2000. 1999 output reached a record of 1.29 million tons for tomato pulp.<ref name=tometeemb>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpafro.embrapa.br/embrapa/Artigos/tomateiro.htm |title=O tomateiro tipo industrial no Brasil. |language=Portuguese |authors=CARVALHO, Jos\u00e9 Orestes M. et allii., Embrapa |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215075058/http://www.cpafro.embrapa.br/embrapa/Artigos/tomateiro.htm |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, production increased to 3.3 million tons, ranking ninth globally behind China, US, [[Turkey]], Italy, [[Egypt]], [[India]], Spain and [[Iran]]. The largest states in 2004 were Goi\u00e1s (871 thousand tons), S\u00e3o Paulo (749 thousand tons), Minas Gerais (622 thousand), Rio de Janeiro (203 thousand) and Bahia (193 thousand).<ref name=tomate>{{cite web |url=http://www.conab.gov.br/conabweb/download/cas/especiais/Tomate_21_08_2006.pdf |title=A Cultura do Tomate. |language=Portuguese |author=CHAVES, Alex Musialowski. |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923210059/http://www.conab.gov.br/conabweb/download/cas/especiais/Tomate_21_08_2006.pdf |archivedate=23 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSuccess in Goi\u00e1s' and Minas Gerais' Cerrado allowed the region to expand from 31% to 84% of production, from 1996 to 2001. The development of localized hybrid varieties raised productivity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unicamp.br/unicamp/unicamp_hoje/ju/dezembro2004/ju276pag08.html |title=Tese de doutorado revela conflitos e interesses na produ\u00e7\u00e3o de tomate |language=Portuguese |author=not\u00edcia por Carmo Gallo Neto |work=Jornal da [[Unicamp]], ed. 276 |date=13\u201323 December 2004 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925021819/http://www.unicamp.br/unicamp/unicamp_hoje/ju/dezembro2004/ju276pag08.html |archivedate=25 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Onion ====\n[[File:Cebola roxa.JPG|thumb|Sample of red onions.]]\n\nSmall farmers are responsible for more than half of the country's production.<ref name=embceb>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/sistprod/cebola/mercado_e_comercializacao.htm |title=Sistema de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de Cebola (Allium cepa L) Mercado e Comercializa\u00e7\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |authors=VILELA, Nirlene Junqueira. et allii. |website= |date= |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217075705/http://www.cnph.embrapa.br/sistprod/cebola/mercado_e_comercializacao.htm |archivedate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Juazeiro]], in Bahia, and [[Petrolina]], in Pernambuco are neighboring towns, separated by [[S\u00e3o Francisco River]]. They have the highest yield, using irrigation to achieve 24 tons per hectare, versus the Brazilian average of seventeen.<ref name=embceb/> In 2006, the two cities 200 thousand tons surpassed that of the other states, behind only Santa Catarina (355 thousand tons).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=2240 |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o de cebola da Bahia e Pernambuco em 2006 ser\u00e1 a segunda maior do pa\u00eds |language=Portuguese |author=Embrapa |website= |date=16 May 2006 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150802/http://www.agronline.com.br/agronoticias/noticia.php?id=2240 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Cassava ===\n\nBrazil is the world's second largest cassava producer, at 12.7%. Exports comprise only .5%. Average exports in 2000 and 2001 were thirteen million, one hundred thousand tons, generating revenue above six hundred million dollars.<ref name=embmand>{{cite journal |url=http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Mandioca/mandioca_cerrados/importancia.htm |series=Cultivo da Mandioca para a Regi\u00e3o do Cerrado |language=Portuguese |author1=Luciano da Silva Souza |author2=Josefino de Freitas Fialho |title=Import\u00e2ncia Econ\u00f4mida |journal=Embrapa Mandioca e Fruticultura. Sistemas de Produ\u00e7\u00e3o |number=8 |issn=1678-8796 |date=January 2003 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214040834/http://sistemasdeproducao.cnptia.embrapa.br/FontesHTML/Mandioca/mandioca_cerrados/importancia.htm |archivedate=14 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt is cultivated in all regions and is used for both human and animal consumption. [[Manioc]] is farmed for human consumption, including flour and [[starch]]. That production chain generates about a million direct jobs,<ref name=embmand/> and some ten million jobs overall.<ref name=entmand>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.diap.org.br/index.php/agencia-diap/7854-producao-da-mandioca-gera-10-milhoes-de-empregos-diretos-e-indiretos |title=Produ\u00e7\u00e3o da mandioca gera 10 milh\u00f5es de empregos diretos e indiretos |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia DIAP |work=Departamento Intersindical de Assessoria Parlamentar |date=1 March 2009 |accessdate=20 May 2010 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727234851/http://www.diap.org.br/index.php/agencia-diap/7854-producao-da-mandioca-gera-10-milhoes-de-empregos-diretos-e-indiretos |archivedate=27 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nForecasts for 2002 were for 22.6 million tons on 1.7 million hectares. The largest producers were Par\u00e1 (17.9%), Bahia (16.7%), Paran\u00e1 (14.5%), Rio Grande do Sul (5.6%) and Amazonas (4.3%) .<ref name=embmand/>\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== Slave and child labor ===\n\n[[File:CarvoariaIrregularByMarcoEvangelista.jpg|thumb|Inspectors from the Ministry of Labor and Federal Police officers at the scene of a clandestine charcoal operation, places where most illegal working situations occur.]]\n\nAccording to data from the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor of the United States]], twenty-first century Brazil ranks third in occurrences of illegal working arrangements (tied with [[India]] and [[Bangladesh]]). Eight of thirteen violations were prevalent in agribusiness, especially in livestock, [[sisal]], sugar cane, rice, tobacco and charcoal. Despite its position, the country's performance was praised, and between 1995 and 2009 approximately 35,000 workers were freed from degrading conditions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=1&local=1&id=2650266&action=noticias |title=Brasil \u00e9 terceiro com maior \u00edndice de trabalho escravo e infantil |language=Portuguese |last=Kohlmann |first=Luciane |work=RBS |date=11 September 2009 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090913004521/http://www.clicrbs.com.br/canalrural/jsp/default.jspx?uf=1&local=1&id=2650266&action=noticias |archivedate=13 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO) recognized the Brazilian effort to fight such practices, which focus on preventing/correcting misbehavior via a system of fines.\n\nAmong the causes of illegal working arrangements were poverty and misinformation.\n\nA Constitutional Amendment Proposal (PEC), would compensate landowners for losses resulting from ending such practices.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.reporterbrasil.com.br/clipping.php?id=700 |title=OIT reconhece esfor\u00e7os do Brasil no combate ao trabalho escravo e infantil, diz ministro do TST. |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |work=Rep\u00f3rter Brasil |date=1 March 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706154243/http://www.reporterbrasil.com.br/clipping.php?id=700 |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 however, the [[Bureau of International Labor Affairs]] issued a ''[[List of Goods Produced by Child Labor or Forced Labor]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dol.gov/ilab/reports/child-labor/list-of-goods/|title=List of Goods Produced by Child Labor or Forced Labor|author=|date=|website=www.dol.gov|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610003351/http://www.dol.gov/ilab/reports/child-labor/list-of-goods/|archivedate=10 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> where Brazil was classified as one of the 74 countries involved in [[child labor]] and [[forced labor]] practices. The report lists 16 products including [[cotton]], cashews, pineapples, rice and sugarcane the production of which still employs children.\n\n=== Environmental impacts ===\n{{See|Environmental issues in Brazil}}\n{{See|Deforestation in Brazil}}\n[[File:Vo\u00e7oroca (23 12 24S - 48 47 59W) - REFON 4.JPG|thumb|Gully in the state of S\u00e3o Paulo.]]\n\nBrazil's agricultural sector and [[deforestation]] account for 75% of its gas emissions responsible for [[climate change]].<ref name=\"Brighter Green\">Mia MacDonald and Justine Simon (2010) Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change: Brazil's Agricultural Revolution. [http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 Brighter Green] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063336/http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 |date=6 June 2011 }}, 2.</ref> For this reason, initiatives were adopted to reduce emissions, mostly by reducing deforestation. The so-called \"Soybean Moratorium\", the Agroecological Zoning for Sugar Cane, and the use of [[fertigation]] are examples.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ictsd.org/i/news/pontes/57140/ |title=O papel da agricultura brasileira nas mudan\u00e7as clim\u00e1ticas |language=Portuguese |author=Luiz Fernando do Amaral |work=Pontes \u2022 Volume 5 \u2022 N\u00famero 4 |date=October 2009 |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726170939/http://ictsd.org/i/news/pontes/57140/ |archivedate=26 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil's [[greenhouse gas]] emissions from agriculture increased 41 percent between 1990 and 2005.<ref>\"Brazil Throws Out Another Climate Challenge Updating Greenhouse Gas Inventory,\" World Wildlife Fund, 27 November 2009. http://wwf.panda.org {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110813183721/http://wwf.panda.org |date=13 August 2011 }}.</ref> Cattle are a major factor. An estimate carried out by [[Friends of the Earth|Friends of the Earth-Amazonia]] ({{Interlanguage link multi|Amigos da Terra - Amaz\u00f4nia Brasileira|pt}}), the Brazilian National Institute for Space Research (INPE) and the [[University of Bras\u00edlia]] concluded that fully half came from cattle.<ref>Bustamante, Mercedes, C. Nobre, and R. Smeraldi. \"Estimating Recent Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Cattle Raising in Brazil,\" S\u00e3o Paulo: Amigos da Terra \u2013 Amaz\u00f4nia Brasileira, National Institute for Space Research, Universidad de Bras\u00edlia, 2009, 1.</ref> If all parts of the \"cattle chain\" had been included, the researchers add, an even higher proportion of greenhouse gases would have been attributed to cattle.<ref name=\"Brighter Green\"/>\n\nCattle and soy production are concentrated in the [[Legal Amazon]] and [[Cerrado]] grasslands regions, and have resulted in considerable [[biodiversity loss]], [[deforestation]] and [[water pollution]].<ref>Mia MacDonald and Justine Simon (2010) Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change: Brazil's Agricultural Revolution. [http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 Brighter Green] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063336/http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 |date=6 June 2011 }}, 1.</ref> As of 2007, about 74 million cattle, or 40 percent of Brazil's herd, were living in what is known as the \"Legal Amazon.\"<ref>Smeraldi, Roberto and Peter H. May. \"The Cattle Realm: A New Phase in the Livestock Colonization of Brazilian Amazonia,\" Highlights in English. S\u00e3o Paulo: Amigos da Terra \u2013 Amaz\u00f4nia Brasileira, 2008, 4. [http://www.amazonia.org.br www.amazonia.org.br.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115022408/http://amazonia.org.br/ |date=15 January 2011 }}</ref> Almost one million square km (386,000 sq mi), or nearly half of the [[Cerrado]], has been burned and is now cattle pasture, or is cultivated for soybeans, corn (both primary ingredients in livestock feed), and sugarcane.<ref>Simone de Lima and Justine Simon (2010) Brazil: Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change. [https://www.youtube.com/user/BrighterGreenNY#p/u/2/_X7FWuvsWi0 Brighter Green] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324211918/https://www.youtube.com/user/BrighterGreenNY |date=24 March 2017 }}, 1.</ref> According to Washington Novaes, \"if we consider the viable fragments of the Cerrado, those with at least two continuous hectares (5 acres), only 5 percent of it is left. It's a very severe level of habitat loss.\"<ref>Mia MacDonald and Justine Simon (2010) \"Cattle, Soyanization, and Climate Change: Brazil's Agricultural Revolution\". [http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 Brighter Green] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063336/http://brightergreen.org/brightergreen.php?id=24 |date=6 June 2011 }}, 10.</ref> At least one quarter of Brazilian grain is grown in [[Cerrado]].\n\n==== Soil erosion ====\nA large part of the Southeast and Northeast region of the country is made up of [[granite|granitic]] and [[gneiss]] rock formations, covered by a layer of [[regolith]], very susceptible to [[soil erosion]] and [[gully]] formation. Bertoni and Neto point out this condition as one of Brazil's highest environmental dangers, and a large part of them result from human activities.<ref name=ddi>{{Cite journal |title=An\u00e1lise da erodibilidade de saprolitos de gnaisse |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=1055\u20131062 |language=Portuguese |author1=F. MoraisI |author2=L. A. P. BacellarII |author3=F. G. Sobreira |journal=Revista Brasileira de Ci\u00eancia do Solo vol.28 no.6 Vi\u00e7osa |date=Nov\u2013Dec 2004 |df=dmy-all |doi=10.1590/S0100-06832004000600014 }}</ref>\n\n[[Soil erosion]] removes nutrients and causes the loss of structure, texture and the decrease of infiltration rates and water retention.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnpma.embrapa.br/analise_econ/ |title=Custos econ\u00f4micos da eros\u00e3o do solo: estimativa pelo m\u00e9todo do custo de reposi\u00e7\u00e3o de nutrientes |language=Portuguese |author1=Jo\u00e3o Fernando Marques |author2=Carlos Benjamin Pazzianotto |website= |date= |accessdate=5 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215105420/http://www.cnpma.embrapa.br/analise_econ/ |archivedate=15 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[plough|Plowing]] and [[herbicide]]s to control undesirable weeds leave the soil exposed and susceptible to erosion \u2013 either by loss of topsoil (which is richer in nutrients), or from gullies. The lost soil fills rivers and reservoirs with [[silt]]. One solution is [[no-till farming]], a practice not in wide use.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agrisus.org.br/artigos.asp?cod=19 |title=Plantio Direto e Desenvolvimento Sustent\u00e1vel |language=Portuguese |author=Bernardo Van Raij |website= |date= |accessdate=11 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301115817/http://www.agrisus.org.br/artigos.asp?cod=19 |archivedate=1 March 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Pesticide ====\nThe world's four thousand agrochemicals are produced in about 15,000 different formulations, 8,000 of which are licensed in Brazil. They include [[insecticide]]s, [[fungicide]]s, [[herbicide]]s, [[vermifuge]]s, and also [[solvent]]s and sanitizers. They are widely used to protect crops from pests, disease and invading species. Indiscriminate use causes unnecessary accumulation of those substances in the soil, water (springs, [[groundwater]], reservoirs) and air.<ref name=tudotox>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sigrh.sp.gov.br/sigrh/ARQS/RELATORIO/CRH/CBH-ALPA/1121/uso_de_agrotoxicos_na_agricultura.html |title=Uso de agrot\u00f3xicos na agricultura |language=Portuguese |author=Relatorio SIGRH-SP |website= |date= |accessdate=12 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160444/http://www.sigrh.sp.gov.br/sigrh/ARQS/RELATORIO/CRH/CBH-ALPA/1121/uso_de_agrotoxicos_na_agricultura.html |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBrazil uses an average of 3.2&nbsp;kg of agrochemicals per hectare \u2013 ranking tenth globally, in some studies, and fifth, in others. S\u00e3o Paulo state is Brazil's largest user, and the largest producer, comprising 80% of the total. Mitigation techniques include farmer education, and the development of resistant species, better farming techniques, biological pest control, among others.<ref name=tudotox/>\n\nIn 2007 tomatoes, lettuce and strawberries showed the highest rates of contamination by agrochemicals. Farmer awareness is low and few comply with rules on the use of these substances, such as Individual Protection Equipment (EPI).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rel-uita.org/sindicatos/trabalhador_rural_agrotoxicos.htm |title=Trabalhador rural \u00e9 o mais atingido por contamina\u00e7\u00e3o |language=Portuguese |author=Bernardo Van Raij |website= |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727211840/http://www.rel-uita.org/sindicatos/trabalhador_rural_agrotoxicos.htm |archivedate=27 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to information from [[National Health Surveillance Agency|Anvisa]], Brazilian farming uses at least ten types of agrochemicals prohibited in other markets, such as the [[European Union]] and the US.<ref>FORMENTI, L\u00edgia. (30 de maio de 2010). \"Brasil se torna o principal destino de agrot\u00f3xicos banidos no exterior\". The State of S.Paulo</ref> In September 2019, Brazil's Agriculture Ministry approved 63 pesticides for commercial use as the government seeks to decrease a backlog of applications for new agricultural chemicals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-agriculture-pesticides-idUSKBN1W22HQ|title=Brazil clears new pesticides as government aims to speed approvals|date=2019-09-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-18|language=en}}</ref> According to an investigation by Unearthed, more than 1,200 pesticides and weedkillers, including 193 containing chemicals banned in the EU, have been registered in Brazil between 2016 and 2019.<ref>[https://unearthed.greenpeace.org/2019/06/12/jair-bolsonaro-brazil-pesticides/ Brazil pesticide approvals soar]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/jun/12/hundreds-new-pesticides-approved-brazil-under-bolsonaro Hundreds of new pesticides approved]</ref>\n\n==== Genetically modified crops ====\n{{Main|Genetically modified crops}}[[File:Manifesta\u00e7\u00e3o pro milho transg\u00eanico (Antonio Cruz) 20mar07.jpg|thumb|Brasilia, 2007: Protesters call for liberation from transgenic maize.]]\n\nThe country is the third largest user in the world in growing [[genetically modified crops]]. The main commodities using this [[biotechnology]] are soy, cotton and, since 2008, maize.<ref name=deftrans>{{Cite web |url=http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=28329 |title=Estudo confirma que agricultura transg\u00eanica beneficia meio ambiente no Brasil |language=Portuguese |author=Portal do Agroneg\u00f3cio (not\u00edcia) |website= |date=9 February 2009 |accessdate=12 December 2009 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522211134/http://www.portaldoagronegocio.com.br/conteudo.php?id=28329 |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSeveral national and international [[NGOs]], such as [[Greenpeace]], [[Landless Workers' Movement|MST]] or Contag, are opposed to the practice. Criticisms include market loss, negative environmental impacts and dominance by large businesses. Entities linked to agribusiness, however, counter with the results of studies carried out by the Brazilian Association of Seeds and Saplings (Abrasem) in 2007 and 2008, affirming \"social-environmental advantages observed in the other countries which have adopted agricultural biotechnology far longer\".<ref name=deftrans/>\n\nFederal Justice decided that foods containing more than 1 percent of modified genes must be labeled to inform consumers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.direito2.com.br/abr/2007/nov/30/consumo-consciente-de-informacoes |title=Consumo consciente de informa\u00e7\u00f5es |language=Portuguese |author=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |website= |date=30 November 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519223339/http://www.direito2.com.br/abr/2007/nov/30/consumo-consciente-de-informacoes |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Future risks for Agriculture and Environment ====\nThe deforestation of the Amazon Rainforest has many negative impacts, among others, on the Agriculture in Brazil who is one of those who promote the deforestation. One of the problems is that in some point the deforestation can reach a tipping point after which it will continue by itself and can not be stopped. This is because half of the rain of the forest is produced by the forest so, when there is less forest there is less rain what harm the forest. It is difficult to say when exactly it will be passed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=A. Nobre |first1=Carlos |last2=Sampaio |first2=Gilvan |last3=Borma |first3=Laura |last4=Carlos Castilla-Rubio |first4=Juan |last5=S. Silva |first5=Jos\u00e9 |last6=Cardoso |first6=Manoel |title=Land-use and climate change risks in the Amazon and the need of a novel sustainable development paradigm |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=113 |issue=39 |pages=10759\u201310768 |date=27 September 2016 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1605516113 |pmid=27638214 |pmc=5047175 |bibcode=2016PNAS..11310759N }}</ref>\n\n===== Impacts on water supply =====\nThe Amazon river basin alone, which covers 48% of the country's territory, accounts for 75% of Brazil's freshwater resources.<ref name=\"alto tiete, p.8\">Formiga Johnson ''et al.'' (June 2005), ''op. cit.'', p.8</ref> The deforestation of the Amazon rainforest has big impacts on the freshwater supply of [[Brazil]]. This harm among others, the agriculture in Brazil which is one of those who promote the deforestation. In the future, it can impact more severely, water supply in Brazil and to other countries: [[Uruguay]], [[Argentina]], [[Paraguay]] and the [[United States]]. This is for two causes:\n\n1. The rainforest provides much of the rainfall in [[Brazil]] even in areas far from it. Deforestation, have already increased the impacts of the droughts of 2005, 2010, and [[2014\u201317 Brazilian drought]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=WELCH |first1=CRAIG |title=How Amazon forest loss may affect water\u2014and climate\u2014far away |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2018/11/how-cutting-the-amazon-forest-could-affect-weather/ |website=National Geographic Society |publisher=National Geographic Society |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n2. The rainforest by inducing rainfall and helping water storage provide water to the rivers that give water to Brazil and others countries.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Joe |last2=Sanchez |first2=Erica |title=World's Water Could Become Scarce if the Amazon Rainforest Is Destroyed |url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/amazon-rainforest-water-crisis/ |website=Global Citizen |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Larson |first1=Christina |last2=Savarese |first2=Mauricio |title=Scientists warn new Brazil president may smother rainforest |url=https://phys.org/news/2018-11-scientists-brazil-smother-rainforest.html |website=Fhys.org |publisher=Science X Network |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Amazon rainforest create 50-75 percent of its own precipitation. It supllies water well beyond the Amazon Basin: Amazon rainfall and rivers feeding regions that generate 70 percent of South America's GDP. Models indicate that moisture from the Amazon influences rainfall as far away as the Western United States and Central America.<ref>{{cite web |last1=A. Butler |first1=Rhett |title=The Importance of the Amazon Rainforest |url=https://rainforests.mongabay.com/amazon/amazon_importance.htm |website=Mongabay |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[2014\u201317 Brazilian drought]] have a big impact on the agriculture in Brazil. \"The Agricultural Economy Institute\" stated that 2014 accounted for S\u00e3o Paulo's worst agricultural losses in half a century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.as-coa.org/articles/brazil-update-historic-drought-takes-toll-agriculture|title=Brazil Update: Historic Drought Takes Toll on Agriculture|last=Glickhouse|first=Rachel|website=AS/COA|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nThe irregular rainfall pattern contributed to a reduction in crop production through the drought period, due to an atmospheric blockage which prevented a cold front from advancing over key crop regions in Brazil, the world's largest exporter of coffee, sugar, soy and beef. In 2014 the drought wiped out a third of the country's coffee crop in some areas, which caused global [[Coffea arabica|coffee arabica]] prices to rise 50% over the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wfo-oma.org/news/the-effects-of-drought-in-brazil.html|title=The effects of drought in Brazil|last=Generale|first=O. M. A.|website=www.wfo-oma.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> In 2015 coffee trees had not recovered from the extreme heat and drought quick enough, triggering another arabica price rally. Crop production of soy, one of the country's largest export crops, decreased by 17% during the drought.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/brazil-water-supply-crops-still-at-risk-a-year-after-epic-drought/|title=Brazil Water Supply, Crops Still at Risk a Year after Epic Drought|website=Scientific American|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> <br />The Cemaden's Rain Monitoring System showed that severe droughts were observed \u00a0in the states of [[Mato Grosso]] and [[Mato Grosso do Sul]], they are both the largest regions for [[soybean]] production and fourth-largest beef producers in Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brazilian.report/money/2018/07/24/brazil-agribusiness-drought-season/|title=Brazil's agribusiness to suffer from worst drought season|date=2018-07-24|website=The Brazilian Report|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\n===== Impact on local temperature =====\nIn 2019 a group of scientists published a research who says that in \"Business as usual\" scenario the deforestation of the Amazon Rainforest will raise the temperature in Brazil by 0.11 degree in average, while in many places the rise will be up to 1.45 degree. The scientists claim that: \" Increased temperatures in already hot locations may increase [[Mortality rate|human mortality rates]] and [[electricity demand]]s, reduce [[agricultural yield]]s and [[water resources]], and contribute to [[Biodiversity|biodiversity collapse]], particularly in tropical regions . Furthermore, local warming may cause shifts in species distributions , including for species involved in [[Infectious Disease|infectious disease transmissions]] .\" The authors of the paper also say that deforestation is already causing a rise in the temperature.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=A. Prevedello |first1=Jayme |last2=R. Winck |first2=Gisele |last3=M. Weber |first3=Marcelo |last4=Nichols |first4=Elizabeth |last5=Sinervo |first5=Barry |title=Impacts of forestation and deforestation on local temperature across the globe |journal=PLOS One|volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=e0213368 |date=20 March 2019 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0213368 |pmid=30893352 |pmc=6426338 |bibcode=2019PLoSO..1413368P }}</ref>\n\n===== Impact on genetic diversity =====\nThe Amazon rainforest is a source of essential genes for crops, livestock, pollination, biological control, cleaning water and [[soil regeneration]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quevedo |first1=Lincoln |title=THE AMAZON FOREST IS DISAPPEARING |url=http://www.deborahhealey.com/s60/lincoln.html |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Possible solutions ====\n===== Organic farming =====\n\n[[File:P\u00e9 de berinjela.jpg|thumb|Organic cultivation of eggplant.]]\n\n[[Organic farming]] aims to produce food without the use of synthetic fertilizers, pesticides or other agrochemicals.<ref>Paull, John (2016) [https://www.academia.edu/26803383/Organics_Olympiad_2016_Global_Indices_of_Leadership_in_Organic_Agriculture Organics Olympiad 2016: Global Indices of Leadership in Organic Agriculture] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112005847/http://www.academia.edu/26803383/Organics_Olympiad_2016_Global_Indices_of_Leadership_in_Organic_Agriculture |date=12 November 2017 }}, Journal of Social and Development Sciences. 7(2):79-87</ref> The IBGE's 2006 Agricultural Census reported the existence of ninety thousand organic farms in Brazil, comprising 2% of the total; however, only 5,106 are certified.<ref name=orgbr>{{cite journal | authorlink = Fabricia Resende; Ticyana Banzato, orgs. | title = Org\u00e2nicos: Brasil j\u00e1 possui 90 mil estabelecimentos que declaram praticar agricultura org\u00e2nica, segundo IBGE | journal = Hortifruti Brasil | number = 85 | publisher = CEPEA ESALQ/USP | volume = 8 | location = Piracicaba | pages = 6\u201317 | date = November 2009 | language = Portuguese | url = http://www.cepea.esalq.usp.br/hfbrasil |url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140719215915/http://cepea.esalq.usp.br/hfbrasil/ | archivedate = 19 July 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOrganics are present mostly in small and medium properties. The majority of producers are organized in associations or cooperatives. The state with the largest number of producers is Bahia (223), followed by Minas Gerais (192), S\u00e3o Paulo (86), Rio Grande do Sul (83), Paran\u00e1 (79), Esp\u00edrito Santo (64) and others.<ref name=orgbr/>\n\nThe Brazil Organics program, constituted in 2005, promotes the sector.<ref name=orgbr/>\n\nBrazil is the twenty-largest exporter in the world, according to data from the Ministry of Development, Industry and Foreign Trade in a\u00e7ai, cacha\u00e7a, cattle, nuts, melons, guaran\u00e1, and beef.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===== Sustainable agriculture =====\nOne possible solution is sustainable farming in the Amazonas Rainforest<ref>{{cite web |last1=ZIENCHUK |first1=JUDI |title=Sustainable Farming In The Amazon Rainforest |url=https://epicureandculture.com/sustainable-farming-in-the-amazon-rainforest/ |website=Epicure & Culture |accessdate=3 May 2019|date=20 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Economy of Brazil}}\n\n{{Brazil topics}}\n\n{{South America topic|Agriculture in}}\n\n[[Category:Agriculture in Brazil| ]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Section headings in sentence case, not title case, perMOS:HEAD", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agriculture_in_Brazil"}
{"title_page": "History of French foreign relations", "text_new": "The '''History of French foreign relations''' Covers French diplomacy and foreign relations down to 1958.  For the more recent developments, see [[Foreign relations of France]]\n\n==Bourbon France 1453\u20131789==\n{{Main|History of France#Early Modern France (1453\u20131789)}}\n\n===Louis XIV and Louis XV===\nUnder the long reigns of kings [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]] (1643\u20131715)<ref>John B. Wolf, ''Louis XIV'' (1968)</ref> and [[Louis XV of France|Louis XV]] (1715\u20131774),<ref>Colin Jones, ''The Great Nation: France from Louis XV to Napoleon, 1715\u201399'' (2002).</ref> France was second in size to Russia but first in terms of economic and military power. It fought numerous expensive wars, usually to protect its voice in the selection of monarchs in neighboring countries.  A high priority was blocking the growth of power of the Habsburg rivals who controlled Austria and Spain.<ref>G. Zeller, \"French diplomacy and foreign policy in their European setting\". In F.L., Carsten, ed., ''The New Cambridge Modern History: Volume  V The Ascendancy of France, 1648\u201388'' (1961): pp 198\u2013221.</ref>\n\nWarfare defined the foreign policies of Louis XIV, and his personality shaped his approach.  Impelled \"by a mix of commerce, revenge, and pique\", Louis sensed that warfare was the ideal way to enhance his glory. In peacetime he concentrated on preparing for the next war. He taught his diplomats their job was to create tactical and strategic advantages for the French military.<ref>James Nathan, \"Force, Order, and Diplomacy in the Age of Louis XIV.\" Virginia Quarterly Review'' 69#4 (1993) 633+.</ref>\n\nLouis XIV had at his service many notable military commanders and an excellent support staff. His chief engineer [[S\u00e9bastien Le Prestre de Vauban|Vauban]] (1633\u20131707) perfected the arts of fortifying French towns and besieging enemy cities. The finance minister [[Jean-Baptiste Colbert]] (1619\u201383) dramatically improved the financial system so that it could support an army of 250,000 men. The system deteriorated under Louis XV so that wars drained the increasingly inefficient financial system.  Louis XIV made France prouder in psychology but poorer in wealth; military glory and cultural splendor were exalted above economic growth.<ref>Cathal J. Nolan, ''Wars of the Age of Louis XIV, 1650\u20131715: An Encyclopedia of Global Warfare and Civilization'' (2008) with over 1000 entries in 607pp.</ref>\n[[File:France 1552-1798.png|thumb|left|Territorial expansion of France under Louis XIV is depicted in orange.]]\n\nUnder Louis XIV, France fought three major wars: the [[Franco-Dutch War]], the [[Nine Years' War|War of the League of Augsburg]], and the [[War of the Spanish Succession]]. There were also two lesser conflicts: the [[War of Devolution]] and the [[War of the Reunions]].\n\nLouis XV did merge [[Lorraine (duchy)|Lorraine]] and [[Corsica]] into France.  However France was badly defeated in the [[Seven Years' War]] (1754\u20131763) and forced to give up its holdings in North America.  It ceded [[New France]] to Great Britain and Louisiana to Spain, and was left with a bitter grudge that sought revenge in 1778 by helping the Americans win independence.  Louis XV's decisions damaged the power of France, weakened the treasury, discredited the absolute monarchy, and made it more vulnerable to distrust and destruction, as happened in the [[French Revolution]], which broke out 15 years after his death.<ref>{{cite book|author=J. H. Shennan|title=France Before the Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aTqQ9vCTMHAC&pg=PA44|year=1995|publisher=Routledge|pages=44\u201345|isbn=9780415119450}}</ref> Norman Davies characterized Louis XV's reign as \"one of debilitating stagnation\", characterized by lost wars, endless clashes between the Court and Parliament, and religious feuds.<ref>{{cite book|author=Norman Davies|title=Europe: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jrVW9W9eiYMC&pg=PA627|year=1996|publisher=Oxford U.P.|pages=627\u201328|isbn=9780198201717}}</ref> A few scholars defend Louis, arguing that his highly negative reputation was based on propaganda meant to justify the French Revolution.  Jerome Blum described him as \"a perpetual adolescent called to do a man's job.\"<ref>Jerome Blum et al. ''The European World: A History'' (3rd ed 1970) p 454</ref>\n\n===American Revolutionary War===\nFrance played a key role helping the  American Patriots win [[American Revolutionary War|their War of Independence against Britain 1775\u20131783]]. Motivated by a long-term rivalry with Britain and by revenge for its territorial losses during Seven Years' War, France began secretly sending supplies in 1775.  In 1777, American captured the British invasion army at Saratoga, demonstrating the viability of their revolt. In 1778, France recognized the United States of America as a sovereign nation, signed a military alliance and went to war with Britain. France built a coalitions with Netherlands and Spain, provided Americans with money and arms, sent a combat army to serve under [[George Washington]], and sent a navy that prevented the second British army from escaping from Yorktown in 1781.<ref>Jonathan R. Dull, ''The French Navy and American Independence: A Study of Arms and Diplomacy 1774\u20131787'' (1975)</ref>\n\nBy 1789, the French debt acquired to fight in that war came to a staggering 1.3 billion livres. It \"set off France's own fiscal crisis, a political brawl over taxation that soon became one of the reasons for French Revolution.\"<ref>Christopher Hodson and Brett Rushforth, \"Bridging the Continental Divide: Colonial America's 'French Quarter.'\" ''OAH Magazine of History'' 25.1 (2011): 19\u201324.</ref>  France did obtain its revenge against Britain, but materially it gained little and its huge debts seriously weakened the government and helped facilitate the [[French Revolution]] in 1789.<ref>{{cite book|author=Peter McPhee|title=The French Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YLCnBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT34|year=2015|publisher=Melbourne U.|page=34|isbn=9780522866971}}</ref>\n\n[[Benjamin Franklin]] served as the American ambassador to France from 1776 to 1785. He met with many leading diplomats, aristocrats, intellectuals, scientists and financiers. Franklin's image and writings caught the French imagination \u2013 there were many images of him sold on the market \u2013 and he became the [[cultural icon]] of the archetypal new American, and even a hero for aspirations for a new order inside France.<ref>{{cite book|last=David Hackett Fischer|title=Liberty and Freedom: A Visual History of America's Founding Ideas|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195162530|url-access=registration|year=2005|publisher=Oxford UP|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195162530/page/185 185]\u201388|isbn=9780195162530}}</ref>\n\n== French Revolution and Napoleon: 1789\u20131815==\n\n===French Revolution===\n{{main|French Revolution}}\nAfter the stated aim of the National Convention to [[export revolution]], the guillotining of Louis XVI of France, and the French opening of the Scheldt, a European military coalition was formed against France. Spain, Naples, Great Britain, and the Netherlands joined Austria and Prussia in [[First Coalition|The First Coalition]] (1792\u201397), the first major concerted effort of multiple European powers to contain Revolutionary France. It took shape after the wars had already begun.<ref>Steven T. Ross, ''European Diplomatic History 1789\u20131815: France Against Europe'' (1969).</ref>\n\nThe Republican government in Paris was radicalised after a diplomatic coup from the Jacobins said it would be the [[Total war|''Guerre Totale'']] (\"total war\") and called for a ''[[Lev\u00e9e en masse]]'' (mass conscription of troops). Royalist invasion forces were defeated at [[Siege of Toulon|Toulon]] in 1793, leaving the French republican forces in an offensive position and granting nationwide fame to a young hero, [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon]] (1769\u20131821). Following their victory at [[Battle of Fleurus (1794)|Fleurus]], the French occupied Belgium and the Rhineland. An invasion of the Netherlands established the puppet [[Batavian Republic]]. Finally, a peace agreement was concluded between France, Spain, and Prussia in 1795 at [[Peace of Basel|Basel]].<ref>Geoffrey Bruun, ''Europe and the French Imperium, 1799\u20131814 '' (1938) [https://archive.org/download/in.ernet.dli.2015.183653/2015.183653.Europe-And-The-French-Imperium-1799-1814_text.pdf online].</ref>\n\n===Napoleonic wars===\n{{main|Napoleonic Wars}}\nBy 1799 Napoleon had seized power in France and proved highly adept at warfare and coalition building. Britain led a series of shifting coalitions to oppose him.  After a brief truce in 1802\u20133, war resumed. In 1806 Prussia joined Britain and Russia, thus forming the [[War of the Fourth Coalition|Fourth Coalition]]. Napoleon was not alone since he now had a complex network of allies and subject states.  The largely outnumbered French army crushed the Prussian army at [[Battle of Jena-Auerstedt|Jena-Auerstedt]] in 1806; Napoleon captured Berlin and went as far as Eastern Prussia. There the Russian Empire was defeated at the [[Battle of Friedland]] (14 June 1807). Peace was dictated in the [[Treaties of Tilsit]], in which Russia had to join the [[Continental System]], and Prussia handed half of its territories to France. The [[Duchy of Warsaw]] was formed over these territorial losses, and Polish troops entered the Grande Arm\u00e9e in significant numbers.<ref>Steven T. Ross, ''European Diplomatic History 1789\u20131815: France Against Europe'' (1969).</ref>\n\n[[File:Europe 1812 map en.png|thumb|250px|Europe on the eve of Napoleon's Russian campaign in 1812, on the height of the [[First French Empire|First Empire]]]]\n\nNapoleon then went back to the west, to deal with Britain. Only two countries remained neutral in the war: Sweden and Portugal, and Napoleon then looked toward the latter. In the [[Treaty of Fontainebleau (1807)|Treaty of Fontainebleau]], a Franco-Spanish alliance against Portugal was sealed as Spain eyed Portuguese territories. French armies entered Spain in order to attack Portugal, but then seized Spanish fortresses and took over the kingdom by surprise. [[Joseph Bonaparte]], Napoleon's brother, was made King of Spain after [[Charles IV of Spain|Charles IV]] abdicated. This occupation of the Iberian peninsula fueled local nationalism, and soon the Spanish and Portuguese fought the French using [[guerrilla tactics]], defeating the French forces at the [[Battle of Bail\u00e9n]] (June and July 1808). Britain sent a short-lived ground support force to Portugal, and French forces evacuated Portugal as defined in the [[Convention of Sintra]] following the Allied victory at [[Battle of Vimeiro|Vimeiro]] (21 August 1808). France only controlled [[Catalonia]] and [[Navarre]] and could have been definitely expelled from the Iberian peninsula had the Spanish armies attacked again, but the Spanish did not.<ref>Charles J. Esdaile, ''Fighting Napoleon: Guerrillas, Bandits & Adventurers in Spain, 1808\u20131814'' (2004).</ref>\n\nAnother French attack was launched on Spain, led by Napoleon himself, and was described as \"an avalanche of fire and steel.\" However, the French Empire was no longer regarded as invincible by European powers. In 1808 Austria formed the [[War of the Fifth Coalition|Fifth Coalition]] in order to break down the French Empire. The Austrian Empire defeated the French at [[Battle of Aspern-Essling|Aspern-Essling]], yet was beaten at [[Battle of Wagram|Wagram]] while the Polish allies defeated the Austrian Empire at [[Battle of Raszyn (1809)|Raszyn]] (April 1809). Although not as decisive as the previous Austrian defeats, the [[Treaty of Sch\u00f6nbrunn|peace treaty]] in October 1809 stripped Austria of a large amount of territories, reducing it even more.\n\n[[File:Napoleons retreat from moscow.jpg|thumb|250px|Napoleon Bonaparte retreating from Moscow, by [[Adolf Northern]].]]\n\nIn 1812 Napoleon could no longer tolerate Russian independence. He assembled a gigantic army and invaded. The [[French invasion of Russia (1812)]] Was a total disaster, caused primarily by weather, partisan attacks, disease and inadequate logistics.  Only small remnants of the invading army returned from Russia. On the Spanish front the French armies were defeated and evacuated Spain.<ref>Michael Adams, ''Napoleon and Russia'' (2006)</ref>\n\nSince France had been defeated on these two fronts, states it previously conquered and controlled struck back. The [[War of the Sixth Coalition|Sixth Coalition]] was formed, and the German states of the Confederation of the Rhine switched sides, finally opposing Napoleon. Napoleon was defeated in the [[Battle of Leipzig|Battle of the Nations]] outside Leipzig in October 1813. The Allies invaded France and Napoleon abdicated on 6 April 1814. The [[Conservative Order|conservative]] [[Congress of Vienna]] reversed the political changes that had occurred during the wars. Napoleon's attempted restoration, a period known as the [[Hundred Days]], ended with his final defeat at the [[Battle of Waterloo]] in 1815.  The monarchy was restored with [[Louis XVIII of France|Louis XVIII]] as king, followed by his brother.  France was soon integrated into the reactionary international situation.  However much of the Napoleonic liberalization of Western Europe, including Italy, and Germany, and adjacent areas became permanent.<ref>Alexander Grab, ''Napoleon and the Transformation of Europe'' (2003)</ref><ref>Kevin H. O'Rourke, \"The Worldwide Economic Impact of the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars, 1793\u20131815\", ''Journal of Global History'' (2006), 1#1 pp 123\u2013149.</ref><ref>Robert R. Palmer, ''The Age of the Democratic Revolution: A Political History of Europe and America, 1760\u20131800''. (2 vol 1959)</ref>\n\n==France 1814\u20131850==\n{{main|International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)}}\nFrance was no longer the dominant power it had been before 1814, but it played a major role in European economics, culture, diplomacy and military affairs. The Bourbons were restored, but left a weak record and one branch was overthrown in 1830 and the other branch in 1848 as Napoleon's nephew was elected president. He made himself emperor as [[Napoleon III]] and lasted until he was defeated and captured by Prussians in 1870 a war that humiliated France and made the new nation of Germany dominant in the continent. France built up an empire, especially in Africa and Indochina. The economy was strong, with a good railway system.  The arrival of the [[Rothschild banking family of France]] in 1812 guaranteed the role of Paris alongside London as a major center of international finance.<ref>Gordon Wright, ''France in Modern Times: From the Enlightenment to the Present'' (1995) pp 182\u201395.</ref>\n\n==Overseas empire in the nineteenth century==\nStarting with its scattered small holdings in India, West Indies and Latin America, France began rebuilding its world empire.<ref>Frederick Quinn, ''The French Overseas Empire'' (2001)</ref><ref>Robert Aldrich, ''Greater France: A History of French Overseas Expansion'' (1996)</ref>  It took control of Algeria in 1830 and began in earnest to rebuild its worldwide empire after 1850, concentrating chiefly in North and West Africa, as well as South-East Asia, with other conquests in Central and East Africa, as well as the South Pacific. Republicans, at first hostile to empire, only became supportive when Germany started to build her own colonial empire In the 1880s. As it developed the new empire took on roles of trade with France, especially supplying raw materials and purchasing manufactured items, as well as lending prestige to the motherland and spreading French civilization and language, and the Catholic religion. It also provided manpower in the World Wars.<ref>{{cite book|author=Tony Chafer|title=The End of Empire in French West Africa: France's Successful Decolonization?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9GseKljgaW0C&pg=PA84|year=2002|publisher=Berg|pages=84\u201385|isbn=9781859735572}}</ref>\n\nIt became a moral mission to lift the world up to French standards by bringing Christianity and French culture. In 1884 the leading exponent of colonialism, [[Jules Ferry]] declared; \"The higher races have a right over the lower races, they have a [[Civilizing mission|duty to civilize the inferior races]].\" Full citizenship rights \u2013 ''assimilation'' \u2013 was a long-term goal, but in practice colonial officials were reluctant to extend full citizenship rights.<ref>{{cite book|author=Assa Okoth|title=A History of Africa: African societies and the establishment of colonial rule, 1800-1915|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6knAMseFPpIC&pg=PA318|year=2006|publisher=East African Publishers|isbn=978-9966-25-357-6|pages=318\u201319}}</ref> France sent small numbers of white permanent settlers to its empire, in sharp contrast to Britain, Spain and Portugal. The notable exception was Algeria, where the French settlers held power but remained a minority.<ref>{{cite book|author=Sung-Eun Choi|title=Decolonization and the French of Algeria: Bringing the Settler Colony Home|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=727-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA53|year=2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|page=53|isbn=9781137520753}}</ref>\n\n==Second Empire: 1851\u20131871==\n{{main|International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)|Napoleon III|Franco-Prussian War}}\nDespite his promises in 1852 of a peaceful reign, [[Napoleon III]]  could not resist the temptations of glory in foreign affairs such as his uncle, the world-famous Napoleon, had achieved.  He was visionary, mysterious and secretive; he had a poor staff, and kept running afoul of his domestic supporters. In the end he was incompetent as a diplomat.<ref>Theodore Zeldin, ''France, 1848\u20131945: Ambition, love and politics'' (1973) pp 558\u201360</ref>  Napoleon did have some successes: he strengthened French control over Algeria, established bases in Africa, began the takeover of Indochina, and opened trade with China. He facilitated a French company building the Suez Canal, which Britain could not stop. In Europe, however, Napoleon failed again and again.<ref>John B. Wolf, ''France: 1814\u20131919'' (2nd ed. 1963) 302\u2013348</ref>\n\nThe [[Crimean War]] of 1854\u20131856 against Russia, in alliance with Britain and the Ottoman Empire, produced heavy losses and high expenses but no territorial or political gains.  War with Austria in 1859 facilitated the unification of Italy, and Napoleon was rewarded with the annexation of Savoy and Nice. The British grew annoyed at his intervention in Syria in 1860\u201361. He angered Catholics alarmed at his poor treatment of the Pope, then reversed himself and angered the anticlerical liberals at home and his erstwhile Italian allies. He lowered the tariffs, which helped in the long run but in the short run angered owners of large estates and the textile and iron industrialists, while leading worried workers to organize. Matters grew worse in the 1860s as Napoleon nearly blundered into war with the United States in 1862.<ref>A. J. P. Taylor, ''Struggle for Mastery'', pp 171\u2013227</ref> [[Second French intervention in Mexico|His plan to take control of Mexico]] in 1861\u20131867 was a total disaster. The United States forced him to evacuate his army from Mexico, and his puppet Emperor was executed.<ref>Nancy Nichols Barker, \"France, Austria, and the Mexican Venture, 1861\u20131864.\" ''French Historical Studies'' (1963) 3#2 pp: 22\u2013245. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/286031 in JSTOR].</ref><ref>Patrick J. Kelly, \"The North American Crisis of the 1860s\", ''The Journal of the Civil War Era'' (2012) 2#3 pp. 337\u2013368; 10.1353/cwe.2012.0074 [http://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/journal_of_the_civil_war_era/v002/2.3.kelly.html Excerpt]</ref>\n\nFinally Napoleon was outmaneuvered by [[Otto von Bismarck]] and went to war with the Germans in 1870 when it was too late to stop German unification.<ref>[[David Wetzel]], ''A duel of giants: Bismarck, Napoleon III, and the origins of the Franco-Prussian war'' (2003).</ref> Napoleon had alienated everyone; after failing to obtain an alliance with Austria and Italy, France had no allies and was bitterly divided at home. It was disastrously defeated on the battlefield, losing Alsace and Lorraine. A. J. P. Taylor is blunt: \"he ruined France as a great power.\"<ref>A. J. P. Taylor, ''Europe: Grandeur and Decline'' (1967) p 64</ref>\n\n===American Civil War===\n{{main|France and the American Civil War}}\nThe [[Second French Empire]] under [[Napoleon III]] remained officially neutral throughout the War and never recognized the Confederate States of America. However, the textile industry needed cotton, and Napoleon III had imperial ambitions in Mexico which could be greatly aided by the Confederacy. The United States had warned that recognition meant war.  France was reluctant to act alone without British collaboration, and the British rejected intervention. Emperor Napoleon III realized that a war with the U.S. without allies \"would spell disaster\" for France.<ref>{{cite book|author=Howard Jones|title=Abraham Lincoln and a New Birth of Freedom: The Union and Slavery in the Diplomacy of the Civil War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gVvZb5oeVtwC&pg=PA183|year=1999|publisher=U of Nebraska Press|page=183|isbn=978-0803225824}}</ref> Napoleon III and his Minister of Foreign Affairs Edouard Thouvenel adopted a cautious attitude and maintained diplomatically correct relations with Washington.  Half the French press favored the Union, while the \"imperial\" press was more sympathetic to the Confederacy. Public opinion generally ignored the war, showing much interest in Mexico.<ref>Lynn M. Case, and Warren E. Spencer, ''The United States and France: Civil War Diplomacy'' (1970)</ref>\n\nNapoleon hoped that that a Confederate victory would result in two weak nations on Mexico's northern borders, allowing French dominance in a country ruled by its puppet Emperor Maximilian.  [[Mat\u00edas Romero]], J\u00faarez's ambassador to the United States, gained some support in Congress for possibly intervening on Mexico's behalf against France's occupation.* Robert Ryal Miller, \"Matias Romero: Mexican Minister to the United States during the Juarez-Maximilian Era\", ''Hispanic American Historical Review'' (1965) 45#2 pp.&nbsp;228\u2013245 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2510566 in JSTOR]<ref>Thomas D. Schoonover, ed., ''Mexican Lobby: Mat\u00edas Romero in Washington 1861--1867'' (UP of Kentucky, 2015).</ref>  However, Secretary of State [[William Seward]] was cautious in limiting US aid to Mexico. He did not want a war with France before the Confederacy was defeated.<ref>Gary Moreno, \"Rage Against the Monarchy American Reaction to the French Intervention in Mexico.\" ''Journal of the West'' 47#3 (2008): 48\u201355.</ref>\n\n=== Mexico===\n{{Further|France\u2013Mexico relations}}\nIn 1861, Mexican conservatives looked to French leader [[Napoleon III]] to abolish the Republic led by liberal President [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]]. France favored the Confederacy but did not accord it diplomatic recognition. The French expected that a Confederate victory would facilitate French economic dominance in Mexico. he helped The Confederacy by shipping urgently needed supplies through the ports of Matamoros, Mexico, and Brownsville (Texas). The Confederacy itself sought closer relationships with Mexico. Juarez turned them down, but the Confederates worked well with local warlords in northern Mexico, and with the French invaders.<ref>J. Fred Rippy, \"Mexican Projects of the Confederates\", ''Southwestern Historical Quarterly'' 22#4 (1919), pp. 291\u2013317 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/30241764 in JSTOR]</ref><ref>Kathryn Abbey Hanna, \"The Roles of the South in the French Intervention in Mexico\", ''Journal of Southern History'' 20#1 (1954), pp. 3\u201321 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2954576 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\nRealizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed an Austrian prince [[Maximilian I of Mexico]] as its puppet ruler in 1864. Owing to the shared convictions of the democratically elected government of Ju\u00e1rez and Lincoln, [[Mat\u00edas Romero]], Ju\u00e1rez's minister to Washington, mobilized support in the U.S. Congress, and raised money, soldiers and ammunition in the United States for the war against Maximilian.<ref>Robert Ryal Miller, \"Matias Romero: Mexican Minister to the United States during the Juarez-Maximilian Era\", ''Hispanic American Historical Review'' (1965) 45#2 pp. 228\u2013245 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2510566 in JSTOR]</ref> Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the [[Monroe Doctrine]].<ref>Frederic Bancroft,  \"The French in Mexico and the Monroe doctrine.\" ''Political science quarterly'' 11.1 (1896): 30\u201343. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2139600 in JSTOR]</ref><ref>Michele Cunningham,  ''Mexico and the foreign policy of Napoleon III'' (Springer, 2016)</ref><ref>Jack Autrey Dabbs, ''The French army in Mexico, 1861\u20131867: a study in military government'' (Hague, Mouton, 1963).</ref>\n\nOnce the Union won the War in spring 1865, it  allowed supporters of Ju\u00e1rez to openly purchase weapons and ammunition and issued stronger warnings to Paris.  Washington sent General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] with 50,000 combat veterans to the Mexican border to emphasize that time had run out on the French intervention. Napoleon III had no choice but to withdrew his outnumbered army in disgrace. Emperor Maximilian refused exile and was executed by the Mexican government in 1867.<ref>Jasper Ridley, ''Maximilian and Ju\u00e1rez'' (2001).</ref>\n\nHistorians typically interpret the fiasco as a disaster for France. They portray an imperialistic attempt to secure access to raw materials and markets, and to establish a Latin, Catholic client state to prevent further American into Latin America. The failure stemmed from lack of realism in its conception, a gross misunderestimate of the power of the United States,  a misunderstanding of Mexican public opinion, and recurring ineptitude in execution. While Maximilian and his widow get popular sympathy, Napoleon earns the sharp negative criticism of historians.<ref>Roger Price in  ''French History'' (Sep 2002) 16#3 pp 376-377.</ref>\n\n==Third Republic: 1871\u20131914==\n{{main|International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)|French Third Republic|French colonial empire}}\n[[File:Europe 1871 map en.png|thumb|250px|Europe after the Franco-Prussian War of 1871, the forming of the German Reich and the French loss of Alsace-Lorraine]]\nFrench foreign policy was based on a hatred of Germany\u2014whose larger size and faster-growing economy could not be matched\u2014combined with a popular revanchism that demanded the return of Alsace and Lorraine. There were some moderate leaders who wanted to forget the past, but Berlin ignored their overtures.<ref>E. Malcolm Carroll, ''French public opinion and foreign affairs, 1870\u20131914'' (1964) pp 47, 109.</ref><ref>J. F. V. Keiger. France and the World Since 1870. (2001) pp  114\u2013116.</ref>\n\nForeign affairs attracted far less attention than domestic affairs. Religious and class differences deeply divided the French people on polarities such as monarchy versus Republicanism, secularism versus Catholicism, farmers versus urbanites, workers versus owners. Permanent professional diplomats and bureaucrats had developed their own  traditions of how to operate  at the [[Quai d'Orsay]] (where the Foreign Ministry was located), and their style  changed little from generation to generation.  Most of the diplomats came from high status or aristocratic families.  Although France was one of the few republics in Europe, its diplomats mingled smoothly with the aristocratic representatives at the royal courts.  Prime ministers and leading politicians generally paid little attention to foreign affairs, allowing a handful of senior men to control policy.  In the decades before the First World War they dominated the embassies in the 10 major countries were France had an ambassador (elsewhere, they set lower-ranking ministers).  They included [[Th\u00e9ophile Delcass\u00e9]], the foreign minister from 1898 to 1906; [[Paul Cambon]],  the ambassador in London, 1890\u20131920; [[Jean Jules Jusserand]] in Washington from 1902 to 1924; and Camille Barrere, in Rome from 1897 to 1924.  In terms of foreign policy, there was general agreement about the need for high protective tariffs, which kept agricultural prices high.  After the defeat by the Germans, there was a strong widespread anti-German sentiment focused on revanchism and regaining Alsace and Lorraine.  The Empire was a matter of great pride, and service as administrators, soldiers and missionaries was a high status, occupation.<ref>Felix Gilbert, David Clay Large, ''The End of the European Era: 1890 to the Present'' (2002) p 64\u201365.</ref><ref>J. F. V. Keiger, ''France and the World since 1870'' (2001) pp 25 \u2013 47.</ref>\n\nBesides a demand for revenge against Germany, imperialism was a factor.<ref>Agnes Murphy, ''The ideology of French imperialism, 1871\u20131881'' (1968).</ref> In the midst of the [[Scramble for Africa]], French and British interest in Africa came into conflict. The most dangerous episode was the [[Fashoda Incident]] of 1898 when French troops tried to claim an area in the Southern Sudan, and a British force purporting to be acting in the interests of the [[Khedive of Egypt]] arrived. Under heavy pressure the French withdrew securing Anglo-Egyptian control over the area. The status quo was recognised by an agreement between the two states acknowledging British control over Egypt, while France became the dominant power in Morocco, but France suffered a humiliating defeat overall.<ref>D.W. Brogan, ''France under the Republic: The Development of Modern France (1870\u20131930)'' (1940) pp 321\u201326</ref>\n\n===Colonial empire in Africa and Asia===\n{{main|Scramble for Africa}}\nThe [[Suez Canal]], initially built by the French, became a joint British-French project in 1875, as both saw it as vital to maintaining their influence and empires in Asia.  In 1882, ongoing civil disturbances in Egypt prompted Britain to intervene, extending a hand to France. The government allowed Britain to take effective control of Egypt.<ref>A.J.P. Taylor, ''The Struggle for Mastery in Europe, 1848\u20131918'' (1954) pp 286\u201392</ref>\n\nUnder the leadership of expansionist [[Jules Ferry]], the Third Republic greatly expanded the [[French colonial empire]]. Catholic missionaries played a major role.  France acquired [[French Indochina|Indochina]], [[Madagascar#French colonization|Madagascar]], vast territories in [[French West Africa|West Africa]] and [[French Equatorial Africa|Central Africa]], and much of [[French Polynesia|Polynesia]].<ref>Robert Aldrich, ''Greater France: A History of French Overseas Expansion'' (1996)</ref>\n\nIn the early 1880s, [[Pierre Savorgnan de Brazza]] was exploring the [[Kongo Kingdom]] for France, at the same time [[Henry Morton Stanley]] explored it in on behalf of [[Leopold II of Belgium]], who would have it as his personal [[Congo Free State]] (see section below).  France occupied [[Tunisia]] in May 1881.  In 1884, France occupied Guinea.  [[French West Africa]] (AOF) was founded in 1895, and [[French Equatorial Africa]] in 1910.<ref>Thomas Pakenham, ''The Scramble for Africa: White Man's Conquest of the Dark Continent from 1876 to 1912'' (1991).</ref><ref>Robert Aldrich, ''Greater France: A history of French overseas expansion'' (1996).</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Scramble for Africa]] in the 1870s and 1880s, the British and French generally recognised each other's spheres of influence. The [[Suez Canal]], initially built by the French, became a joint British-French project in 1875, as both saw it as vital to maintaining their influence and empires in Asia.<ref>Turner p.26-7</ref> In 1882, ongoing civil disturbances in Egypt (''see [[Urabi Revolt]]'') prompted Britain to intervene, extending a hand to France. France's expansionist Prime Minister [[Jules Ferry]] was out of office, and the government was unwilling to send more than an intimidatory fleet to the region. Britain established a protectorate, as France had a year earlier in [[Tunisia]], and popular opinion in France later put this action down to duplicity.<ref>{{cite book|title=France: The Third Republic 1870\u20131914|author=Keith Randell|series=Access to History|year=1991|isbn=978-0-340-55569-9}}</ref> It was about this time that the two nations established co-ownership of [[Vanuatu]]. The [[Anglo-French Convention of 1882]] was also signed to resolve territory disagreements in western Africa.\n\n====Fashoda crisis====\nIn the 1875\u20131898 era, serious tensions with Britain erupted over African issues. At several points war was possible, but it never happened.<ref>T. G. Otte, \"From 'War-in-Sight' to Nearly War: Anglo\u2013French Relations in the Age of High Imperialism, 1875\u20131898\", ''Diplomacy and Statecraft'' (2006) 17#4 pp 693\u2013714.</ref>  One brief but dangerous dispute occurred during the [[Fashoda Incident]] when French troops tried to claim an area in the Southern Sudan, and a British force purporting to be acting in the interests of the [[Khedive of Egypt]] arrived.<ref>Roger Glenn Brown, ''Fashoda reconsidered: the impact of domestic politics on French policy in Africa, 1893\u20131898'' (1970)</ref>  Under heavy pressure the French withdrew securing Anglo-Egyptian control over the area. The status quo was recognised by an agreement between the two states acknowledging British control over Egypt, while France became the dominant power in [[Morocco]]. France had failed in its main goals.  P.M.H. Bell says, \"Between the two governments there was a brief battle of wills, with the British insisting on immediate and unconditional French withdrawal from Fashoda. The French had to accept these terms, amounting to a public humiliation....Fashoda was long remembered in France as an example of British brutality and injustice.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=P. M. H. Bell|title=France and Britain, 1900-1940: Entente and Estrangement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mr-OAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA3|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|page=3|isbn=9781317892731}}</ref><ref>A. J. P. Taylor, ''The Struggle for Mastery in Europe, 1848\u20131918'' (1954) pp 381\u201388</ref><ref>D. W. Brogan, ''France under the Republic: The Development of Modern France (1870\u20131930)'' (1940) pp 321\u201326</ref><ref>William L. Langer, ''The diplomacy of imperialism: 1890\u20131902 (1951) pp 537\u201380</ref>\n\n====Asia====\nFrance had colonies in Asia and looked for alliances and found in Japan a possible ally. At Japan's request Paris sent military missions in [[French military mission to Japan (1872\u201380)|1872\u20131880]], in [[French military mission to Japan (1884\u201389)|1884\u20131889]] and in [[French military mission to Japan (1918\u201319)|1918\u20131919]] to help modernize the Japanese army.  Conflicts with China over Indochina climaxed during the [[Sino-French War]] (1884\u20131885). [[Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Courbet|Admiral Courbet]] destroyed the Chinese fleet anchored at [[Battle of Foochow|Foochow]]. The treaty ending the war, put France in a protectorate over northern and central Vietnam, which it divided into [[Tonkin]] and [[Annam (French colony)|Annam]].<ref name=wak>Frederic Wakeman, Jr., ''The Fall of Imperial China'' (1975) pp. 189\u2013191.</ref>\n\n=== Franco-Russian Alliance===\n{{Main|Franco-Russian Alliance}}\nFrance was deeply split between the monarchists on one side, and the Republicans on the other. The Republicans at first seemed highly unlikely to welcome any military alliance with Russia. That large nation was poor and not industrialized; it was intensely religious and authoritarian, with no sense of democracy or freedom for its peoples.  It oppressed Poland, and exiled, and even executed political liberals and radicals. At a time when French Republicans were rallying in the [[Dreyfus affair]] against anti-Semitism, Russia was the most notorious center in the world of anti-Semitic outrages, including multiple murderous large-scale pogroms against the Jews. On the other hand, France was increasingly frustrated by Bismarck's success in isolating it diplomatically. France had issues with Italy, which was allied with Germany and Austria-Hungary in the Triple Alliance. Paris made a few overtures to Berlin, but they were rebuffed, and after 1900 there was a threat of war between France and Germany over Germany's attempt to deny French expansion into Morocco. Great Britain was still in its \"splendid isolation\" mode and after a major agreement in 1890 with Germany, it seemed especially favorable toward Berlin. Colonial conflicts in Africa brought Britain and France to a major crisis The Fashoda crisis of 1898 brought Britain and France almost to the brink of war and ended with a humiliation of France that left it hostile to Britain. By 1892 Russia was the only opportunity for France to break out of its diplomatic isolation. Russia had been allied with Germany the new Kaiser Wilhelm removed Bismarck in 1890 and in 1892 ended the \"Reinsurance treaty\" with Russia. Russia was now alone diplomatically and like France, it needed a military alliance to contain the threat of Germany's strong army and military aggressiveness. The pope, angered by German anti-Catholicism, worked diplomatically to bring Paris and St. Petersburg together. Russia desperately needed money for our infrastructure of railways and ports facilities. The German government refused to allow its banks to lend money to Russia, but French banks eagerly did so. For example, it funded the essential trans-Siberian railway. Negotiations were increasingly successful, and by 1895. France and Russia had signed the [[Franco-Russian Alliance]], a strong military alliance to join together in war if Germany attacked either of them.  France had finally escaped its diplomatic isolation.<ref>John B.  Wolf, ''France 1814\u20131919: The rise of a Liberal-Democratic Society'' (1963)</ref><ref>William L. Langer, ''The diplomacy of Imperialism: 1890\u20131902'' (1960), pp 3\u201366.</ref>\n\n==1900\u20131914==\n{{Main|French entry into World War I|German entry into World War I}}\n\n[[File:WWIchartX.svg|350px|thumb|Diplomatic alignments in 1900-1914; Italy was neutral, then joined the Allies in 1915.]]\nAfter  [[Otto von Bismarck]]'s removal in 1890, French efforts to isolate Germany became successful; with the formation of the [[Triple Entente]], Germany began to feel encircled.<ref>Samuel R. Williamson Jr., \"German Perceptions of the Triple Entente after 1911: Their Mounting Apprehensions Reconsidered\" ''Foreign Policy Analysis'' 7.2 (2011): 205\u2013214.</ref>  Foreign minister Delcass\u00e9, especially, went to great pains to woo Russia and Great Britain. Key markers were the [[Franco-Russian Alliance]] of 1894, the 1904 [[Entente Cordiale]] with Great Britain, and finally the [[Anglo-Russian Entente]] in 1907 which became the [[Triple Entente]]. This formal alliance with Russia, and informal alignment with Britain, against Germany and Austria eventually led Russia and Britain to enter World War I as France's Allies.<ref>Taylor, ''The Struggle for Mastery in Europe, 1848\u20131918'' (1954) pp 345, 403\u201326</ref><ref>G. P. Gooch, ''Before the war: studies in diplomacy'' (1936), chapter on Delcass\u00e9 pp 87\u2013186.</ref>\n\nBy 1914 French foreign policy was thus based on an alliance with Russia, and an informal understanding with Britain, all based on the assumption that the main threat was from Germany.<ref>Cody Nester, \"France and the Great War: Belligerent Warmonger or Failed Peacekeeper? A Literature Review.\" ''History'' 12 (2015): 2.</ref><ref>John Keiger, ''France and the Origins of the First World War'' (1985) [http://www.vlib.us/wwi/resources/archives/texts/t040831c.html summary]</ref> The crisis of 1914 was unexpected, and when Germany mobilized its forces in response to Russian mobilization, France also had to mobilize or be overwhelmed bu sheer numbers.  Germany then invaded Belgium and France, and World War I had begun.<ref>Margaret MacMillan, ''The War that Ended Peace: The Road to 1914'' (2013).</ref><ref>Christopher Clark, ''The sleepwalkers: how Europe went to war in 1914'' (2012).</ref>\n\n==First World War==\n{{Further|Diplomatic history of World War I}}\nGermany declared war on France on 3 August 1914 and invaded Belgium and northeastern France following its [[Schlieffen Plan]].  The plan seemed to promise quick victory but it failed because of inadequate forces, unexpected Belgian resistance, and poor coordination among German generals. France had already launched its invasion of Germany with [[Plan XVII]], but very quickly realized it needed to defend Paris at all costs. It did so at the [[First Battle of the Marne]] {{nowrap|(5\u201312 September),}}; the German armies were defeated and forced back.  The war became stalemated on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]], with practically no movement until spring 1918. Both sides suffered very high casualties caused by repeated infantry attacks against defensive positions protected by trenches, barbed wire, machine guns, and heavy artillery using aircraft as spotters, and poison gas.  Meanwhile, the rich industrial and mining regions of Belgium and northeastern France remained in German hands throughout the war.  Marshals [[Joseph Joffre]] (1852\u20131931) and [[Douglas Haig]] (1861\u20131928) believed that attrition would win the war by wearing down the German reserves in multiple massive assaults. German general [[Erich von Falkenhayn]] (1861\u20131922) was outnumbered and focused on defense. Both sides failed to realize the stultifying effect of trench warfare on morale and the loss of hundreds of thousands of lives in futile attempts to win a \"decisive battle.\"<ref>Robert T. Foley, \"What's in a Name?: The Development of Strategies of Attrition on the Western Front, 1914\u20131918.\" ''Historian'' 68.4 (2006): 722\u2013746. [https://www.academia.edu/download/38289107/Foley_FWW_Attrition_Compared.pdf online]</ref>\n\nAfter Socialist leader [[Jean Jaur\u00e8s]]. a pacifist, was assassinated at the start of the war, the French socialist movement abandoned its antimilitarist positions and joined the national war effort. The labor unions supported the war. Prime Minister [[Rene Viviani]]  called for unity\u2014for a \"[[Union sacr\u00e9e]]\" (\"Sacred Union\")--Which was a wartime truce between the right and left factions that had been fighting bitterly. France had few dissenters. However, [[war-weariness]] was a major factor by 1917, even reaching the army.<ref>Philippe Bernard and Henri Dubief, ''The Decline of the Third Republic, 1914\u20131938''  (1988) pp 3\u201377.</ref>\n\nThe French Right supported the war, emphasizing the deep spiritual value of \"the Union Sacr\u00e9e.\"  The middle-of-the-road Radicals split\u2014one wing wanted a compromise peace. By winter 1916\u201317 strong annexationist demands emerged on the right, calling for annexation of Germany's Saar basin to France and the creation of independent German states on the left bank of the Rhine.<ref>David Stevenson, \"French War Aims and the American Challenge, 1914\u20131918\" ''Historical Journal'' 22#4 (1979)  pp. 877\u2013894 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2638691 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\nIn 1914 London and Paris agreed that financially Britain would support the weaker Allies and that France would take care of itself. there was no common financial policy. French credit collapsed in 1916 and Britain took full control of the failing Allied finances and began loaning large sums to Paris. The J. P. Morgan bank in New York assumed control of French loans in the fall of 1916 and relinquished it to the US government when the U,S, entered the war in 1917.<ref>Martin Horn, \"External Finance in Anglo-French Relations in the First World War, 1914\u20131917.\" ''The International History Review'' 17.1 (1995): 51\u201377.</ref>\n\nIn 1917 the Russian Revolution ended the Franco-Russian alliance, and French policy changed. It joined Britain sending forces against the Bolsheviks and in support of the \"white\" counter-revolutionaries. Paris gave active support to the Southern Slav unionist movement and to the Czech and Polish claims for independence. Serbia, was a loyal ally of France throughout World War I. Serbia was highly appreciative of French financial and material aid before its collapse in 1915 as well as funding the Serbian government in exile. There was popular support in France for Serbia as seen in taking in refugees and educating students. France took part in the armed liberation of Serbia, Montenegro, and Vojvodina in 1918.<ref>David Stevenson, ''French War Aims Against Germany, 1914\u20131919'' (1982).</ref>\n\n===Paris Peace conference 1919===\n{{Further|Paris Peace Conference, 1919| Georges Clemenceau|Treaty of Versailles}}\nFrance suffered very heavy losses in the war, in terms of battle casualties and economic distress, but came out on the winning side. It demanded Germany make good all its financial losses (including pensions for the veterans.)  At the Paris peace conference of 1919, vengeance against defeated Germany was the main French theme, and Prime Minister Clemenceau was largely effective against the moderating influences of the British and Americans.   The [[Treaty of Versailles]] was forced upon Germany which deeply resented the harsh terms.<ref>George Noble, ''Policies and opinions at Paris, 1919: Wilsonian diplomacy, the Versailles Peace, and French public opinion'' (1968).</ref><ref>Margaret McMillan, ''Paris 1919: six months that changed the world'' (2007).</ref>  France strongly supported the new Kingdom of the Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes.  It became [[Yugoslavia]] and in the 1920s and 1930s helped France by opposing German ambitions in the Balkans.<ref>Anthony Adamthwaite, ''Grandeur and Misery: France's bid for power in Europe 1914\u20131940'' (1995) pp  89\u2013109.</ref>\n\n==Interwar years==\n{{further|International relations (1919\u20131939)|Causes of World War II}}\n\nFrench foreign and security policy after 1919 used traditional alliance strategies to weaken German's potential to threaten France and comply with the strict obligations devised by France in the Treaty of Versailles. The main diplomatic strategy came in response to the demands of the French army to form alliances against the German threat.  Germany resisted then finally complied, aided by American money, and France took a more conciliatory policy by 1924 in response to pressure from Britain and the United States, as well as to French realization that its potential allies in Eastern Europe were weak and hard to coordinate.<ref>Peter Jackson, \"France and the problems of security and international disarmament after the first world war.\" ''Journal of Strategic Studies'' 29#2 (2006): 247\u2013280.</ref><ref>Nicole Jordan, \"The Reorientation of French Diplomacy in the mid-1920s: the Role of Jacques Seydoux.\" ''English Historical Review'' 117.473 (2002): 867\u2013888.</ref>  It proved impossible to establish military alliances with the United States or Britain. A tentative Russian agreement in 1935 was politically suspect and was not implemented.<ref>{{cite book|author=Richard Overy|title=The road to war|url=https://archive.org/details/roadtowar00over|url-access=registration|year=1999|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-028530-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/roadtowar00over/page/140 140]\u201341}}</ref> The alliances with Poland and Czechoslovakia; these proved to be weak ties that collapsed in the face of German threats in 1938 in 1939.<ref>Piotr Stefan Wandycz, ''The Twilight of French Eastern Alliances, 1926\u20131936: French-Czechoslovak-Polish Relations from Locarno to the Remilitarization of the Rhineland'' (1988) ch 1 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctt7ztrh0.5 online]</ref>\n\n===1920s===\nFrance was part of the Allied force that [[Occupation of the Rhineland|occupied the Rhineland]] following the Armistice. Foch supported Poland in the [[Greater Poland Uprising (1918\u201319)|Greater Poland Uprising]] and in the [[Polish\u2013Soviet War]] and France also joined Spain during the [[Rif War (1920)|Rif War]].  From 1925 until his death in 1932, [[Aristide Briand]], as prime minister during five short intervals, directed French foreign policy, using his diplomatic skills and sense of timing to forge friendly relations with [[Weimar Germany]] as the basis of a genuine peace within the framework of the [[League of Nations]]. He realized France could neither contain the much larger Germany by itself nor secure effective support from Britain or the League.<ref>Eugen Weber, ''The Hollow Years: France in the 1930s'' (1996) p. 125</ref>\n\nIn January 1923 as a response to the failure of Germany to ship enough coal as part of its reparations, France (and  Belgium) occupied the industrial region of the [[Ruhr]]. Germany responded with passive resistance, including Printing vast amounts of marks To pay for the occupation, thereby causing runaway inflation. Inflation heavily damaged the German middle class (Whose bank accounts became worthless) but it also damaged the French franc. France fomented a separatist movement pointing to an independent buffer state, but it collapsed after some bloodshed.  The intervention was a failure, and in summer 1924 France accepted the American solution to the reparations issues, as expressed in the [[Dawes Plan]]. According to the Dawes Plan, American banks made long-term loans to Germany which used the dollars to pay reparations.<ref>Conan Fischer, ''The Ruhr Crisis 1923\u20131924'' (2003).</ref>  The United States demanded repayment of the war loans, although the terms were slightly softened in 1926.  All the loans, payments and reparations were suspended in 1931, and all were finally resolved in 1951.<ref>Adamthwaite, ''Grandeur and Misery'' pp 29\u201330, 48.</ref><ref>Philip A.  Grant Jr. and Martin Schmidt, \"France and the American War Debt Controversy, 1919\u20131929\" ''Proceedings of the Western Society for French History'' (1981), Vol. 9, pp 372\u2013382.</ref>\n\nThe [[Locarno Treaties]] of 1925 helped bring Germany back into the French good graces.  It guaranteed the border between France and Germany, but ignored Germany's controversial eastern border.  In Poland, the public humiliation received by Polish diplomats was one of the contributing factors to the fall of the Grabski cabinet. Locarno contributed to the worsening of the atmosphere between Poland and France, weakening the [[French-Polish alliance]]. [[J\u00f3zef Beck]] ridiculed the treaties saying, \"Germany was officially asked to attack the east, in return for peace in the west.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Brecher|title=The World of Protracted Conflicts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xQ4XDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA204|year=2016|publisher=Lexington Books|page=204|isbn=9781498531887}}</ref> \n \nIn the 1920s, France built the [[Maginot Line]], an elaborate system of static border defences, designed to fight off any German attack. The Maginot Line did not extend into Belgium, where Germany attacked in 1940 and went around the French defenses.  Military alliances were signed with weak powers in 1920\u201321, called the \"[[Little Entente]]\".<ref>William Allcorn, ''The Maginot Line 1928\u201345'' (2012).</ref>\n\n===1930s===\nBritish historian [[Richard Overy]] explains how the country that had dominated Europe for three centuries wanted one last extension of power, but failed in its resolve:\n:In the 1930s France became a deeply conservative,  defensive society, split by social conflict, undermined by failing and un-modernized economy and an empire in crisis. All these things explain the loss of will and direction in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|author=Richard Overy|title=The road to war|page=189}}</ref>\n\nThe foreign policy of right-wing Prime Minister [[Pierre Laval]] (1934\u20131936) was based on a distrust of Britain. By 1936, he sought rapprochement with Germany, relied heavily on cooperation with Fascist Italy, and dealt in personal diplomacy. He did sign a defense agreement with the Soviet Union in 1935, but it was not implements by Laval nor by his left-wing successors.<ref>Duroselle, ''France and the Nazi threat'' (2004) pp 85\u2013111.</ref>\n\nAppeasement was increasingly adopted as Germany grew stronger, for France was increasingly weakened by a stagnant economy, unrest in its colonies, and bitter internal political fighting.  Appeasement was the fall-back position when it was impossible to make a major decision.  Martin Thomas says it was not a coherent diplomatic strategy nor a copying of the British.<ref>Martin Thomas,  \"Appeasement in the Late Third Republic\", ''Diplomacy and Statecraft'' 19#3 (2008): 566\u2013607.</ref>   When Hitler in 1936 sent troops into the Rhineland\u2014the part of Germany where no troops were allowed\u2014neither Paris nor London would risk war, and nothing was done.<ref>Stephen A. Schuker, \"France and the Remilitarization of the Rhineland, 1936\", ''French Historical Studies'' 14.3 (1986): 299\u2013338.</ref> France also appeased Italy on the Ethiopia question because it could not afford to risk an alliance between Italy and Germany.<ref>Reynolds M. Salerno, \"The French Navy and the Appeasement of Italy, 1937\u20139\", ''English Historical Review'' 112#445 (1997): 66\u2013104.</ref>\n\nHitler's remilitarization of the Rhineland changed the balance of power decisively in favor of the ''Reich''.<ref>Gerhard Weinberg, ''The Foreign Policy of Hitler's Germany Diplomatic Revolution in Europe 1933\u201336'' (1970), p. 262.</ref> French credibility in standing against German expansion or aggression was left in doubt. French military strategy was entirely defensive, and it had no intention whatever of invading Germany if war broke out. Instead it planned  to defend the [[Maginot Line]]. Its failure to send even a single unit into Rhineland signaled that strategy to all of Europe. Potential allies in Eastern Europe could no longer trust in an alliance with a France that could not be trusted to deter Germany through threat of an invasion.  without such deterrence, the ally was militarily helpless.  Belgium dropped its defensive alliance with France and relied on neutrality. Paris neglected to expand the Maginot line to cover the Belgian border, which is where Germany invaded in 1940.  Mussolini had previously pushed back against German expansion, now he realized cooperation with France was unpromising, so he began instead to swing in favor of Berlin. All of France's friends were disappointed \u2013 even the Pope told the French ambassador that, \"Had you ordered the immediate advance of 200,000 men into the zone the Germans had occupied, you would have done everyone a very great favor.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Record|title=The Specter of Munich: Reconsidering the Lessons of Appeasing Hitler|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aV0B4_cBkc0C&pg=PA29|year=2007|publisher=Potomac Books|pages=27\u201329|isbn=9781597970396}}</ref>\n\n[[Appeasement]] in union with Britain now became the main policy after 1936, as France sought peace in the face of Hitler's escalating demands.    [[\u00c9douard Daladier]]. prime minister 1938\u201340, refused to go to war against Germany and Italy without British support. He endorsed [[Neville Chamberlain]] who wanted to save peace using the [[Munich Agreement]] in 1938.<ref>{{cite book|author=Martin Thomas|title=Britain, France and Appeasement: Anglo-French Relations in the Popular Front Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TJXqvBz3JHcC&pg=PA137|year=1996|publisher=Berg|page=137|isbn=9781859731925}}</ref><ref>Maurice Larkin, ''France since the Popular Front: Government and People, 1936\u20131986'' (1988) pp 63\u201381</ref>  France's military alliance with Czechoslovakia was sacrificed at Hitler's demand when France and Britain agreed to his terms at [[Munich Agreement|Munich]] in 1938.<ref>Nicole Jordan, \"L\u00e9on Blum and Czechoslovakia, 1936\u20131938.\" ''French History'' 5#1 (1991): 48\u201373.</ref><ref>Martin Thomas, \"France and the Czechoslovak crisis\", ''Diplomacy and Statecraft'' 10.23 (1999): 122\u2013159.</ref>\n\nThe left-wing [[L\u00e9on Blum]] government in 1936\u201337 joined the right-wing Britain government in establishing an arms embargo during the [[Spanish Civil War]] (1936\u201339). Blum rejected support for the Spanish Republicans because of his fear that civil war might spread to deeply divided France.<ref>George C. Windell, \"L\u00e9on Blum and the Crisis over Spain, 1936\", ''Historian'' (1962) 24#4 pp 423\u2013449</ref>  As the Republican cause faltered in Spain, Blum secretly supplied the Republican cause with warplanes money and sanctuaries.  The government nationalized arms suppliers, and dramatically increased its program of rearming the French military in a last-minute catch up with the Germans.  It also tried to build up the weak Polish army.<ref>Larkin, ''France since the Popular Front'', (1988) pp 45\u201362</ref>\n\nFrench foreign policy in the 1920s and 1930s aimed to build military alliances with small nations in Eastern Europe in order to counter the threat of German attacks.  Paris saw Romania as an ideal partner in this venture, especially in  1926 to 1939. During World War II the alliance failed. Romania was first neutral and then after Germany defeated France in 1940 it aligned with Germany. The main device France had used was arms sales in order to strengthen Romania and ensure its goodwill. French military promises were vague and not trusted after the sellout of Czechoslovakia at Munich in 1938, By 1938 French needed all the arms it could produce. Meanwhile Germany was better poised to build strong economic ties.  In 1938-39 France made a final effort to guarantee Romanian borders because it calculated that Germany needed Romanian oil, but Romania decided war with Germany would be hopeless and so it veered toward Berlin.<ref>William A. Hoisington Jr, \"The Struggle for Economic Influence in Southeastern Europe: The French Failure in Romania, 1940.\" ''Journal of Modern History'' 43.3 (1971): 468-482.  [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1878564 online]</ref>\n\n==Second World War ==\n{{further|Vichy France|Free France|Military history of France during World War II}}\n\n===Entry into war===\n{{Main|Munich Agreement}}\n\nIn 1938 Germany demanded control of the German-speaking [[Sudetenland]] region of Czechoslovakia. That small country had a defense alliance with France but militarily its position was hopeless. The Munich conference  of September 29\u201330, 1938, was a summit meeting of leaders from Germany, Italy Britain and France.  The Soviet Union and Czechoslovakia were not invited.  The British and French wanted peace\u2014or at least enough delay to allow them to try to catch up to German military superiority. Britain did not control French actions, but London had more influence on Paris than vice versa. The leading French voice for cooperating with British Prime Chamberlain in appeasement was foreign minister [[Georges Bonnet]]. He was a \"munichois\"\u2014that is, a defeatist and pacifist who sensed that France would lose to Germany in a war.<ref>Daniel Hucker, \"Public Opinion between Munich and Prague: The View from the French Embassy.\" ''Contemporary British History'' 25.3 (2011): 407-427.</ref>  He wanted to abandon the alliances with  Poland and Russia and allow Germany a free hand in the east so it would ignore France.<ref>Anthony Adamthwaite, ''Grandeur And Misery: France's Bid for Power in Europe, 1914\u20131940'' (1995) p 216.</ref>  After a short conference Hitler got his way\u2014the agreement allowed Germany to peacefully absorb the Sudetenland.<ref>John McVickar Haight Jr,  \"France, the United States, and the Munich crisis.\" ''Journal of Modern History'' 32.4 (1960): 340\u2013358.</ref> In March, 1939, Germany took over Bohemia and Moravia, and turned Slovakia into a puppet state. The British and French finally realized that appeasement did not produce peace.<ref>Jean-Baptiste Duroselle, ''France and the Nazi Threat: The Collapse of French Diplomacy 1932\u20131939'' (2004) pp 277\u2013301.</ref><ref>Robert Boyce, ''French Foreign and Defence Policy, 1918\u20131940: The Decline and Fall of a Great Power'' (1998) [https://www.questia.com/library/108244015/french-foreign-and-defence-policy-1918-1940-the online]</ref><ref>Robert J. Young, ''France and the Origins of the Second World War'' (1996) [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=LkxdDwAAQBAJ  excerpt], covers historiography in ch 2.</ref>\n\nIn spring 1939 Hitler demanded concessions from Poland and this time Britain and France announced they would go to war to defend the integrity of Poland. Efforts to bring the USSR into the coalition failed and instead it formed an agreement with Hitler to divide up Poland and Eastern Europe.  Hitler did not believe the Allies would fight in such a faraway hopeless cause, and he invaded Poland on September 1, 1939. Britain and France declared war on September 3, 1939. But there was little they could or did do to help Poland.<ref>Duroselle, ''France and the Nazi Threat'' pp 336\u2013415,</ref><ref>Andrew  Boxer, \"French Appeasement: Andrew Boxer Considers Explanations for France's Disastrous Foreign Policy between the Wars.\" ''History Review'' 59 (2007): 45.</ref>\n\n===German conquest 1940===\nFrance and Britain together declared war against Germany two days after it invaded Poland.  The British and French empires joined the war but no one else.  Britain and France took a defensive posture, fearing German air attacks on cities. France hoped the [[Maginot Line]] would protect it from an invasion. There was little fighting between the fall of Poland in mid-September and the following spring; it was the [[Phoney War]] in Britain or ''Dr\u00f4le de guerre'' \u2013 \"the funny sort of war\" \u2013 in France. Britain tried several peace feelers, but Hitler did not respond.<ref>Gerhard L. Weinberg, ''A World at Arms: A Global History of World War II'' (1994) ch 2. [https://archive.org/details/worldatarmsgloba00wein online free to borrow]</ref>\n\nIn spring 1940 Germany launched its [[Blitzkrieg]] against Denmark and Norway, easily pushing the British out. Then it invaded the Low Countries and tricked Britain and France into sending their best combat units deep into the Netherlands, where they became trapped in the [[Battle of France]] in May 1940. The Royal Navy rescued over 300,000 British and French soldiers from Dunkirk, but left behind all the equipment.<ref>Joel Blatt, ed., ''The French Defeat of 1940'' (1998)</ref>\n\nParis fell to the Germans on 14 June 1940, and the government surrendered on 24 June 1940. Nazi Germany occupied three-fifths of France's territory, leaving the rest in the southeast to the new Vichy government, which was a bit more than a puppet state since it still had a navy.  However nearly 2 million French soldiers became prisoners of war in Germany. They served as hostages and forced laborers in German factories. The United States suddenly realized Germany was on the verge of controlling practically all of Europe, and it determined to rapidly build up its small Army and Air Force, and expand its Navy. Sympathy with Britain was high, and many were willing to send munitions, but few Americans called for war.<ref>Weinberg, ''A World at Arms: A Global History of World War II'' (1994) ch 3. [https://archive.org/details/worldatarmsgloba00wein online free to borrow]</ref>\n\n===Vichy France===\n{{main|Foreign relations of Vichy France}}\nThe fall of France in June 1940 brought a new regime known as [[Vichy France]]. Theoretically it was neutral, but in practice it was partly controlled by Germany until November 1942, when Germany took full control. Vichy was intensely conservative and anti-Communist, but it was practically helpless with Germany controlling half of France directly and holding nearly two million French POWs as hostages. Vichy finally collapsed when the Germans fled in summer 1944.<ref>Peter Jackson and Simon Kitson, \"The paradoxes of foreign policy in Vichy France\", in Jonathan Adelman, ed., ''Hitler and His Allies in World War Two'' (Routledge, 2007) pp&nbsp;79\u2013115 [https://www.amazon.com/Hitler-His-Allies-World-War/dp/0415321670/  excerpt and text search]</ref>\n\nThe United States granted Vichy full diplomatic recognition, sending Admiral [[William D. Leahy]] to Paris as American ambassador. President Roosevelt hoped to use American influence to encourage those elements in the Vichy government opposed to military collaboration with Germany. Vichy still controlled its overseas colonies and Washington encouraged Vichy to resist German demands such as for air bases in Syria or to move war supplies through French North Africa. The essential American position was that France should take no action not explicitly required by the armistice terms that could adversely affect Allied efforts in the war. When Germany took full control the U.S. and Canada cut their ties.<ref>William Langer, ''Our Vichy gamble'' (1947)</ref>\n\n====French fleet====\nBritain feared that the French naval fleet could end up in German hands and be used against its own naval forces, which were so vital to maintaining north Atlantic shipping and communications. Under the armistice, France had been allowed to retain the [[French Navy]], the ''Marine Nationale'', under strict conditions. Vichy pledged that the fleet would never fall into the hands of Germany, but refused to send the fleet beyond Germany's reach by sending it to Britain or to far away territories of the French empire such as the West Indies. Shortly after France gave up it attacked a large French naval contingent in [[Destruction of the French Fleet at Mers-el-Kebir|Mers-el-Kebir]], killing 1,297 French military personnel. Vichy severed diplomatic relations but did not declare war on Britain. Churchill also ordered French ships in British ports to be seized by the Royal Navy. The French squadron at [[Alexandria|Alexandria, Egypt]], under Admiral [[Ren\u00e9-Emile Godfroy]], was effectively interned until 1943.\n\nThe American position towards Vichy France and Free France was inconsistent. President Roosevelt disliked and distrusted de Gaulle, and agreed with Ambassador Leahy's view that he was an \"apprentice dictator.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=David Mayers|title=FDR's Ambassadors and the Diplomacy of Crisis: From the Rise of Hitler to the End of World War II|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wjLKYL3xbmAC&pg=PA160|year= 2012|publisher=Cambridge U.P.|page=160|isbn=9781107031265}}</ref>\n\n====North Africa====\nPreparing for a landing in North Africa in late 1942, the US looked for a top French ally. It turned to [[Henri Giraud]] shortly before the landing on 8 November 1942, but he had little local support. By hapstance the Vichy leader Admiral [[Fran\u00e7ois Darlan]] was captured and supported the Americans. The Allies, with General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] in charge,  signed a deal with Admiral Darlan on 22 November 1942 in which the Allies recognized Darlan as high commissioner for North Africa and West Africa.<ref>Arthur L. Funk, \"Negotiating the 'Deal with Darlan,'\" ''Journal of Contemporary History''  (1973) 8#1 pp&nbsp;81\u2013117 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/259995 in JSTOR].</ref> The Allied world was stunned at giving a high command to man who days before had been collaborating with the Nazis; Roosevelt and Churchill supported Eisenhower, for he was following a plan that had been worked out in London and had been approved by Roosevelt and Churchill.  Darlan was assassinated on 24 December 1942, so Washington turned again towards Giraud, who was made High Commissioner of French North and West Africa. Giraud failed to build a political base and was displaced by the last man with any standing, de Gaulle.<ref>Martin Thomas, \"The Discarded Leader: General Henri Giraud and the Foundation of the French Committee of National Liberation\", ''French History'' (1996) 10#12 pp&nbsp;86\u2013111</ref><ref>Adrienne Doris Hytier, ''Two Years of French Foreign Policy: Vichy, 1940\u20131942'' (1958) [https://www.questia.com/library/405717/two-years-of-french-foreign-policy-vichy-1940-1942 online]</ref>\n\n===Free France===\n{{see also|Free French Forces}}\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:De-gaulle-radio.jpg|thumb|right|General de Gaulle speaking on [[BBC Radio]] during the war]] -->\n\nFree France was the insurgent French government based in London and the overseas French colonies and led by charismatic general [[Charles de Gaulle]]. He was the most senior French military officer to reject the June 1940 surrender (\"Armistice\") and oppose the Vichy government of Marshall P\u00e9tain. From London on 18 June 1940 he gave an impassioned radio address [[Appeal of 18 June|exhorting the patriotic French people to resist]] [[Nazi Germany]]<ref name=\"Berthon\">{{Cite book|title=Allies at War: The Bitter Rivalry among Churchill, Roosevelt, and de Gaulle |last=Berthon|first=Simon|year=2001|publisher=Collins|place=London|isbn=978-0-00-711622-5|page=21}}</ref>  He organized the [[Free French Forces]] from soldiers that had escaped with the British at Dunkirk. With British military support the Free French gradually gained control of all French colonies except [[French Indochina|Indochina]], which the Japanese controlled.  The U.S., Britain and Canada wanted Vichy to keep nominal control of the small islands of [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon|St. Pierre and Miquelon]] for reasons of prestige, but de Gaulle seized them anyway in late 1941.<ref>Martin Thomas, \"Deferring to Vichy in the Western Hemisphere: The St. Pierre and Miquelon Affair of 1941\", ''International History Review'' (1997) 19#4 pp&nbsp;809\u2013835.[http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/07075332.1997.9640805#.UcdqXJyDnsg online]</ref>\n\nDe Gaulle headed a government in exile based in London, but he continued to create diplomatic problems for the U.S. and Britain. When the British and Americans landed in France in June 1944, he refused to allow French soldiers to land on D-Day. He insisted that France be treated as a great power by the other Allies, and that he himself was the only representative of France. Roosevelt disliked him, but he had Churchill's support. The U.S. and Britain allowed de Gaulle the honor of being the first to march into Paris at the head of his army after the Germans had fled.<ref>Jean Lacouture, ''DeGaulle: The Rebel, 1890\u20131944'' (1990) pp&nbsp;515\u201327</ref>\n\nCommunists played a major role in the French resistance, and the USSR was leading the fight against Germany, so De Gaulle emphasized that Free France supported the USSR.<ref>Robert Gildea, ''France since 1945'' (2002) pp 30-35.</ref> Relations cooled in fall 1943 to summer 1944, then warmed up again and de Gaulle visited Moscow. He made concessions to Stalin to obtain Soviet support against Anglo-Saxon dominance.  There was a hope of making France a bridge between the Soviets and the Anglo-Americans. None of the  Big Three wanted to pretend that France was a power again, so it was not invited to the decisive Yalta conference in February 1945, which was humiliating.  Furthermore, Communist efforts to seize power in Poland Europe, as directed by Stalin, were worrisome to the French. With Roosevelt replaced by Harry Truman, De Gaulle increasingly turned to the American presence to maintain balance of power.<ref>John Young, \"Stalin and de Gaulle\", ''History Today'' (June 1990) 40#6.</ref>\n\n==Fourth Republic, 1944\u20131958==\n{{Further|French Fourth Republic|Cold War}}\n\nThe [[Popular Republican Movement]] (MRP), a large moderate party based on the Catholic vote, dominated French foreign and colonial policies during most of the later 1940s and 1950s. Along with the French Socialist Party, it was the most energetic supporter in the country of European integration. It was also a strong backer of [[NATO]] and of close alliance with the United States, making it the most \"Atlanticist\" of French political parties.  Its leaders, especially [[Georges Bidault]] and [[Paul Coste-Floret]] (foreign and colonial ministers respectively in several French coalition governments) were primary architects of France's hard-line colonial policies that culminated in long insurgencies in [[Vietnam]] (1946\u20131954) and [[Algeria]] (1954\u20131962), as well as a series of smaller insurrections and political crises elsewhere in the French Empire. The MRP eventually divided over the Algerian question in the late 1950s (with Bidault being an avid supporter of the [[Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]]).<ref>Russell Beckett Capelle, ''The MRP and French foreign policy'' (1963).  [https://www.questia.com/library/1022177/the-mrp-and-french-foreign-policy online]</ref>\n\nFrance was bitter when the United States and Britain refused to share atomic secrets with it. The upshot was France developed its own nuclear weapons and delivery systems.<ref>Peter K. Parides,  \"The Halban Affair and British Atomic Diplomacy at the End of the Second World War.\" ''Diplomacy & Statecraft'' 23.4 (2012): 619\u2013635.</ref>   However Britain did ensure that France was included in the split of conquered Germany into Soviet, British, American and French zones.  Following Soviet refusals to participate in a German rebuilding effort set forth by western European countries in 1948, the US, Britain and France spearheaded the establishment of West Germany from the [[Bizone|three Western zones of occupation]] in April 1949.<ref>Heike Bungert, \"A New Perspective on French-American Relations during the Occupation of Germany, 1945\u20131948: Behind-the-Scenes Diplomatic Bargaining and the Zonal Merger.\" ''Diplomatic History'' (1994) 18#3 pp: 333\u2013352.</ref>\n\nThe [[Cold War]] began in 1947, as Britain and the United States started providing aid to Greece and Turkey, in order to prevent a Communist takeover.  Despite its large pro-Soviet Communist Party, France joined the Allies. The first move was the Franco-British alliance realized in the Dunkirk Treaty in March 1947.<ref>Sean Greenwood,  \"Return to Dunkirk: The origins of the Anglo\u2010French treaty of March 1947.\" ''The Journal of Strategic Studies'' 6.4 (1983): 49\u201365.</ref>\n\nThe [[Marshall Plan]] (officially the European Recovery Program, ERP) was the American initiative 1948\u20131951 to aid Europe, in which the United States gave away $17 billion (approximately $160 billion in current dollar value) in economic support to help rebuild European economies and foster European unity in the face of Soviet threats. France received $2.3 billion about 18% of the Marshall total. This allowed France to make heavy purchases of food and machinery from the United States.<ref>Chiarella Esposito, ''America's feeble weapon: funding the Marshall Plan in France and Italy, 1948\u20131950'' (Greenwood 1994)</ref> Counting other programs, the U.S. government in total gave France $4.7  billion in grants from 1945 through 1951.  There was no requirement for repayment.<ref>{{cite book|author=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Bozo|title=French Foreign Policy since 1945: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PICLCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15|year=2016|publisher=Berghahn Books|page=15|isbn=9781785332777}}</ref>  The Marshall Plan required a lessening of interstate barriers, a dropping of many petty regulations constraining business (such as a limit on Hollywood films), and encouraged increase productivity, labour Union membership, and the adoption of modern business procedures.<ref>Anthony Carew, ''Labour under the Marshall Plan: the politics of productivity and the marketing of management science'' (Manchester University Press, 1987)</ref>\n \nFrance, the United States, Britain, Canada and eight other western European countries signed the [[North Atlantic Treaty]] in April 1949, establishing the [[NATO|North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO).<ref>John Lewis Gaddis, ''The Cold War: A New History'' (2005). p. 34\"</ref>\n\n===Indochina War (1946\u20131954)===\n{{Main|First Indochina War}}\nThe First Indochina War (generally known as the ''Indochina War'' in France) began in [[French Indochina]] on 19 December 1946 and lasted until 1 August 1954.  Fighting between French forces and their Communist opponents known as the [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] began in September 1945. The conflict pitted a range of forces, including the [[French Union]]'s [[French Far East Expeditionary Corps]], led by [[French Fourth Republic|France]] and supported by Emperor [[B\u1ea3o \u0110\u1ea1i]]'s [[Vietnamese National Army]] against the Vi\u1ec7t Minh, led by [[Ho Chi Minh]] and [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]]. Most of the fighting took place in [[Tonkin]] in Northern Vietnam, along with Chinese border. The conflict eventually reached most of Vietnam and also extended into the neighboring French Indochina protectorates of [[Laos]] and [[Cambodia]].\n\nAfter the Japanese surrendered, Chinese forces in September 1945 entered Tonkin and a small British task force landed at Saigon. The Chinese accepted the Vietnamese government under Ho Chi Minh, created by resistance forces of the Vi\u1ec7t Minh, then in power in Hanoi. The British refused to do likewise in Saigon, and deferred to the French there from the outset, against the ostensible support of the Vi\u1ec7t Minh by American [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]] representatives. On [[V-J Day]], September 2, Ho Chi Minh, had proclaimed in Hanoi the establishment of the Democratic Republic of Vietnam (DRV). The DRV ruled as the only civil government in all of Vietnam for a period of about 20 days, after the abdication of the \"Japanese puppet\", Emperor B\u1ea3o \u0110\u1ea1i.  On 23 September 1945,  French forces overthrew the local DRV government, and declared French authority restored in Cochinchina. Guerrilla warfare began around Saigon immediately.<ref>{{cite web|title=United States \u2013 Vietnam Relations, 1945\u20131967: A Study Prepared by the Department of Defense/I. A. U.S. Policy, 1940\u201350, pages 18\u201319|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page%3APentagon-Papers-Part_I.djvu/30|publisher=the Pentagon|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe first few years of the war involved a low-level rural insurgency against French authority. However, after the Chinese communists reached the Northern border of Vietnam in 1949, the conflict turned into a conventional war between two armies equipped with modern weapons supplied by the United States and the Soviet Union.<ref>Ronald  Irving, ''The first Indochina war: French and American policy, 1945\u201354'' (Croom Helm, 1975)</ref> French Union forces included colonial troops from the whole  empire (Moroccan, Algerian, Tunisian, Laotian, Cambodian, and Vietnamese ethnic minorities), French professional troops and units of the [[French Foreign Legion]]. The use of [[Metropolitan France|metropolitan]] recruits was forbidden by the government to prevent the war from becoming even more unpopular at home. It was called the \"dirty war\" (''la sale guerre'') by the Left in France.<ref>Edward Rice-Maximin, ''Accommodation and Resistance: The French Left, Indochina, and the Cold War, 1944\u20131954'' (Greenwood, 1986).</ref>\n\nWhile the strategy of pushing the Vi\u1ec7t Minh into attacking a well-defended base in a remote part of the country at the end of their logistical trail was validated at the [[Battle of N\u00e0 S\u1ea3n]], the lack of construction materials (especially concrete), tanks (because of lack of road access and difficulty in the jungle terrain), and air cover precluded an effective defense, culminating in a decisive French defeat at the [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu]].<ref>Nikki Cooper, \"Dien Bien Phu\u2014fifty years on.\" ''Modern & Contemporary France'' (2004) 12#4 pp: 445\u2013457.</ref>\n\nAt the [[Geneva Conference (1954)|international Geneva Conference]] on July 21, 1954 the new socialist French government and the Vi\u1ec7t Minh made an agreement that was denounced by the government of Vietnam and by the United States, but which effectively gave the Communists control of North Vietnam above the [[Vietnamese Demilitarized Zone|17th parallel]].  [[South Vietnam]], with heavy American support. continued under Emperor B\u1ea3o \u0110\u1ea1i.  In 1955 B\u1ea3o \u0110\u1ea1i would be deposed by his prime minister, [[Ng\u00f4 \u0110\u00ecnh Di\u1ec7m]], creating the Republic of Vietnam. Soon an insurgency backed by the North developed against Di\u1ec7m's government. The conflict gradually escalated into the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>Spencer Tucker, ed. ''Encyclopedia of the Vietnam War'' (3 vol. 1998)</ref>\n\n[[Pierre Mend\u00e8s France]] was a [[Radical Party (France)|Radical party leader]] and the Prime Minister for eight months in 1954\u201355, working with the support of the Socialist and Communist parties. His top priority was ending the war in Indochina, which had already cost 92,000 dead 114,000 wounded and 28,000 captured. Public opinion polls show that in February 1954, only 7% of the French people wanted to continue the fight to keep Indochina out of the hands of the Communists, led by [[Ho Chi Minh]] and his [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] movement.<ref>Maurice Larkin, ''France since the Popular Front: Government and People 1936\u20131996'' (1997) pp 240\u20131.</ref> At the [[Geneva Conference (1954)]] He made a deal that gave the Vi\u1ec7t Minh control of Vietnam north of the seventeenth parallel, and allowed him to pull out all French forces.<ref>Kenneth T. Young, ''The 1954 Geneva Conference: Indo-China and Korea'' (Greenwood Press, 1968)</ref> That left South Vietnam standing alone. However, the United States moved in and provided large scale financial military and economic support for South Vietnam.<ref>{{cite book|author=Thomas J. Christensen|title=Worse Than a Monolith: Alliance Politics and Problems of Coercive Diplomacy in Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z1v2pqaOmuEC&pg=PA123|year=2011|publisher=Princeton UP|pages=123\u201325|isbn=978-1400838813}}</ref> Mend\u00e8s France next came to an agreement with [[Habib Bourguiba]], the nationalist leader in Tunisia, for the independence of that colony by 1956, and began discussions with the nationalist leaders in Morocco for a French withdrawal.<ref>Alexander Werth, ''The Strange History of Pierre Mend\u00e8s France and the Great Conflict over French North Africa'' (London, 1957)</ref>\n\n===European unification begins===\nFrench fears of a resurgent Germany made it reluctant to support the plan to merge the British and American zones of occupation. However growing fear of the Soviets, and the need for American economic assistance led the French to merge their zone into what became West Germany.<ref>Heike Bungert,  \"A New Perspective on French-American Relations during the Occupation of Germany, 1945\u20131948: Behind-the-Scenes Diplomatic Bargaining and the Zonal Merger.\" ''Diplomatic History'' 18.3 (1994): 333\u2013352.</ref>\n\nThe creation of the [[European Coal and Steel Community]] (ECSC) was first proposed by French foreign minister [[Robert Schuman]] and French economic theorist [[Jean Monnet]] on 9 May 1950 as a way to prevent further war between France and Germany.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Holm|title=The Marshall Plan: A New Deal For Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vi4lDwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=159\u201360|isbn=9781317426059}}</ref>\n\nThough Britain was invited, its [[Attlee ministry|Labour government]], then preparing for a re-election fight, did not join the initiative.<ref>Edmund Dell, ''The Schuman Plan and the British Abdication of Leadership in Europe'' (1995).</ref> ECSC was formally established in 1951 by the [[Treaty of Paris (1951)|Treaty of Paris]], signed by France, Italy, West Germany and the three [[Benelux]] states: Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands. Among these states the ECSC would remove trade barriers and create a [[Single market|common market]] for coal and steel. The ECSC was governed by a 'High Authority', checked by bodies representing governments, Members of Parliament and an [[independent judiciary]].<ref>Desmond Dinan, ''Ever closer union: an introduction to European integration'' (1999) [https://www.rienner.com/uploads/47e029fe2f724.pdf online excerpt].</ref>\n\n==Fifth Republic (1958 to 1981)==\nSee [[Foreign relations of France]], which covers 1981 to the present.\n\n===President de Gaulle, 1958\u20131969===\n{{main|Foreign policy of Charles de Gaulle|Charles de Gaulle#1962\u201368: Politics of grandeur|Gaullism}}\n\nThe [[May 1958 crisis|May 1958 seizure of power in Algiers by French army units]] and French settlers opposed to concessions in the face of Arab nationalist insurrection ripped apart the unstable Fourth Republic. The National Assembly brought him back to power during the May 1958 crisis. De Gaulle founded the Fifth Republic with a strengthened presidency, and he was elected in the latter role. He managed to keep France together while taking steps to end the war, much to the anger of the Pieds-Noirs (Frenchmen settled in Algeria) and the military; both previously had supported his return to power to maintain colonial rule. He granted independence to Algeria in 1962 and progressively to other French colonies.<ref>Winock, Michel. \"De Gaulle and the Algerian Crisis 1958\u20131962.\" in Hugh Gough and John Home, eds., ''De Gaulle and Twentieth Century France'' (1994) pp 71\u201382.</ref>\n\nProclaiming that grandeur was the essential to the nature of France, de Gaulle initiated his \"Politics of Grandeur\",<ref>{{cite book|last=Kolodziej|first= Edward A|title=French International Policy under de Gaulle and Pompidou: The Politics of Grandeur|year=1974|page=618}}</ref> He demanded complete autonomy for France in world affairs, which meant that it has its major decisions which could not be forced upon it by NATO, the European Community or anyone else. De Gaulle pursued a policy of \"national independence.\"  He twice vetoed Britain's entry into the Common Market, fearing it might overshadow France in European affairs.<ref>Helen Parr, \"Saving the Community: The French Response to Britain's Second EEC Application in 1967\", ''Cold War History'' (2006) 6#4 pp 425\u2013454</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=W. W. Kulski|title=De Gaulle and the World: The Foreign Policy of the Fifth French Republic|url=https://archive.org/details/degaulleworld00kuls|url-access=registration|year=1966|publisher=Syracuse UP|page=239ff}}</ref> While not officially abandoning [[NATO]], he withdraw from its military integrated command, fearing that the United States had too much control over NATO.<ref>{{cite book|author=Kulski|title=De Gaulle and the World: The Foreign Policy of the Fifth French Republic|publisher=Syracuse University Press|url=https://archive.org/details/degaulleworld00kuls|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/degaulleworld00kuls/page/176 176]|year=1966}}</ref> He launched an independent [[Force de dissuasion|nuclear development program]] that made France the [[France and weapons of mass destruction|fourth nuclear power]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Gabrielle Hecht and Michel Callon, eds.|title=The Radiance of France: Nuclear Power and National Identity after World War II|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8yl2BbxqFY0C&pg=PR7|year=2009|publisher=MIT Press|pages=7\u20139|isbn=9780262266178}}</ref>\n\nHe [[\u00c9lys\u00e9e Treaty|restored]] cordial [[Franco-German relations]] in order to create a European counterweight between the \"Anglo-Saxon\" (American and British) and Soviet spheres of influence.  De Gaulle openly criticised the [[Vietnam War|U.S. intervention in Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/de-gaulle-urges-the-united-states-to-get-out-of-vietnam|title=De Gaulle urges the United States to get out of Vietnam|publisher=History.com|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> He was angry at American economic power, especially what his Finance minister called the \"[[exorbitant privilege]]\" of the U.S. dollar.<ref>{{cite book|author=Barry Eichengreen|title=Exorbitant Privilege: The Rise and Fall of the Dollar and the Future of the International Monetary System|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TIlpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA4|year=2011|publisher=Oxford UP|page=4|isbn=9780199781485}}</ref> He went to Canada and proclaimed \"[[Vive le Qu\u00e9bec libre]]\", The catchphrase for an independent Quebec.<ref>See [https://books.google.com/books?id=aA8WBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&dq=de+gaulle+free+quebec&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=cCSlVJTiMoT8UriogvgK&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=de%20gaulle%20free%20quebec&f=false Wayne C. Thompson, ''Canada 2014'' (2013)]</ref>\n\nDe Gaulle resigned in 1969 after losing a [[1969 French constitutional referendum|referendum]] in which he proposed more decentralization.\n\n===President Georges Pompidou 1969\u20131974===\nAs president, [[Georges Pompidou]] had full charge of foreign-policy, largely ignoring his premier [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]] and relying instead on his aide [[Maurice Schumann]]. Pompidou tried to closely follow de Gaulle's policies, but he totally lacked the General's charisma, innovation and ability to startled friends and enemies alike. He lacked experience and a smooth hand, and for the first two years most of his initiatives proved failures. Fortunately for his domestic popularity, the French people paid little attention to foreign affairs.  In terms of Mediterranean policy, he made an effort to foster closer relations with North African and Middle Eastern countries in order to develop a hinterland including all nations bordering the Mediterranean. However, de Gaulle had favored the  Arab cause against the Israelis, especially in the [[Six-Day War]] in 1967 in which Israel, under attack from all directions, decisively defeated  all its Arab neighbors. Pompidou continued the hostility, and tried to come to terms with Morocco as well. He tried to sell French weapons to [[Muammar Gaddafi|Colonel Qaddafi]], the reckless dictator of Libya. An outburst of international hostility scuttled that adventure. His greatest disaster came and Algeria, Which doubled its taxes on French-owned oilfields, and finally nationalized them in 1971. Pompidou watched helplessly.<ref>Serge Berstein and Jean-Pierre Rioux, ''The Pompidou Years, 1969\u20131974'' (2000) pp 22\u201324.</ref>\n\nThe United States was eager to restore positive relations with France after de Gaulle's departure from office. New US President [[Richard Nixon]] and his top adviser [[Henry Kissinger]] admired Pompidou; the politicians were in agreement on most major policy issues. The United States offered to help the French nuclear programme. Economic difficulties, however, arose following the [[Nixon Shock]] and the [[1973\u201375 recession]], particularly over the role of the American dollar as the medium for world trade.<ref>Marc Trachtenberg, \"The French Factor in US Foreign Policy during the Nixon-Pompidou Period\", in  ''The Cold War and After: History, Theory, and the Logic of International Politics'' (2012) ch 7.</ref>\n\nPompidou did well in fostering helpful guidance with the newly-independent former French colonies in Africa. In 1971, he visited Mauritania, Senegal, Ivory Coast, Cameroons, and Gabon. He brought a message of cooperation and financial assistance, but without the traditional paternalism.<ref>Edward A. Kolodziej, ''French Foreign Policy under de Gaulle and Pompidou: The Politics of Grandeur'' (1974).</ref>\n\n===President Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing, 1974\u20131981  ===\n[[File:Carter guadeloupe.gif|thumb|230px|right|Leaders [[Helmut Schmidt]] of West Germany, [[Jimmy Carter]] of the U.S., Giscard and [[James Callaghan]] of Britain, in Guadeloupe, 1979]]\n\nGiscard was a pragmagtist who billed himself as \"a conservative who likes change.\" In 1975 he invited the heads of government from [[West Germany]], Italy, Japan, the United Kingdom and the United States to a summit to form the [[Group of Six]] major economic powers (now the [[G7]], including Canada).<ref>D. L. Hanley, A P Kerr, and N. H. Waites, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cmuIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA41 ''Contemporary France: Politics and Society Since 1945''] (2005) pp 41\u201343.</ref>  In support of European economic unification, Giscard and his friend West German Chancellor [[Helmut Schmidt]] launched the European Monetary System (EMS) in April 1978.<ref>Jonathan  Story, \"The launching of the EMS: an analysis of change in foreign economic policy.\" ''Political Studies'' 36.3 (1988): 397\u2013412.</ref><ref>Kenneth Dyson,  \"EMU, political discourse and the fifth French republic: Historical institutionalism, path dependency and \u2018craftsmen\u2019 of discourse.\" ''Modern & Contemporary France'' 7.2 (1999): 179\u2013196.</ref>\n\nIn 1977, in [[Op\u00e9ration Lamantin]], Giscard ordered fighter jets to deploy in Mauritania and suppress the [[Polisario]] guerrillas fighting against Mauritanian military occupation of [[Western Sahara]]. It failed to kep in power the French-installed Mauritanian leader [[Moktar Ould Daddah]], as he was overthrown by his own army. A peace agreement was signed with the [[Western Sahara|Sahrawi]] resistance.\n\nGiscard took an interest in the regime of [[Jean-B\u00e9del Bokassa]] in the [[Central African Republic]]. Giscard was initially a friend of Bokassa, and supplied the regime. However, the growing unpopularity of that government led Giscard to begin distancing himself from Bokassa. In 1979, French troops helped drive Bokassa out of power and restore former president [[David Dacko]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aSxIDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=Giscard+was+initially+a+friend+of+Bokassa#v=onepage&q=Giscard%20%20Bokassa%20David%20Dacko&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of the Central African Republic|last=Bradshaw|first=Richard|last2=Fandos-Rius|first2=Juan|date=27 May 2016|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810879928|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[File:Poincar\u00e9 Petit Journal 26 janvier 1913.jpg|right|thumb|[[Raymond Poincar\u00e9]] elected president in 1913.]]\n\n*[[Causes of World War I]]\n*[[Diplomatic history of World War II]]\n*[[Cold War]]\n*[[French colonial empire]]\n* [[French entry into World War I]]\n*[[Historiography of the British Empire]]\n*[[History of U.S. foreign policy]]\n*[[International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)]]\n*[[International relations (1919\u20131939)]]\n*[[Military history of France]]\n*[[Napoleonic Wars]]\n*[[Paris Peace Conference, 1919]]\n*[[Politics of France]]\n*[[Territorial evolution of France]]\n*[[Timeline of French history]]\n*\n*[[Austria\u2013France relations]]\n*[[Bulgaria\u2013France relations]]\n*[[China\u2013France relations]]\n*[[Egypt\u2013France relations]]\n*[[France\u2013Germany relations]]\n**[[Foreign relations of Germany]]\n*[[France\u2013Italy relations]]\n*[[France\u2013Russia relations]], includes USSR\n*[[France\u2013Serbia relations]]\n*[[France\u2013Spain relations