ased in the United States on May 15, 2020, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]], but due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the film got taken out of the release schedule.<ref name=\"Reschedule\">{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/new-saw-movie-spiral-antebellum-release-date-delayed-coronavirus/ |title=Lionsgate Delays Chris Rock's 'Saw' Movie, Janelle Monae's 'Antebellum' |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nLionsgate's officially released synopsis reads \"Working in the shadow of an esteemed police veteran ([[Samuel L. Jackson]]), brash detective Ezekiel \"Zeke\" Banks ([[Chris Rock]]) and his rookie partner William Schenk ([[Max Minghella]]) take charge of a grisly investigation into murders that are eerily reminiscent of the city's gruesome past. Unwittingly trapped in a deepening mystery, Zeke finds himself at the center of the killer's morbid game.\"<ref name=Patches />\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Chris Rock]] as Det. Ezekiel \"Zeke\" Banks\n* [[Samuel L. Jackson]] as Marcus\n* [[Max Minghella]] as Det. William Schenk<ref name=\"thewrap\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/samuel-l-jackson-joins-chris-rocks-saw-reboot/ |title=Samuel L. Jackson Joins Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=Welk |first=Brian |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=July 8, 2019 |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Marisol Nichols]] as Capt. Angie Garza<ref name=\"thewrap\"/>\n* [[Zoie Palmer]] as Kara Boswick\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAccording to [[Chris Rock]], the origins of ''Spiral: From The Book of Saw'' came from a chance meeting with the head of [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] at a friend's wedding, and felt doing something in the horror genre would be a new avenue to take his career, though planned to include some comedic elements in the film.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://collider.com/why-chris-rock-made-a-saw-movie/ | title = Chris Rock Explains Why He Made a 'Saw' Movie | first = Adam | last =Chitwood | date = January 13, 2020 | accessdate = January 22, 2020 | work = [[Collider (website)|Collider]] }}</ref>  Rock approached Lionsgate with his ideas of extending the franchise, who became very interested in the concept.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/chris-rock-to-reboot-saw-franchise-with-lionsgate-twisted-pictures-1202616185/ |title=Chris Rock To Reboot 'Saw' Franchise With Lionsgate & Twisted Pictures |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Lionsgate's CEO [[Joe Drake (producer)|Joe Drake]] said that Rock's idea was \"completely reverential to the legacy of the material while reinvigorating the brand with his wit, creative vision and passion for this classic horror franchise\".<ref name=\"announce\"/> By January 2018, industry rumors had said that Lionsgate had begun discussions of a ninth ''Saw'' film, for which [[The Spierig Brothers]] would not be returning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-jigsaw-sequel/ |title='Saw 9' Conversation is Reportedly Happening |last=Stephens |first=David |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet, Inc. |date=January 16, 2018 |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> By April 2018, [[Twisted Pictures]] was reported to be developing a sequel with ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'' writers [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3491755/jigsaw-writers-currently-working-next-saw-exclusive/ |title='Jigsaw' Writers Are Currently Working On Next 'Saw' [Exclusive] |last=Miska |first=Brad |date=April 3, 2018 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2019, the film was officially in production.<ref name=\"announce\"/> Former series director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] returned to helm the film, along with series veterans [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] as producers. Rock was involved as an executive producer, in addition to writing the story treatment. Joining Rock as executive producers included the original ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' creators [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]], along with Daniel Heffner.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3561412/saw-reimagined-chris-rock-darren-bousman-returning-direct/ |title='Saw' Being Reimagined by Chris Rock with Darren Bousman Returning to Direct! |first=Brad |last=Miska |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Stolberg and Goldfinger were affirmed as scriptwriters.<ref name=\"announce\"/> With the announcement, Rock stated, \"I've been a fan of ''Saw'' since the first film in 2004. I am excited by the opportunity to take this to a really intense and twisted new place.\"<ref name=\"announce\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/chris-rock-saw-spinoff-1203216731/ | title = Chris Rock Rebooting 'Saw' Franchise With Lionsgate | first=  Dave | last =  McNary | date = May 16, 2019 | accessdate = July 8, 2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | publisher = [[Penske Media Corporation]] }}</ref> Burg and Koules said that Rock's treatment of ''Saw'' was comparable to what [[Eddie Murphy]] had done for [[buddy cop film]]s in ''[[48 Hrs.]]'', giving the ''Saw'' series a \"completely fresh perspective\".<ref name=\"announce\"/> Stolberg later confirmed that the ninth installment will exist in the same canon as the previous eight films, and will not be a reboot, nor will it be a direct sequel to ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a28205256/saw-movie-reboot-timeline-confirmed/ | title = How 'Saw' reboot fits in with the series timeline | first= Dan | last = Seddon | date = July 8, 2019 | accessdate = July 8, 2019 | work = [[Digital Spy]] | publisher = [[Hearst Communications]]}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nOn July 8, 2019, filming commenced in [[Toronto]] under the working title of ''The Organ Donor''. Rock, [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Max Minghella]], and [[Marisol Nichols]] were announced to be starring in the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/samuel-l-jackson-chris-rock-saw-movie-1203260924/ |title=Samuel L. Jackson to Star in Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=July 8, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-movie-filming-start/ |title=New 'Saw' Movie Set To Start Filming This Month |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet, Inc. |first=Q. V. |last=Hough |date=June 27, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Lionsgate\u2019s CEO Joe Drake stated, \"We think Samuel L. Jackson and Chris Rock along with Max Minghella and Marisol Nichols make this film completely special in the ''Saw'' canon and we can't wait to unleash this unexpected and sinister new story on fans of this franchise. This is next level of ''Saw'' on full tilt.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/more-like-saw-muel-l-jackson-right-1836185124?IR=T |title=More Like Saw-muel L. Jackson, Right? |last=Lussier |first=Germain |date=July 9, 2019 |website=[[Gizmodo]] |publisher=[[G/O Media]] |accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref> On August 28, 2019, filming officially wrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3580945/chris-rocks-new-take-saw-wraps-production/ |title=Chris Rock's New Take on 'Saw' Wraps Production |last=Brad |first=Miska |date=August 28, 2019 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref> In February 2020, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] gave the film an R rating, for \"sequences of grisly bloody violence and torture, pervasive language, some sexual references and brief drug use\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.filmratings.com/Search?filmTitle=spiral&x=0&y=0| title=Spiral (2020) | work=The Classification and Rating Adiministration | publisher=[[Motion Picture Association of America]] | accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nThe film was known under the working title ''The Organ Donor''<ref>{{cite web |last=Wilhelmi |first=Jack|title=How Does The 'Saw' Reboot Connect To The Original Movies? |url=https://screenrant.com/how-the-saw-reboot-connects-to-original-movies/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |date=November 24, 2019 |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> until the name ''Spiral: From the Book of Saw'' was leaked to the press on January 22, 2020, along with [[Mongrel Media]] as the Canadian distributor.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burwick|first1=Kevin|title=Bewildering Saw 9 Title Allegedly Leaks, But Is It for Real?|url=https://movieweb.com/saw-9-official-title-spiral/|website=[[MovieWeb]]|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The first teaser poster and trailer, released on February 5, 2020, confirmed ''Spiral'' as the title of the film.<ref name=Patches>{{cite web|last=Patches|first= Matt|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/5/21124064/spiral-trailer-chris-rock-saw-reboot|title=The 'Spiral' trailer is our first cut of Chris Rock's Saw reboot|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate = February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Spiral'' was scheduled to be released on May 15, 2020 in the United States by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/chris-rocks-saw-reboot-release-date-moved-up-may-2020-1226072 |title=Chris Rock's 'Saw' Movie Moved Up to May 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Valence Media]] |last=Galuppo |first=Mia |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref> but was delayed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. Lionsgate intends to announce a new release date \"once there is more clarity on when movie theaters\" will reopen.<ref name=\"Reschedule\" /> It was originally scheduled to be released on October 23, 2020, but was moved up to May 15, 2020, to avoid competition with ''[[Halloween Kills]]'', the sequel to 2018's ''[[Halloween (2018 film)|Halloween]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/chris-rock-saw-reboot-may-2020-1203275353/ |title=Chris Rock's 'Saw' Reboot Moves Up Five Months to May 2020 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.lionsgate.com/movies/spiral}}\n* {{IMDb title|10342730|Spiral}}\n* [http://www.mongrelmedia.com/index.php/filmlink?id=66364d59-dfc5-e911-a98f-0edcbcd33718  ''Spiral''] on [[Mongrel Media]]\n\n{{Chris Rock}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Saw}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spiral (2020 film)}}\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Saw films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming sequel films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilming:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiral_(2020_film)"}
{"title_page": "\u015awiebodzin", "text_new": "{{short description|Town and capital of \u015awiebodzin County, Lubusz Voivodeship, Poland}}\n{{Other places}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = \u015awiebodzin\n| image_skyline = Swiebodzin ratusz 0.jpg\n| image_caption = Town hall of \u015awiebodzin\n| image_flag = POL \u015awiebodzin flag.svg\n| image_shield = POL \u015awiebodzin COA.svg\n| pushpin_map = Poland Lubusz Voivodeship#Poland\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{POL}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{flag|Lubusz Voivodeship|name=Lubusz}}\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Powiat|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[\u015awiebodzin County|\u015awiebodzin]]\n| subdivision_type3 = [[Gmina]]\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Gmina \u015awiebodzin|\u015awiebodzin]]\n| leader_title = Mayor\n| leader_name = Tomasz Sielicki\n| area_total_km2 = 10.54\n| population_as_of = 2019-06-30<ref>{{cite web |title=Population. Size and structure and vital statistics in Poland by territorial divison in 2019. As of 30th June|url=https://stat.gov.pl/en/topics/population/population/population-size-and-structure-and-vital-statistics-in-poland-by-territorial-divison-in-2019-as-of-30th-june,3,26.html|website=stat.gov.pl|publisher=Statistics Poland|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n| population_total = 21736\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| timezone =[[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset = +1\n| timezone_DST = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +2\n| coordinates = {{coord|52|15|N|15|32|E|region:PL|display=inline,title}}\n| postal_code_type = Postal code\n| postal_code = 66-200 to 66-201\n| blank_name = [[Polish car number plates|Car plates]]\n| blank_info = FSW\n| website = {{URL|http://www.swiebodzin.eu}}\n}}\n'''\u015awiebodzin''' {{IPAc-pl|\u015b|f|j|e|'|b|o|d\u017a|i|n}} ({{lang-de|Schwiebus}}) is a [[town]] in western [[Poland]] with 21,736 inhabitants (2019). It is the capital of [[\u015awiebodzin County]]. Since the Local Government Reorganization Act of 1998, \u015awiebodzin has been part of [[Lubusz Voivodeship]]. It was formerly part of the [[Zielona G\u00f3ra Voivodeship]] (1975\u20131998).\n\n\u015awiebodzin is an important transportation hub, lying at the crossroads of the Polish [[National roads in Poland#List of national roads|national roads 2 and 3]]. The [[Autostrada A2 (Poland)|A2 motorway]] and [[Expressway S3 (Poland)|S3 expressway]] cross near the town. \u015awiebodzin is located {{convert|39|km|mi|abbr=on}} northeast of [[Zielona G\u00f3ra]], one of the two voivodeship's capitals, {{convert|195|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Wroc\u0142aw]] and {{convert|110|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of [[Pozna\u0144]]; {{convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the [[Germany|German]] border and {{convert|130|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of [[Berlin]]. The crowned [[Christ the King (\u015awiebodzin)|statue of Christ]] in \u015awiebodzin, completed in November 2010, is one of the world's tallest statues of Jesus.\n\n==History==\n===Middle Ages===\n[[File:\u015awiebodzin, mury miejskie przy ul. Okr\u0119\u017cnej.jpg|thumb|left|Partly preserved medieval town walls]]\nThe town's name derives from the Polish personal name ''\u015awieboda'', related to ''swoboda'' meaning \"freedom\".<ref>[[Kazimierz Rymut|K. Rymut]], ''Nazwy miast Polski'', Ossolineum 1987, s. 242.</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YH_RAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA491&lpg=PA491&dq=%C5%9Bwieboda+slownik&source=bl&ots=z50vFTqbGn&sig=gedIhDT2_uN832mC8Qi9frZ5uQc&hl=en&ei=DQDbTLyzFpCisAOX9NDjBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Linde, Samuel Bogumi\u0142. \"Slownik j\u1eb9zyka polskiego\", Volume 5. 1812 |publisher=Books.google.ca |date= |accessdate=2012-05-16}}</ref> The area was part of Poland since the creation of the state in the 10th century. As a result of the fragmentation of Poland, it initially was part of [[Duchy of Greater Poland|Greater Poland]], and later it was part of [[Duchy of Silesia|Silesia]]. The earliest historical records which mention ''Sebusianis, Sipusius Silesius, Suebosian, Soebosian, Suebusianus'' for today's \u015awiebodzin date from the beginning of the 14th century, when the area belonged to the [[Lower Silesia]]n Polish-ruled [[Duchy of G\u0142og\u00f3w]]. The town sprang up at the intersection of the old trade routes linking Silesia with [[Pomerania]] and a branch of the route running from [[Lusatia]] to [[Pozna\u0144]] in [[Greater Poland]] and further to [[Pomerelia]]. Initially, the town was probably a defensive fortification, built on the western banks of Lake Zamecko at a slight elevation. The town wall was ringed by settlements, which were much later incorporated into the city itself.\n[[File:Silesia map.png|thumb|left|Bohemian Silesia (green) with northern \u015awiebodzin exclave]]\nIn 1319 the [[Margraviate of Brandenburg|Brandenburg]] margrave [[Waldemar, Margrave of Brandenburg-Stendal|Waldemar of Ascania]] conquered \u015awiebodzin and the town of [[Sulech\u00f3w]] to its south. He died in the same year and the territory fell back to the [[Silesian Piasts]], who in 1329 became vassals of [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]], an Electorate of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. When in 1476 Duke [[Henry XI of G\u0142og\u00f3w]] died without issue, fights over his succession broke out between Duke [[Jan II the Mad]] of [[Duchy of \u017baga\u0144|\u017baga\u0144]] and the Brandenburg Elector [[Albrecht III, Elector of Brandenburg|Albert III Achilles of Hohenzollern]], who in ca.1479 was able to acquire the northern part of the duchy with the towns of Crossen ([[Krosno Odrza\u0144skie]]) and Z\u00fcllichau (Sulech\u00f3w), which were incorporated into the [[Neumark]] district of Brandenburg in 1537. The area of \u015awiebodzin however remained a Bohemian fief, becoming an [[Enclave and exclave|exclave]] of the Silesian crown land which in 1526 passed with the Bohemian Kingdom to the [[Habsburg Monarchy]].\n\n===Early modern period===\n[[File:\u015awiebodzin - fotopolska.eu (146819).jpg|thumb|right|Partial view of the town square]]\nBecause of the town's location at an important crossroads, it developed economically, particularly in the areas of commerce and craft production. In the 15th century and particularly in the 16th century, Schwiebus was known for manufacturing beer and exporting cloth. It also developed various urban handicrafts and manufactured goods for local purposes (the weekly market). The salt, wool, grain, horse, and beef trades were also important.\nFor a time the Schwiebus territory was granted by the emperor to [[Brandenburg-Prussia]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?vid=OCLC04519949&id=nduuOHX8Nl8C&pg=RA2-PA299&lpg=RA2-PA299&dq=schwiebus#PRA2-PA296,M1 |title=Complete Works of Thomas Carlyle ... - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=2005-11-08 |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> Representatives of well-known Silesian families, including the von Knobelsdorffs, among others, held authority and power in the town as district [[starost]]s and castle commanders on behalf of the [[Habsburg]]s.\n[[File:Swiebodzin dawny.jpg|thumb|left|17th-century view of the town]]\nBecause of its position near the [[Holy Roman Empire]]'s border with the [[Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth|Kingdom of Poland]], the town most likely had a population of mixed [[Poles|Polish]] and [[Germans|German]] descent at this time, but Germans were the majority by the [[early modern period]]. During the 16th and the first half of the 17th centuries, the town expanded economically, spatially, and demographically, in spite of local conflicts and the turbulent [[Protestant Reformation]] and [[Counter-Reformation]].\n\nAfter the victory of King [[Frederick II of Prussia]] in the [[Silesian Wars|First Silesian War]] (1740\u20131742), Schwiebus came under [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] administration. In 1817 its territory was merged with the southern Z\u00fcllichau region to form the Z\u00fcllichau-Schwiebus District in the [[Province of Brandenburg]]. Schwiebus remained in this territorial form until 1945. Annexation by Prussia brought about a sharp economic crisis, as the tradesmen of Schwiebus were cut off from many of their traditional markets and outlets. The Prussian authorities also increased local taxes while limiting the town's autonomy. The period of revolutions and [[Napoleonic wars]] brought about a depression in the cloth trade and limited the economic prospects of the town.\n\nThe town's extended stagnation ended with the [[Heinrich Friedrich Karl Reichsfreiherr vom und zum Stein|Stein]]-[[Karl August von Hardenberg|Hardenberg]] economic reforms and the beginning of the [[industrial revolution]] in the mid-19th century. As a medium-sized town and hub of the local market, lying at the intersection of several routes of communication, including the new [[Frankfurt (Oder)]]-[[Pozna\u0144]] railway line, Schwiebus became a center of local industry (textile, machinery, and agricultural food processing). The town was modernized at this time with improved traffic arteries, renovation of the town hall, reconstruction of the church of St. Michael, and the construction of several new public service buildings (law courts, high school, gas works, and post office). Schwiebus contributed to and benefited from the economic expansion of the [[German Empire]] in the years before 1914.\n\n===20th century===\n{{multiple image|align = right|perrow = 2|total_width=350\n| image1 = \u015awiebodzin, ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 par. pw \u015bw. Micha\u0142a Archanio\u0142a.JPG\n| image2 = \u015awiebodzin, ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 MB Kr\u00f3lowej Polski (05).jpg\n| footer = Historic churches of \u015awiebodzin: Saint Michael Archangel church (on the left), Our Lady Queen of Poland church (on the right)\n}}\nA new period of economic stagnation began with the territorial changes in central Europe after Germany's defeat in [[World War I]]. In the [[interwar period]], Schwiebus found itself in the eastern outskirts of Germany, twenty kilometers west of the newly imposed German-Polish border. During the 1920s, [[Weimar Republic|Weimar Germany]] experienced two major economic crises, the [[hyperinflation]] of the early 1920s and the [[Great Depression]] beginning in 1929. The citizens of Schwiebus suffered severe economic hardship during this time. As was the case elsewhere in Germany, many of the town's citizens were dissatisfied with their lot and turned to political extremism.\n\n[[Adolf Hitler]] of the [[Nazi Party]] came to power in Germany in 1933. Hitler quickly moved to consolidate and expand his power, adopting severe repressive measures against his political opposition and the German [[Jew]]ish minority. However, Hitler remained popular with the public because he oversaw the German economic recovery of the 1930s. The new government sponsored many public works programs and a massive rearmament campaign which included the construction of an extensive fortified line of bunkers, ''Ostwall'' (today known as the [[Mi\u0119dzyrzecz Fortified Region]]) twenty kilometers north of Schwiebus.\n\n[[World War II]] (1939\u201345) first brought hardship to Schwiebus and then total disaster. In early January 1945, the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]] began its final advance through Poland into eastern Germany, reaching Schwiebus before the end of the month. By this time, many of its inhabitants had already fled, fearing the Soviet revenge for the atrocities perpetrated by the German occupation forces against the civilian population of the Soviet Union. The town was largely spared from destruction during the fighting, as the bulk of the Soviet forces passed to the north and south on their way to [[Battle of Berlin|Berlin]]. It was finally captured in 31 January 1945. The capture was not without casualties.<ref>http://opty.info/nasze-forum/wspomnienia/tragiczne-losy-siostr-boromeuszek-za-swiebodzina/</ref>\n\nAfter Germany's defeat in the war, Schwiebus became \u015awiebodzin, and was once again part of Poland.\n\nThe new Polish government adopted the [[communism|communist economic system]] and enacted sweeping social, economic, and political reforms.  \u015awiebodzin's economic recovery was also hampered by the Soviet policy of dismantling industrial facilities in conquered areas, and shipping components back to the Soviet Union. In this way, \u015awiebodzin lost some of its prewar industries, particularly its breweries.\n\n\u015awiebodzin expanded in the period under communist rule, and its population doubled. New neighborhoods were built to the south of the railway line, composed largely of [[Plattenbau|pre-fabricated apartment buildings]]. The Communist Economic Planning Commissions chose to develop the electromechanical, furniture, and timber industries in \u015awiebodzin. Products were exported throughout Poland and to the other states in the [[Soviet Bloc]].\n\nHowever, with the collapse of the Soviet Bloc and the [[revolutions of 1989]], \u015awiebodzin once again experienced economic upheaval. With some difficulties, the local economy was adapted to the international [[market economy]]. New industries and businesses were established, but others were unable to compete in the new environment and went bankrupt. Many more goods became available in local shops, but at prices that many inhabitants could not afford. In recent years, a few foreign-owned discount supermarkets, pizzerias, hotels, and other businesses have been established in the town, taking advantage of the proximity of Poland's main east-west motorway. With the economic changes there have also been political changes. A series of non-communist local governments have been elected since 1989.\n\n==Attractions and sites of interest==\n[[File:Swiebodzin (9662661400).jpg|thumb|left|[[Facade]]s at the market square]]\n[[File:Christ the King Statue \u015awiebodzin 05.jpg|thumb|190px|Statue of ''[[Christ the King (\u015awiebodzin)|Christ the King]]'']]\nThe center of \u015awiebodzin still contains remnants of the town's past as a [[medieval]] walled settlement, including two nearly intact towers and fragments of the town\u2019s [[defensive walls]] and [[bastion]]s. The central [[market square]] is dominated by the [[town hall]], built around 1550 in the [[renaissance architecture|renaissance]] style and rebuilt in the 19th century with the addition of its prominent [[clock tower]]. The town hall still contains its original [[gothic architecture|gothic]] [[vault (architecture)|vaults]] in the rooms of the Regional Museum and basement cafe. There are two large churches in the town center, the Church of St. Michael the Archangel and the Church of the Mother of God. The Church of St. Michael was first built in the second half of the 15th Century, and its [[gothic revival architecture|neo-gothic]] [[fa\u00e7ade]] was added in the second half of the 19th century. The neo-gothic Church of the Mother of God was built during the [[Imperial Germany|Imperial German]] period as a [[Protestant Church]] but was reconsecrated as a [[Catholic Church]] after World War II.\n\nIn the summer of 2008, assembly of the ''[[Christ the King (\u015awiebodzin)|Christ the King]]'', a giant statue of a crowned [[Jesus Christ]], began on a hill on the outskirts of the town. Intended to serve as a future site of pilgrimage, the statue was completed in November 2010, and is claimed to be the world's largest statue of Jesus,<ref name=completed>{{cite news | url = https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jl4gAKRLm6GA5JHGsu19b4VCAW7Q?docId=145283da4231446ea852f4ca5f562a41 | title = Giant Jesus statue completed in Polish town | last =  | first = |date = November 6, 2010 | agency = Associated Press| publisher = Google | accessdate =  November 7, 2010}}</ref> although if the crown is excluded the ''[[Cristo de la Concordia]]'' in Bolivia is still taller. Construction was funded by donations from local people and as far away as [[Canada]].<ref name=completed/> The existence of the statue has seen fellow Poles referring to the town jokingly as ''Rio de \u015awiebodzineiro''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oleksiak|first1=Wojciech|title=Polandball - A Case Study|url=http://culture.pl/en/article/polandball-a-case-study|accessdate=6 August 2014|work=Culture.pl|publisher=[[Adam Mickiewicz Institute]]|date=9 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810074510/http://culture.pl/en/article/polandball-a-case-study|archivedate=10 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n\u015awiebodzin has a table tennis club KS Jofrakuda \u015awiebodzin which is playing in 3.liga (Polish third division). The club has also the other teams playing in lower divisions of [[Lubusz Voivodeship|Lubusz]]. The club is known from a successful work with young table tennis players, who are highly ranked in Polish youth categories.\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Laweczka Czes\u0142aw Niemen \u015awiebodzin.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Czes\u0142aw Niemen]]'s monument on the Market Square]]\n*[[Martin Agricola]] (1486\u20131556), composer\n*[[Ruth Margarete Roellig]] (1878\u20131969), writer\n*Otto Feige ([[B. Traven]]) (ca. 1882 \u2013 ca. 1969), writer of ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]''\n*[[Werner Kolh\u00f6rster]] (1887\u20131946), physicist\n*[[Walter Warzecha]] (1891\u20131956), admiral and last commander of the [[Kriegsmarine]]\n*{{ill|Alfred Knispel|de}} (1898\u20131945), artist\n*[[Karl-Heinz Bendert]] (1914\u20131983), [[Luftwaffe]] ace  \n*[[Wolfhart Westendorf]] (1924\u20132018), egyptologist\n*[[Michael Witzel]] (born 1943), [[Wales Professor of Sanskrit]] at Harvard University\n*[[Zdzis\u0142aw Hoffmann]]  (born 1959), first ever triple jump World Champion (1983)\n*[[Piotr Rysiukiewicz]] (born 1974), sprinter\n[[File:Swiebodzin szkola po renowacji.jpg|thumb|Former parish school]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\nSee [[Gmina \u015awiebodzin#Twin towns \u2013 sister cities|twin towns of Gmina \u015awiebodzin]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.swiebodzin.eu/ Official website] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.schwiebus.pl/ Historical artifacts from \u015awiebodzin/Schwiebus] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.swiebodzin.com/ Regionalny Portal Informacyjny] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.sztetl.org.pl/en/city/swiebodzin/ Jewish Community in \u015awiebodzin] on Virtual Shtetl\n*[http://www.gazeta.swiebodzin.pl/ GAZETA \u015awiebodzi\u0144ska] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.gazeta-lokalna.pl/ Gazeta Lokalna. Dwutygodnik Powiatu \u015awiebodzi\u0144skiego]\n*[http://www.jofrakuda.cba.pl/ Oficjalna strona KS Jofrakudy \u015awiebodzin / Official website of the table-tennis club KS Jofrakuda] {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{\u015awiebodzin County}}\n{{Gmina \u015awiebodzin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swiebodzin}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Lubusz Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:\u015awiebodzin County]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Town and capital of \u015awiebodzin County, Lubusz Voivodeship, Poland}}\n{{Other places}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = \u015awiebodzin\n| image_skyline = Swiebodzin ratusz 0.jpg\n| image_caption = Town hall of \u015awiebodzin\n| image_flag = POL \u015awiebodzin flag.svg\n| image_shield = POL \u015awiebodzin COA.svg\n| pushpin_map = Poland Lubusz Voivodeship#Poland\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{POL}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{flag|Lubusz Voivodeship|name=Lubusz}}\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Powiat|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[\u015awiebodzin County]]\n| subdivision_type3 = [[Gmina]]\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Gmina \u015awiebodzin]]\n| leader_title = Mayor\n| leader_name = Tomasz Sielicki\n| area_total_km2 = 10.54\n| population_as_of = 2019-06-30<ref>{{cite web |title=Population. Size and structure and vital statistics in Poland by territorial divison in 2019. As of 30th June|url=https://stat.gov.pl/en/topics/population/population/population-size-and-structure-and-vital-statistics-in-poland-by-territorial-divison-in-2019-as-of-30th-june,3,26.html|website=stat.gov.pl|publisher=Statistics Poland|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n| population_total = 21736\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| timezone =[[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset = +1\n| timezone_DST = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +2\n| coordinates = {{coord|52|15|N|15|32|E|region:PL|display=inline,title}}\n| postal_code_type = Postal code\n| postal_code = 66-200 to 66-201\n| blank_name = [[Polish car number plates|Car plates]]\n| blank_info = FSW\n| website = {{URL|http://www.swiebodzin.eu}}\n}}\n'''\u015awiebodzin''' {{IPAc-pl|\u015b|f|j|e|'|b|o|d\u017a|i|n}} ({{lang-de|Schwiebus}}) is a [[town]] in western [[Poland]] with 21,736 inhabitants (2019). It is the capital of [[\u015awiebodzin County]]. Since the Local Government Reorganization Act of 1998, \u015awiebodzin has been part of [[Lubusz Voivodeship]]. It was formerly part of the [[Zielona G\u00f3ra Voivodeship]] (1975\u20131998).\n\n\u015awiebodzin is an important transportation hub, lying at the crossroads of the Polish [[National roads in Poland#List of national roads|national roads 2 and 3]]. The [[Autostrada A2 (Poland)|A2 motorway]] and [[Expressway S3 (Poland)|S3 expressway]] cross near the town. \u015awiebodzin is located {{convert|39|km|mi|abbr=on}} northeast of [[Zielona G\u00f3ra]], one of the two voivodeship's capitals, {{convert|195|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Wroc\u0142aw]] and {{convert|110|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of [[Pozna\u0144]]; {{convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the [[Germany|German]] border and {{convert|130|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of [[Berlin]]. The crowned [[Christ the King (\u015awiebodzin)|statue of Christ]] in \u015awiebodzin, completed in November 2010, is one of the world's tallest statues of Jesus.\n\n==History==\n===Middle Ages===\n[[File:\u015awiebodzin, mury miejskie przy ul. Okr\u0119\u017cnej.jpg|thumb|left|Partly preserved medieval town walls]]\nThe town's name derives from the Polish personal name ''\u015awieboda'', related to ''swoboda'' meaning \"freedom\".<ref>[[Kazimierz Rymut|K. Rymut]], ''Nazwy miast Polski'', Ossolineum 1987, s. 242.</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YH_RAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA491&lpg=PA491&dq=%C5%9Bwieboda+slownik&source=bl&ots=z50vFTqbGn&sig=gedIhDT2_uN832mC8Qi9frZ5uQc&hl=en&ei=DQDbTLyzFpCisAOX9NDjBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Linde, Samuel Bogumi\u0142. \"Slownik j\u1eb9zyka polskiego\", Volume 5. 1812 |publisher=Books.google.ca |date= |accessdate=2012-05-16}}</ref> The area was part of Poland since the creation of the state in the 10th century. As a result of the fragmentation of Poland, it initially was part of [[Duchy of Greater Poland|Greater Poland]], and later it was part of [[Duchy of Silesia|Silesia]]. The earliest historical records which mention ''Sebusianis, Sipusius Silesius, Suebosian, Soebosian, Suebusianus'' for today's \u015awiebodzin date from the beginning of the 14th century, when the area belonged to the [[Lower Silesia]]n Polish-ruled [[Duchy of G\u0142og\u00f3w]]. The town sprang up at the intersection of the old trade routes linking Silesia with [[Pomerania]] and a branch of the route running from [[Lusatia]] to [[Pozna\u0144]] in [[Greater Poland]] and further to [[Pomerelia]]. Initially, the town was probably a defensive fortification, built on the western banks of Lake Zamecko at a slight elevation. The town wall was ringed by settlements, which were much later incorporated into the city itself.\n[[File:Silesia map.png|thumb|left|Bohemian Silesia (green) with northern \u015awiebodzin exclave]]\nIn 1319 the [[Margraviate of Brandenburg|Brandenburg]] margrave [[Waldemar, Margrave of Brandenburg-Stendal|Waldemar of Ascania]] conquered \u015awiebodzin and the town of [[Sulech\u00f3w]] to its south. He died in the same year and the territory fell back to the [[Silesian Piasts]], who in 1329 became vassals of [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]], an Electorate of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. When in 1476 Duke [[Henry XI of G\u0142og\u00f3w]] died without issue, fights over his succession broke out between Duke [[Jan II the Mad]] of [[Duchy of \u017baga\u0144|\u017baga\u0144]] and the Brandenburg Elector [[Albrecht III, Elector of Brandenburg|Albert III Achilles of Hohenzollern]], who in ca.1479 was able to acquire the northern part of the duchy with the towns of Crossen ([[Krosno Odrza\u0144skie]]) and Z\u00fcllichau (Sulech\u00f3w), which were incorporated into the [[Neumark]] district of Brandenburg in 1537. The area of \u015awiebodzin however remained a Bohemian fief, becoming an [[Enclave and exclave|exclave]] of the Silesian crown land which in 1526 passed with the Bohemian Kingdom to the [[Habsburg Monarchy]].\n\n===Early modern period===\n[[File:\u015awiebodzin - fotopolska.eu (146819).jpg|thumb|right|Partial view of the town square]]\nBecause of the town's location at an important crossroads, it developed economically, particularly in the areas of commerce and craft production. In the 15th century and particularly in the 16th century, Schwiebus was known for manufacturing beer and exporting cloth. It also developed various urban handicrafts and manufactured goods for local purposes (the weekly market). The salt, wool, grain, horse, and beef trades were also important.\nFor a time the Schwiebus territory was granted by the emperor to [[Brandenburg-Prussia]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?vid=OCLC04519949&id=nduuOHX8Nl8C&pg=RA2-PA299&lpg=RA2-PA299&dq=schwiebus#PRA2-PA296,M1 |title=Complete Works of Thomas Carlyle ... - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=2005-11-08 |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> Representatives of well-known Silesian families, including the von Knobelsdorffs, among others, held authority and power in the town as district [[starost]]s and castle commanders on behalf of the [[Habsburg]]s.\n[[File:Swiebodzin dawny.jpg|thumb|left|17th-century view of the town]]\nBecause of its position near the [[Holy Roman Empire]]'s border with the [[Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth|Kingdom of Poland]], the town most likely had a population of mixed [[Poles|Polish]] and [[Germans|German]] descent at this time, but Germans were the majority by the [[early modern period]]. During the 16th and the first half of the 17th centuries, the town expanded economically, spatially, and demographically, in spite of local conflicts and the turbulent [[Protestant Reformation]] and [[Counter-Reformation]].\n\nAfter the victory of King [[Frederick II of Prussia]] in the [[Silesian Wars|First Silesian War]] (1740\u20131742), Schwiebus came under [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] administration. In 1817 its territory was merged with the southern Z\u00fcllichau region to form the Z\u00fcllichau-Schwiebus District in the [[Province of Brandenburg]]. Schwiebus remained in this territorial form until 1945. Annexation by Prussia brought about a sharp economic crisis, as the tradesmen of Schwiebus were cut off from many of their traditional markets and outlets. The Prussian authorities also increased local taxes while limiting the town's autonomy. The period of revolutions and [[Napoleonic wars]] brought about a depression in the cloth trade and limited the economic prospects of the town.\n\nThe town's extended stagnation ended with the [[Heinrich Friedrich Karl Reichsfreiherr vom und zum Stein|Stein]]-[[Karl August von Hardenberg|Hardenberg]] economic reforms and the beginning of the [[industrial revolution]] in the mid-19th century. As a medium-sized town and hub of the local market, lying at the intersection of several routes of communication, including the new [[Frankfurt (Oder)]]-[[Pozna\u0144]] railway line, Schwiebus became a center of local industry (textile, machinery, and agricultural food processing). The town was modernized at this time with improved traffic arteries, renovation of the town hall, reconstruction of the church of St. Michael, and the construction of several new public service buildings (law courts, high school, gas works, and post office). Schwiebus contributed to and benefited from the economic expansion of the [[German Empire]] in the years before 1914.\n\n===20th century===\n{{multiple image|align = right|perrow = 2|total_width=350\n| image1 = \u015awiebodzin, ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 par. pw \u015bw. Micha\u0142a Archanio\u0142a.JPG\n| image2 = \u015awiebodzin, ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 MB Kr\u00f3lowej Polski (05).jpg\n| footer = Historic churches of \u015awiebodzin: Saint Michael Archangel church (on the left), Our Lady Queen of Poland church (on the right)\n}}\nA new period of economic stagnation began with the territorial changes in central Europe after Germany's defeat in [[World War I]]. In the [[interwar period]], Schwiebus found itself in the eastern outskirts of Germany, twenty kilometers west of the newly imposed German-Polish border. During the 1920s, [[Weimar Republic|Weimar Germany]] experienced two major economic crises, the [[hyperinflation]] of the early 1920s and the [[Great Depression]] beginning in 1929. The citizens of Schwiebus suffered severe economic hardship during this time. As was the case elsewhere in Germany, many of the town's citizens were dissatisfied with their lot and turned to political extremism.\n\n[[Adolf Hitler]] of the [[Nazi Party]] came to power in Germany in 1933. Hitler quickly moved to consolidate and expand his power, adopting severe repressive measures against his political opposition and the German [[Jew]]ish minority. However, Hitler remained popular with the public because he oversaw the German economic recovery of the 1930s. The new government sponsored many public works programs and a massive rearmament campaign which included the construction of an extensive fortified line of bunkers, ''Ostwall'' (today known as the [[Mi\u0119dzyrzecz Fortified Region]]) twenty kilometers north of Schwiebus.\n\n[[World War II]] (1939\u201345) first brought hardship to Schwiebus and then total disaster. In early January 1945, the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]] began its final advance through Poland into eastern Germany, reaching Schwiebus before the end of the month. By this time, many of its inhabitants had already fled, fearing the Soviet revenge for the atrocities perpetrated by the German occupation forces against the civilian population of the Soviet Union. The town was largely spared from destruction during the fighting, as the bulk of the Soviet forces passed to the north and south on their way to [[Battle of Berlin|Berlin]]. It was finally captured in 31 January 1945. The capture was not without casualties.<ref>http://opty.info/nasze-forum/wspomnienia/tragiczne-losy-siostr-boromeuszek-za-swiebodzina/</ref>\n\nAfter Germany's defeat in the war, Schwiebus became \u015awiebodzin, and was once again part of Poland.\n\nThe new Polish government adopted the [[communism|communist economic system]] and enacted sweeping social, economic, and political reforms.  \u015awiebodzin's economic recovery was also hampered by the Soviet policy of dismantling industrial facilities in conquered areas, and shipping components back to the Soviet Union. In this way, \u015awiebodzin lost some of its prewar industries, particularly its breweries.\n\n\u015awiebodzin expanded in the period under communist rule, and its population doubled. New neighborhoods were built to the south of the railway line, composed largely of [[Plattenbau|pre-fabricated apartment buildings]]. The Communist Economic Planning Commissions chose to develop the electromechanical, furniture, and timber industries in \u015awiebodzin. Products were exported throughout Poland and to the other states in the [[Soviet Bloc]].\n\nHowever, with the collapse of the Soviet Bloc and the [[revolutions of 1989]], \u015awiebodzin once again experienced economic upheaval. With some difficulties, the local economy was adapted to the international [[market economy]]. New industries and businesses were established, but others were unable to compete in the new environment and went bankrupt. Many more goods became available in local shops, but at prices that many inhabitants could not afford. In recent years, a few foreign-owned discount supermarkets, pizzerias, hotels, and other businesses have been established in the town, taking advantage of the proximity of Poland's main east-west motorway. With the economic changes there have also been political changes. A series of non-communist local governments have been elected since 1989.\n\n==Attractions and sites of interest==\n[[File:Swiebodzin (9662661400).jpg|thumb|left|[[Facade]]s at the market square]]\n[[File:Christ the King Statue \u015awiebodzin 05.jpg|thumb|190px|Statue of ''[[Christ the King (\u015awiebodzin)|Christ the King]]'']]\nThe center of \u015awiebodzin still contains remnants of the town's past as a [[medieval]] walled settlement, including two nearly intact towers and fragments of the town\u2019s [[defensive walls]] and [[bastion]]s. The central [[market square]] is dominated by the [[town hall]], built around 1550 in the [[renaissance architecture|renaissance]] style and rebuilt in the 19th century with the addition of its prominent [[clock tower]]. The town hall still contains its original [[gothic architecture|gothic]] [[vault (architecture)|vaults]] in the rooms of the Regional Museum and basement cafe. There are two large churches in the town center, the Church of St. Michael the Archangel and the Church of the Mother of God. The Church of St. Michael was first built in the second half of the 15th Century, and its [[gothic revival architecture|neo-gothic]] [[fa\u00e7ade]] was added in the second half of the 19th century. The neo-gothic Church of the Mother of God was built during the [[Imperial Germany|Imperial German]] period as a [[Protestant Church]] but was reconsecrated as a [[Catholic Church]] after World War II.\n\nIn the summer of 2008, assembly of the ''[[Christ the King (\u015awiebodzin)|Christ the King]]'', a giant statue of a crowned [[Jesus Christ]], began on a hill on the outskirts of the town. Intended to serve as a future site of pilgrimage, the statue was completed in November 2010, and is claimed to be the world's largest statue of Jesus,<ref name=completed>{{cite news | url = https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jl4gAKRLm6GA5JHGsu19b4VCAW7Q?docId=145283da4231446ea852f4ca5f562a41 | title = Giant Jesus statue completed in Polish town | last =  | first = |date = November 6, 2010 | agency = Associated Press| publisher = Google | accessdate =  November 7, 2010}}</ref> although if the crown is excluded the ''[[Cristo de la Concordia]]'' in Bolivia is still taller. Construction was funded by donations from local people and as far away as [[Canada]].<ref name=completed/> The existence of the statue has seen fellow Poles referring to the town jokingly as ''Rio de \u015awiebodzineiro''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oleksiak|first1=Wojciech|title=Polandball - A Case Study|url=http://culture.pl/en/article/polandball-a-case-study|accessdate=6 August 2014|work=Culture.pl|publisher=[[Adam Mickiewicz Institute]]|date=9 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810074510/http://culture.pl/en/article/polandball-a-case-study|archivedate=10 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n\u015awiebodzin has a table tennis club KS Jofrakuda \u015awiebodzin which is playing in 3.liga (Polish third division). The club has also the other teams playing in lower divisions of [[Lubusz Voivodeship|Lubusz]]. The club is known from a successful work with young table tennis players, who are highly ranked in Polish youth categories.\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Laweczka Czes\u0142aw Niemen \u015awiebodzin.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Czes\u0142aw Niemen]]'s monument on the Market Square]]\n*[[Martin Agricola]] (1486\u20131556), composer\n*[[Ruth Margarete Roellig]] (1878\u20131969), writer\n*Otto Feige ([[B. Traven]]) (ca. 1882 \u2013 ca. 1969), writer of ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]''\n*[[Werner Kolh\u00f6rster]] (1887\u20131946), physicist\n*[[Walter Warzecha]] (1891\u20131956), admiral and last commander of the [[Kriegsmarine]]\n*{{ill|Alfred Knispel|de}} (1898\u20131945), artist\n*[[Karl-Heinz Bendert]] (1914\u20131983), [[Luftwaffe]] ace  \n*[[Wolfhart Westendorf]] (1924\u20132018), egyptologist\n*[[Michael Witzel]] (born 1943), [[Wales Professor of Sanskrit]] at Harvard University\n*[[Zdzis\u0142aw Hoffmann]]  (born 1959), first ever triple jump World Champion (1983)\n*[[Piotr Rysiukiewicz]] (born 1974), sprinter\n[[File:Swiebodzin szkola po renowacji.jpg|thumb|Former parish school]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\nSee [[Gmina \u015awiebodzin#Twin towns \u2013 sister cities|twin towns of Gmina \u015awiebodzin]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.swiebodzin.eu/ Official website] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.schwiebus.pl/ Historical artifacts from \u015awiebodzin/Schwiebus] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.swiebodzin.com/ Regionalny Portal Informacyjny] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.sztetl.org.pl/en/city/swiebodzin/ Jewish Community in \u015awiebodzin] on Virtual Shtetl\n*[http://www.gazeta.swiebodzin.pl/ GAZETA \u015awiebodzi\u0144ska] {{in lang|pl}}\n*[http://www.gazeta-lokalna.pl/ Gazeta Lokalna. Dwutygodnik Powiatu \u015awiebodzi\u0144skiego]\n*[http://www.jofrakuda.cba.pl/ Oficjalna strona KS Jofrakudy \u015awiebodzin / Official website of the table-tennis club KS Jofrakuda] {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{\u015awiebodzin County}}\n{{Gmina \u015awiebodzin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swiebodzin}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Lubusz Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:\u015awiebodzin County]]\